d a lodge \u2014 home to William Chin, the butler, and his family. Other buildings included a stable, a root house, a tool house and a drive shed. Later in the century, cottages for married servants were also erected.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.torontopubliclibrary.ca/detail.jsp?Entt=RDMDC-PICTURES-R-246&R=DC-PICTURES-R-246 The Grange, 1909, from the Toronto Public Gallery]\n*[http://www.ago.net/grange Art Gallery of Ontario: The Grange]\n\n{{NHSC}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grange}}\n[[Category:Houses in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Museums in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Historic house museums in Ontario]]\n[[Category:National Historic Sites in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Georgian architecture in Canada]]\n[[Category:Art Gallery of Ontario]]\n[[Category:Designated heritage properties in Ontario]]\n", "name_user": "Blairall", "label": "safe", "comment": "small fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Grange_(Toronto)"}
{"title_page": "Albany, New Zealand", "text_new": "{{for|the electorate|Albany (New Zealand electorate)}}{{for|other places named Albany|Albany}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=August 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2011}}\n{{Infobox New Zealand suburbs\n| name           = Albany\n| image          = Albany North Shore Possible Bulk.jpg\n| caption1       = A drawing (looking from the northwest) of how the Albany Town Centre could theoretically be built up if all development were carried out to the maximum allowed around 2006\n| city1          = [[Auckland Council]]\n| city2          =\n| ward           = [[Albany ward (local government)|Albany]]\n| established    = \n| coordinates    = {{coord|36|43|S|174|42|E|region:NZ_type:city_scale:100000|display=it}}\n| area           =\n| population     = 3,057\n| popdate        = 2013\n| trainstations  =\n| ferryterminals =\n| airports       =\n| hospitals      =\n| north          = [[Albany Heights]]\n| northeast      = \n| east           = [[Pinehill, New Zealand|Pinehill]]\n| southeast      = [[Rosedale, Auckland|Rosedale]]\n| south          = [[Brookfield, New Zealand|Brookfield]]\n| southwest      = [[The Landing, New Zealand|The Landing]]\n| west           = \n| northwest      = [[Albany North]]\n| map            = NZ-Albany.png\n| caption2       = Location of Albany in Auckland.\n}}\n\n'''Albany''' is one of the northernmost suburbs of the contiguous [[Auckland]] metropolitan area in New Zealand. It is located to the north of the [[Waitemat\u0101 Harbour]], \n\n{{Convert|15|km|mi}} northwest of the Auckland city centre. The suburb is in the Albany ward, one of the thirteen administrative divisions of [[Auckland Council]].  One of the city's newest suburbs, it was until relatively recently a town in its own right, and still has a feeling of not being truly a part of the city, which lies predominantly to the southeast of it. Much of the land to the north of Albany is still semi-rural.\n\nThe [[M\u0101ori language|M\u0101ori]] name for the area was Okahukura (literally, 'place of rainbows' or 'place of butterflies'). The town was originally known as Lucas Creek. By 1890 it was a fruit-growing area and in that year it was renamed 'Albany' after the fruit-growing district called [[Albany, Western Australia|'Albany' in Australia]], pronounced with a short 'a' as in ''Albert''.<ref>{{cite journal\n| title = Edge city\n| journal= New Zealand Geographic\n| issue= 37 \n| publisher = \n| date = 1998\n| url = https://www.nzgeo.com/stories/edge-city/\n| accessdate = 17 August 2017\n| first=Liz\n| last=Mahoney\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=History books offer 'definite' guidance on pronunciation of Albany |first=Amy |last=Baker |url= https://www.stuff.co.nz/the-press/national/95706530/History-books-offer-definite-guidance-on-pronunciation-of-Albany |newspaper=Stuff |date=22 August 2017 |accessdate=24 August 2017}}</ref> The name ''Albany'' derives from ''[[Alba]]'' (Gaelic for Scotland) and its Latinisation.\n\n==City planning==\nIn 2005, there were plans to turn a major swath of Albany into a planned mini-urban centre, described as a \"happy mix of businesses, hotels, shops, apartments, and entertainment (including) an environment of parks and lakes and of tree-lined streets, paths and cycleways linking to the new [[Albany Busway Station|park-and-ride bus station]] and the [[Northern Busway, Auckland|rapid-busway lanes]] along the Northern Motorway to downtown Auckland\", according to a newspaper report.<ref name=twsSEPxvx37>{{cite news\n| author = Wayne Thompson\n| title = Albany blueprint gets green light\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 25 Oct 2005\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/commercial-construction/news/article.cfm?c_id=693&objectid=10351837\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n}}</ref> It would be home to 10,000 people.<ref name=twsSEPxvx37/> Authorities wanted sound-proofed apartments against outside noise.<ref name=twsSEPxvx37/> Initial plans called for hotels, library, municipal swimming pool as well as the headquarters for the North Shore City Council.<ref name=twsSEPxvx37/> In some respects, development has proceeded accordingly, but the 2008\u201309 economic downturn has blunted some of this activity.\n\n===Demographics===\nThe population was 3,057 in the 2013 Census, an increase of 888 from the 2006 Census.<ref name=twsSEPxvx01>{{NZ Quickstats2013|13255|Albany}}</ref> There were 1,092 occupied dwellings in Albany in 2013,<ref name=twsSEPxvx01 /> and demographic makeup was 73% European, 5% Maori, 2% Pacific peoples, 22% Asian, 3% Middle Eastern/Latin American/African, and 1% other.<ref name=twsSEPxvx01/> The median income of $32,600 was higher than for the Auckland Region of $29,600.<ref name=twsSEPxvx01/> Unemployment in Albany was 7.0%, lower than the Auckland average of 8.1%.<ref name=twsSEPxvx01/> 91% had internet access and 88% had cell phones.<ref name=twsSEPxvx01/> Cars were prevalent.<ref name=twsSEPxvx01/> A near majority (48%) were born overseas.<ref name=twsSEPxvx01/> Ethnically, in keeping with the wider North Shore, Albany was predominantly [[Pakeha]] and Asian, and had a relatively high proportion of recent migrants from both elsewhere in New Zealand and overseas.\n\n===Retail and commercial activity===\nAlbany has become, in some respects, a substantial shopping and retail zone within the northwestern Auckland area.\n\nThe area (the future 'Albany Town Centre') is fast-growing in terms of its population and the development of the built environment, following planning decisions and land sales made by central and local governments in the 1980s and 1990s. Through the 1990s industrial and retail areas were rapidly produced, predominantly owned and occupied by local and foreign corporate capital. A major [[Shopping mall|shopping centre]] hub was opened in the late 1990s and has since expanded, with [[Westfield Albany]] becoming New Zealand's largest shopping centre. The so-called supermall opened in August 2007 on McKinnon Drive costing $210 million with 142 shops built by over 3500 workers, which features 1800 cinema seats and an indoor area of 7ha.<ref name=twsSEPxvx18/> There is parking for 2300 vehicles.<ref name=twsSEPxvx18/> [[Kmart Australia|Kmart]], [[Farmers Trading Company | Farmers]], and [[New World (supermarket)|New World]] stores are anchors.<ref name=twsSEPxvx18>{{cite news\n| author = Anne Gibson\n| title = Countdown under way for Albany supermall rollout\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 23 Aug 2007\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/shopping/news/article.cfm?c_id=318&objectid=10459307\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n}}</ref> The mall claimed it provides \"free space for community organisations for awareness and fundraising activities\" but one volunteer claimed he was ejected from the premises while trying to raise money for veterans because of a dispute with mall management.<ref name=twsSEPxvx24>{{cite news\n| author = \n| title = Poppy Appeal clash at Albany mall\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 22 Apr 2008\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/yvonne-tahana/news/article.cfm?a_id=345&objectid=10505463\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n| first=Yvonne\n| last=Tahana\n}}</ref>\n\nThere has been development of a substantial retail project anchored by a 10,000 square metre Mega Mitre 10 store on Oteha Valley Road, across from the North Harbour Stadium, run by Symphony Projects Management.<ref name=twsSEPxvx44>{{cite news\n| author = \n| title = DIY centre to join Albany retail scene\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 10 Oct 2007\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/ing-property-trust/news/article.cfm?o_id=87&objectid=10468910\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n| first=Anne\n| last=Gibson\n}}</ref>\n\nAlbany has been the site of a $500 million so-called ''Super City'' showcase development project. Plans in 2006 featured a 200-room hotel, apartment complex with three 30-storey towers, and up to 15 office blocks rising 10 levels high.<ref name=twsSEPxvx13>{{cite news\n| author = \n| title = Albany to grow into city in own right\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 17 Nov 2006\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10411174\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n| first=Anne\n| last=Gibson\n}}</ref> But in the economic downturn of 2008\u201309, the project was in dire straits; one report suggested up to 350 investors (many elderly) risked losing up to $20 million.<ref name=twsSEPxvx06>{{cite news\n| author = \n| title = Investors risk losing $20m on Albany project\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 9 Jun 2009\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/albany/news/article.cfm?l_id=380&objectid=10577259\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n| first=Anne\n| last=Gibson\n}}</ref>\n\nAlbany has a site for [[Sky Television (New Zealand)|Sky Television]]'s [[Prime (New Zealand TV channel)|Prime TV]], as well as the Broadcast Centre for Sky PPV.\n\nThere are movie theatres<ref name=twsSEPxvx03>{{cite news|title=Cinema |publisher=New Zealand Herald |date=2009-09-15 |url=http://movies.nzherald.co.nz/cinema/view/sm7v3/ |accessdate=2009-09-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100525003856/http://movies.nzherald.co.nz/cinema/view/sm7v3/ |archivedate=25 May 2010 }}</ref> including the 1800-seat multiplex inside the new mall, although there were reports of roof problems and weathertightness.<ref name=twsSEPxvx15>{{cite news\n| author = Anne Gibson\n| title = Engineers called in after leaks shut giant cinema\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 11 Jul 2008\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/albany/news/article.cfm?l_id=380&objectid=10520971\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n}}</ref> A large furniture store opened in May 2009 creating up to 30 jobs.<ref name=twsSEPxvx04>{{cite news\n| author = \n| title = Freedom Furniture to open Albany store\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 26 May 2009\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/albany/news/article.cfm?l_id=380&objectid=10574655\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n}}</ref> High tech firms such as Garmin, a firm specializing in satellite navigation and communications technology, has a showroom in Albany.<ref name=twsSEPxvx09>{{cite news\n| author = \n| title = Garmin in Albany\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 17 Jan 2009\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/albany/news/article.cfm?l_id=380&objectid=10552298\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n}}</ref> There are upscale restaurants.<ref name=twsSEPxvx10>{{cite news\n| author = \n| title = Wine Box Cafe, Albany\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 15 May 2009\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/phoebe-falconer/news/article.cfm?a_id=127&objectid=10572457\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n| first=Phoebe\n| last=Falconer\n}}</ref><ref name=twsSEPxvx12>{{cite news\n| author = \n| title = Paper Moon Cafe, Albany\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 1 Jun 2009\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/restaurants/news/article.cfm?c_id=304&objectid=10575308\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n| first=Peter\n| last=Calder\n}}</ref> Surf-wear fashion retailer Billabong has an outlet store in Albany.<ref name=twsSEPxvx21>{{cite web\n |title=Billabong Outlet Shop \n |publisher=New Zealand Herald \n |date=2009-09-15 \n |url=http://www.theshore.co.nz/v1/Billabong-Outlet-Shop-189.html \n |accessdate=2009-09-15 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100411041055/http://www.theshore.co.nz/v1/Billabong-Outlet-Shop-189.html \n |archivedate=11 April 2010 \n}}</ref><ref name=twsSEPxvx22>{{cite news\n| author = Colin Taylor\n| title = Investors jump on board big Albany syndication scheme\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 20 Jun 2009\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/commercial-property/news/article.cfm?c_id=28&objectid=10582323\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n}}</ref><ref name=twsSEPxvx33>{{cite news\n| author = \n| title = Totara, Albany\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 23 Jun 2008\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/albany/news/article.cfm?l_id=380&objectid=10517891\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n}}</ref>\n\n===Residential real estate===\nConsiderable housing development has also taken place since the early 1990s, which has been facilitated by the extension of the Northern Motorway through the area. There are upscale properties; one large property (318 sq m) on 2ha of land, with a six-bedroom three-bathroom five-car garage house with a pool and solar-powered stable for horses including a \"hoof soaking path\" cost approximately $1.5 million in 2006.<ref name=twsSEPxvx11>{{cite news\n| author = \n| title = Albany: Free rein\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 4 Mar 2006\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/coast-country-real-estate/news/article.cfm?c_id=248&objectid=10370922\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n| first=Sandra\n| last=Goodwin\n}}</ref> In 2005, the rent for a two bedroom apartment (part of a four bedroom house with a two car garage) was $300 per week.<ref name=twsSEPxvx48>{{cite news\n| author = \n| title = Albany: Home and income\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 14 May 2005\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/property/news/article.cfm?c_id=8&objectid=10125367\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n}}</ref>\n\n===Sports===\nAlbany has one of the [[Auckland (region)|Auckland Region]]'s newest sports facilities, [[North Harbour Stadium]]. It draws 25,000 spectators to games<ref name=twsSEPxvx37/> and is home to [[North Harbour Rugby Union|North Harbour]] rugby team in the [[ITM Cup]] and occasionally hosts [[Super Rugby|Super 15]] matches of the [[Blues (Super Rugby)|Blues]]. It was also a stadium used in the [[2011 Rugby World Cup]]. Albany has a gymnasium where New Zealand taekwondo Olympic representatives [[Logan Campbell (taekwondo)|Logan Campbell]] and [[Robin Cheong]] trained in 2008 under the guidance of their coach Grandmaster Jin Keun Oh.\n<ref name=twsSEPxvx27>{{cite news\n| author = Dana Johannsen\n| title = Taekwondo: Campbell's fighting chance\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 18 Jul 2008\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/albany/news/article.cfm?l_id=380&objectid=10522138\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n}}</ref> It has a tennis park.<ref name=twsSEPxvx31>{{cite news\n| author = \n| title = Tennis: Statham to lead Davis Cup team at Albany\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 6 Mar 2009\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/davis-cup/news/article.cfm?c_id=1500887&objectid=10560274\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n}}</ref> Rugby teams practice regularly.<ref name=twsSEPxvx05>{{cite news\n| author = \n| title = Rugby: Teams for pre-season action in Albany, Rotorua\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 21 Jan 2009\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/albany/news/article.cfm?l_id=380&objectid=10552850\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n}}</ref>\n\nThe North Harbour BMX club has a race track at Bush Road, Albany where many New Zealand reps have trained and raced.<ref>[http://www.nhbmx.org.nz North Harbour BMX]</ref>\n\nAlbany is home to the [[Albany United]] association football club, who compete in the [[Northern Regional Football League Division 2]]. [[North Harbour Stadium]] occasionally hosts [[All Whites]] matches.\n\n===Transportation===\nThe [[Albany Busway Station]] connecting to the [[Northern Busway, Auckland|Northern Busway]] was opened in 2005.\n\n===Parks===\n[[File:Lucas Creek from Kell Park platform.jpg|thumb|250px|View of Lucas Creek in Kell Park, Albany.]]\nThe [[North Shore, New Zealand | North Shore City]] council expanded Albany's parkland; in 2007, it paid $3 million for new land totalling {{convert|7000|sqm|sqft|0}}.<ref name=twsSEPxvx17/> There was approximately {{convert|1200|ha|acre|0|abbr=on}} of parkland across the city.<ref name=twsSEPxvx17>{{cite news\n| author = Wayne Thompson\n| title = $2.99m for Albany parkland\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 10 Jul 2007\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/urban-design/news/article.cfm?c_id=139&objectid=10450607\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n}}</ref> Kell Park reserve next to the new Albany Village Library was known for its free-range Bantam chicken population and pirate ship flying fox playground.\n\nA Council notice stated: \"It is prohibited to abandon chickens or to uplift them from this area.\" It also listed chicken \"re-home\" options. The city has traditionally allowed chickens to roam free; according to one newspaper report, \"chickens are undeniably something of a traditional presence in Albany ... Poultry have been roaming free there for more than 30 years, acquiring an iconic status and helping to attract visitors while inspiring a bronze rooster statue and a logo that's proudly emblazoned on local lamp posts.\"<ref name=twsSEPxvx14>{{cite news\n| author =  Bob Kerridge\n| title = Bob Kerridge: Tradition, tourism can't justify cruelty\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 29 May 2008\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/albany/news/article.cfm?l_id=380&objectid=10513070\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n}}</ref> But in 2008 the [[Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals]] objected, causing controversy.<ref name=twsSEPxvx14/> There were health issues as well, with bird droppings on playgrounds and seats and picnic areas and incidents of birds being run over by vehicles.<ref name=twsSEPxvx20/> But when North Shore City Council officers were ordered to shoot chickens, it caused controversy including an outburst from [[Auckland]] City Mayor John Banks, saying the shootings were \"an act of wanton destruction and an animal rights outrage.\"<ref name=twsSEPxvx20>{{cite news\n| author = Alice Neville\n| title = Banks calls chook shoot 'wanton destruction' (+video)\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 27 May 2008\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/albany/news/article.cfm?l_id=380&objectid=10512609\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n}}</ref> In 2008, while Albany village continues to have a rooster on its logo, the free-roaming chicken population is no more, although there was talk of a managed population at Kell Park.<ref name=twsSEPxvx47>{{cite news\n| author = \n| title = Hens no longer rule roost in Albany\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 9 Apr 2008\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/spca/news/article.cfm?o_id=356&objectid=10502872\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n}}</ref>\n\n===Education===\n[http://www.albany.school.nz Albany Primary School] is a contributing primary (years 1-6) school<ref>{{TKI|1202|Albany Primary School}}</ref> with a roll of {{NZ school roll data|1202|y}} as of {{NZ school roll data|||y|y||.}}\n\n[[Kristin School]] is an independent composite school<ref>{{TKI|29|Kristin School}}</ref> offering the International Baccalaureate.  It has a roll of {{NZ school roll data|29|y}} as of {{NZ school roll data|||y|y||.}}\n\n[[Pinehurst School]] is a private composite (years 1-13) school<ref>{{TKI|440|Pinehurst School}}</ref> with a roll of {{NZ school roll data|440|y}} as of {{NZ school roll data|||y|y||.}}\n\n[[Albany Junior High School]] at [[North Harbour, New Zealand|North Harbour]] was opened in 2005,<ref name=twsSEPxvx28>{{cite news\n| author = \n| title = High winds take small toll of apartment block\n| work = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 19 Oct 2005\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/albany/news/article.cfm?l_id=380&objectid=10350926\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n| first=Anne\n| last=Gibson\n}}</ref><ref>{{TKI|6948|Albany Junior High School}}</ref> and has a roll of {{NZ school roll data|6948|y}} as of {{NZ school roll data|||y|y||.}}\n\n[[Albany Senior High School, Auckland|Albany Senior High School]] opened in 2009 for year 11-13 students.<ref name=\"NZ_Herald_10438572\">{{cite news |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/category/story.cfm?c_id=35&objectid=10438572 |title=School bell delay to let students 'wake up' |author=McKenzie-Minifie, Martha |date=9 May 2007 |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> Due to delays in completing the Senior campus, the Senior High School initially shared the Albany Junior High School site.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.nzherald.co.nz/section/1/story.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10520430 |title=$7m cost of temporary campus at Albany Senior High |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |date=8 July 2008|first=Martha|last=McKenzie-Minifie}}</ref> There was controversy about cost overruns when Albany Senior High school was under construction in 2008.<ref name=twsSEPxvx40>{{cite news\n| author = Martha McKenzie-Minifie\n| title = $7m cost of temporary campus at Albany Senior High\n| work = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 8 Jul 2008\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/albany/news/article.cfm?l_id=380&objectid=10520430\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n}}</ref> The new building opened in 2009 to serve 1400 persons.<ref name=twsSEPxvx45>{{cite news\n| author = Wayne Thompson\n| title = Plan for secondary school at Albany angers residents\n| work = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 13 Sep 2006\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/secondary-education/news/article.cfm?c_id=315&objectid=10400972\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n}}</ref> It has a roll of {{NZ school roll data|563|y}} as of {{NZ school roll data|||y|y||.}}<ref>{{TKI|563|Albany Senior High School}}</ref>\n\nAll schools are coeducational and have a [[Socio-Economic Decile|decile rating]] of 10.\n\nAlbany contains the northern campus of [[Massey University]]. It offers 70 majors plus specialised programmes including Mathematics and Information Sciences, Fundamental Sciences, Food Technology, Engineering, Design, Jazz, Social Sciences, Business, Philosophy<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.massey.ac.nz/massey/learning/departments/school-of-humanities/study/subjects/philosophy.cfm|title=Philosophy - Massey University|last=Zealand|first=Massey University, New|website=www.massey.ac.nz|access-date=2016-10-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161011224815/http://www.massey.ac.nz/massey/learning/departments/school-of-humanities/study/subjects/philosophy.cfm|archive-date=11 October 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and Education.<ref name=twsSEPxvx02>{{cite web\n| author = \n| title = Massey University Albany\n| publisher = Massey University\n| date = 2009-09-15\n| url = http://auckland.massey.ac.nz/\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n}}</ref> The school has three areas: East Precinct off State Highway 17; Oteha Rohe, off the Albany Highway; Albany Village Precinct off Kell Drive and State Highway 17, where the Schools of Engineering, Design and Psychology are.<ref name=twsSEPxvx02/> It has a campus shuttle bus between the three campuses leaving every 40 to 45 minutes.<ref name=twsSEPxvx02/> There are bus routes to Albany.<ref name=twsSEPxvx02/>\n\nThe former [[Centrepoint (commune)|Centrepoint]] commune was on farmland near the town centre. After Bert Potter, its founder and leader, was imprisoned on drug and sex abuse charges in 1992,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://crime.co.nz/c-files.aspx?ID=1844|title=Bert Potter -The Centrepoint Community|accessdate=17 July 2009}}</ref> it declined and in 2000 it closed. It was replaced by the Kahikatea Eco-Village and Art-Space.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10507764|title=Memory won't fade easily from Centrepoint property|work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]|first=Megan|last=Jones|date=4 May 2008}}</ref> It has been converted into a research centre for natural medicine, offering courses in aromatherapy, nutrition, naturopathy, herbalism, yoga and ayurvedic medicine.<ref name=twsSEPxvx07>{{cite news\n| author = \n| title = Healing touch for Centrepoint site\n| work = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 17 Dec 2008\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/albany/news/article.cfm?l_id=380&objectid=10548393\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n| first=Anne\n| last=Gibson\n}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book | first=A. W. | last=Reed | title=The Reed Dictionary of New Zealand Place Names | publisher=Reed Books | location=Auckland | year=2002 | isbn=0-7900-0761-4}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://kura.aucklandlibraries.govt.nz/digital/collection/photos/search/searchterm/Albany/field/title/ Photographs of Albany] held in [[Auckland Libraries|Auckland Libraries']] heritage collections.\n\n[[Category:Suburbs of Auckland]]\n[[Category:Populated places in the Auckland Region]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the electorate|Albany (New Zealand electorate)}}{{for|other places named Albany|Albany}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=August 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2011}}\n{{Infobox New Zealand suburbs\n| name           = Albany\n| image          = Albany North Shore Possible Bulk.jpg\n| caption1       = A drawing (looking from the northwest) of how the Albany Town Centre could theoretically be built up if all development were carried out to the maximum allowed around 2006\n| city1          = [[Auckland Council]]\n| city2          =\n| ward           = [[Albany ward (local government)|Albany]]\n| established    = \n| coordinates    = {{coord|36|43|S|174|42|E|region:NZ_type:city_scale:100000|display=it}}\n| area           =\n| population     = 3,057\n| popdate        = 2013\n| trainstations  =\n| ferryterminals =\n| airports       =\n| hospitals      =\n| north          = [[Albany Heights]]\n| northeast      = \n| east           = [[Pinehill, New Zealand|Pinehill]]\n| southeast      = [[Rosedale, Auckland|Rosedale]]\n| south          = [[Brookfield, New Zealand|Brookfield]]\n| southwest      = [[The Landing, New Zealand|The Landing]]\n| west           = \n| northwest      = [[Albany North]]\n| map            = NZ-Albany.png\n| caption2       = Location of Albany in Auckland.\n}}\n\n'''Albany''' is one of the northernmost suburbs of the contiguous [[Auckland]] metropolitan area in New Zealand. It is located to the north of the [[Waitemat\u0101 Harbour]], \n\n{{Convert|15|km|mi}} northwest of the Auckland city centre. The suburb is in the Albany ward, one of the thirteen administrative divisions of [[Auckland Council]].  One of the city's newest suburbs, it was until relatively recently a town in its own right, and still has a feeling of not being truly a part of the city, which lies predominantly to the southeast of it. Much of the land to the north of Albany is still semi-rural.\n\nThe [[M\u0101ori language|M\u0101ori]] name for the area was Okahukura (literally, 'place of rainbows' or 'place of butterflies'). The town was originally known as Lucas Creek. By 1890 it was a fruit-growing area and in that year it was renamed 'Albany' after the fruit-growing district called [[Albany, Western Australia|'Albany' in Australia]], pronounced with a short 'a' as in ''Albert''.<ref>{{cite journal\n| title = Edge city\n| journal= New Zealand Geographic\n| issue= 37 \n| publisher = \n| date = 1998\n| url = https://www.nzgeo.com/stories/edge-city/\n| accessdate = 17 August 2017\n| first=Liz\n| last=Mahoney\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=History books offer 'definite' guidance on pronunciation of Albany |first=Amy |last=Baker |url= https://www.stuff.co.nz/the-press/national/95706530/History-books-offer-definite-guidance-on-pronunciation-of-Albany |newspaper=Stuff |date=22 August 2017 |accessdate=24 August 2017}}</ref> The name ''Albany'' derives from ''[[Alba]]'' (Gaelic for Scotland) and its Latinisation.\n\n==City planning==\nIn 2005, there were plans to turn a major swath of Albany into a planned mini-urban centre, described as a \"happy mix of businesses, hotels, shops, apartments, and entertainment (including) an environment of parks and lakes and of tree-lined streets, paths and cycleways linking to the new [[Albany Busway Station|park-and-ride bus station]] and the [[Northern Busway, Auckland|rapid-busway lanes]] along the Northern Motorway to downtown Auckland\", according to a newspaper report.<ref name=twsSEPxvx37>{{cite news\n| author = Wayne Thompson\n| title = Albany blueprint gets green light\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 25 Oct 2005\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/commercial-construction/news/article.cfm?c_id=693&objectid=10351837\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n}}</ref> It would be home to 10,000 people.<ref name=twsSEPxvx37/> Authorities wanted sound-proofed apartments against outside noise.<ref name=twsSEPxvx37/> Initial plans called for hotels, library, municipal swimming pool as well as the headquarters for the North Shore City Council.<ref name=twsSEPxvx37/> In some respects, development has proceeded accordingly, but the 2008\u201309 economic downturn has blunted some of this activity.\n\n===Demographics===\nThe population was 3,057 in the 2013 Census, an increase of 888 from the 2006 Census.<ref name=twsSEPxvx01>{{NZ Quickstats2013|13255|Albany}}</ref> There were 1,092 occupied dwellings in Albany in 2013,<ref name=twsSEPxvx01 /> and demographic makeup was 73% European, 5% Maori, 2% Pacific peoples, 22% Asian, 3% Middle Eastern/Latin American/African, and 1% other.<ref name=twsSEPxvx01/> The median income of $32,600 was higher than for the Auckland Region of $29,600.<ref name=twsSEPxvx01/> Unemployment in Albany was 7.0%, lower than the Auckland average of 8.1%.<ref name=twsSEPxvx01/> 91% had internet access and 88% had cell phones.<ref name=twsSEPxvx01/> Cars were prevalent.<ref name=twsSEPxvx01/> A near majority (48%) were born overseas.<ref name=twsSEPxvx01/> Ethnically, in keeping with the wider North Shore, Albany was predominantly [[Pakeha]] and Asian, and had a relatively high proportion of recent migrants from both elsewhere in New Zealand and overseas.\n\n===Retail and commercial activity===\nAlbany has become, in some respects, a substantial shopping and retail zone within the northwestern Auckland area.\n\nThe area (the future 'Albany Town Centre') is fast-growing in terms of its population and the development of the built environment, following planning decisions and land sales made by central and local governments in the 1980s and 1990s. Through the 1990s industrial and retail areas were rapidly produced, predominantly owned and occupied by local and foreign corporate capital. A major [[Shopping mall|shopping centre]] hub was opened in the late 1990s and has since expanded, with [[Westfield Albany]] becoming New Zealand's largest shopping centre. The so-called supermall opened in August 2007 on McKinnon Drive costing $210 million with 142 shops built by over 3500 workers, which features 1800 cinema seats and an indoor area of 7ha.<ref name=twsSEPxvx18/> There is parking for 2300 vehicles.<ref name=twsSEPxvx18/> [[Kmart Australia|Kmart]], [[Farmers Trading Company | Farmers]], and [[New World (supermarket)|New World]] stores are anchors.<ref name=twsSEPxvx18>{{cite news\n| author = Anne Gibson\n| title = Countdown under way for Albany supermall rollout\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 23 Aug 2007\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/shopping/news/article.cfm?c_id=318&objectid=10459307\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n}}</ref> The mall claimed it provides \"free space for community organisations for awareness and fundraising activities\" but one volunteer claimed he was ejected from the premises while trying to raise money for veterans because of a dispute with mall management.<ref name=twsSEPxvx24>{{cite news\n| author = \n| title = Poppy Appeal clash at Albany mall\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 22 Apr 2008\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/yvonne-tahana/news/article.cfm?a_id=345&objectid=10505463\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n| first=Yvonne\n| last=Tahana\n}}</ref>\n\nThere has been development of a substantial retail project anchored by a 10,000 square metre Mega Mitre 10 store on Oteha Valley Road, across from the North Harbour Stadium, run by Symphony Projects Management.<ref name=twsSEPxvx44>{{cite news\n| author = \n| title = DIY centre to join Albany retail scene\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 10 Oct 2007\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/ing-property-trust/news/article.cfm?o_id=87&objectid=10468910\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n| first=Anne\n| last=Gibson\n}}</ref>\n\nAlbany has been the site of a $500 million so-called ''Super City'' showcase development project. Plans in 2006 featured a 200-room hotel, apartment complex with three 30-storey towers, and up to 15 office blocks rising 10 levels high.<ref name=twsSEPxvx13>{{cite news\n| author = \n| title = Albany to grow into city in own right\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 17 Nov 2006\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10411174\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n| first=Anne\n| last=Gibson\n}}</ref> But in the economic downturn of 2008\u201309, the project was in dire straits; one report suggested up to 350 investors (many elderly) risked losing up to $20 million.<ref name=twsSEPxvx06>{{cite news\n| author = \n| title = Investors risk losing $20m on Albany project\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 9 Jun 2009\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/albany/news/article.cfm?l_id=380&objectid=10577259\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n| first=Anne\n| last=Gibson\n}}</ref>\n\nAlbany has a site for [[Sky Television (New Zealand)|Sky Television]]'s [[Prime (New Zealand TV channel)|Prime TV]], as well as the Broadcast Centre for Sky PPV.\n\nThere are movie theatres<ref name=twsSEPxvx03>{{cite news|title=Cinema |publisher=New Zealand Herald |date=2009-09-15 |url=http://movies.nzherald.co.nz/cinema/view/sm7v3/ |accessdate=2009-09-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100525003856/http://movies.nzherald.co.nz/cinema/view/sm7v3/ |archivedate=25 May 2010 }}</ref> including the 1800-seat multiplex inside the new mall, although there were reports of roof problems and weathertightness.<ref name=twsSEPxvx15>{{cite news\n| author = Anne Gibson\n| title = Engineers called in after leaks shut giant cinema\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 11 Jul 2008\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/albany/news/article.cfm?l_id=380&objectid=10520971\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n}}</ref> A large furniture store opened in May 2009 creating up to 30 jobs.<ref name=twsSEPxvx04>{{cite news\n| author = \n| title = Freedom Furniture to open Albany store\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 26 May 2009\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/albany/news/article.cfm?l_id=380&objectid=10574655\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n}}</ref> High tech firms such as Garmin, a firm specializing in satellite navigation and communications technology, has a showroom in Albany.<ref name=twsSEPxvx09>{{cite news\n| author = \n| title = Garmin in Albany\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 17 Jan 2009\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/albany/news/article.cfm?l_id=380&objectid=10552298\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n}}</ref> There are upscale restaurants.<ref name=twsSEPxvx10>{{cite news\n| author = \n| title = Wine Box Cafe, Albany\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 15 May 2009\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/phoebe-falconer/news/article.cfm?a_id=127&objectid=10572457\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n| first=Phoebe\n| last=Falconer\n}}</ref><ref name=twsSEPxvx12>{{cite news\n| author = \n| title = Paper Moon Cafe, Albany\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 1 Jun 2009\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/restaurants/news/article.cfm?c_id=304&objectid=10575308\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n| first=Peter\n| last=Calder\n}}</ref> Surf-wear fashion retailer Billabong has an outlet store in Albany.<ref name=twsSEPxvx21>{{cite web\n |title=Billabong Outlet Shop \n |publisher=New Zealand Herald \n |date=2009-09-15 \n |url=http://www.theshore.co.nz/v1/Billabong-Outlet-Shop-189.html \n |accessdate=2009-09-15 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100411041055/http://www.theshore.co.nz/v1/Billabong-Outlet-Shop-189.html \n |archivedate=11 April 2010 \n}}</ref><ref name=twsSEPxvx22>{{cite news\n| author = Colin Taylor\n| title = Investors jump on board big Albany syndication scheme\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 20 Jun 2009\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/commercial-property/news/article.cfm?c_id=28&objectid=10582323\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n}}</ref><ref name=twsSEPxvx33>{{cite news\n| author = \n| title = Totara, Albany\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 23 Jun 2008\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/albany/news/article.cfm?l_id=380&objectid=10517891\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n}}</ref>\n\n===Residential real estate===\nConsiderable housing development has also taken place since the early 1990s, which has been facilitated by the extension of the Northern Motorway through the area. There are upscale properties; one large property (318 sq m) on 2ha of land, with a six-bedroom three-bathroom five-car garage house with a pool and solar-powered stable for horses including a \"hoof soaking path\" cost approximately $1.5 million in 2006.<ref name=twsSEPxvx11>{{cite news\n| author = \n| title = Albany: Free rein\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 4 Mar 2006\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/coast-country-real-estate/news/article.cfm?c_id=248&objectid=10370922\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n| first=Sandra\n| last=Goodwin\n}}</ref> In 2005, the rent for a two bedroom apartment (part of a four bedroom house with a two car garage) was $300 per week.<ref name=twsSEPxvx48>{{cite news\n| author = \n| title = Albany: Home and income\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 14 May 2005\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/property/news/article.cfm?c_id=8&objectid=10125367\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n}}</ref>\n\n===Sports===\nAlbany has one of the [[Auckland (region)|Auckland Region]]'s newest sports facilities, [[North Harbour Stadium]]. It draws 25,000 spectators to games<ref name=twsSEPxvx37/> and is home to [[North Harbour Rugby Union|North Harbour]] rugby team in the [[ITM Cup]] and occasionally hosts [[Super Rugby|Super 15]] matches of the [[Blues (Super Rugby)|Blues]]. It was also a stadium used in the [[2011 Rugby World Cup]]. Albany has a gymnasium where New Zealand taekwondo Olympic representatives [[Logan Campbell (taekwondo)|Logan Campbell]] and [[Robin Cheong]] trained in 2008 under the guidance of their coach Grandmaster Jin Keun Oh.\n<ref name=twsSEPxvx27>{{cite news\n| author = Dana Johannsen\n| title = Taekwondo: Campbell's fighting chance\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 18 Jul 2008\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/albany/news/article.cfm?l_id=380&objectid=10522138\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n}}</ref> It has a tennis park.<ref name=twsSEPxvx31>{{cite news\n| author = \n| title = Tennis: Statham to lead Davis Cup team at Albany\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 6 Mar 2009\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/davis-cup/news/article.cfm?c_id=1500887&objectid=10560274\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n}}</ref> Rugby teams practice regularly.<ref name=twsSEPxvx05>{{cite news\n| author = \n| title = Rugby: Teams for pre-season action in Albany, Rotorua\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 21 Jan 2009\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/albany/news/article.cfm?l_id=380&objectid=10552850\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n}}</ref>\n\nThe North Harbour BMX club has a race track at Bush Road, Albany where many New Zealand reps have trained and raced.<ref>[http://www.nhbmx.org.nz North Harbour BMX]</ref>\n\nAlbany is home to the [[Albany United]] association football club, who compete in the [[Northern Regional Football League Division 2]]. [[North Harbour Stadium]] occasionally hosts [[All Whites]] matches.\n\n===Transportation===\nThe [[Albany Busway Station]] connecting to the [[Northern Busway, Auckland|Northern Busway]] was opened in 2005.\n\n===Parks===\n[[File:Lucas Creek from Kell Park platform.jpg|thumb|250px|View of Lucas Creek in Kell Park, Albany.]]\nThe [[North Shore, New Zealand | North Shore City]] council expanded Albany's parkland; in 2007, it paid $3 million for new land totalling {{convert|7000|sqm|sqft|0}}.<ref name=twsSEPxvx17/> There was approximately {{convert|1200|ha|acre|0|abbr=on}} of parkland across the city.<ref name=twsSEPxvx17>{{cite news\n| author = Wayne Thompson\n| title = $2.99m for Albany parkland\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 10 Jul 2007\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/urban-design/news/article.cfm?c_id=139&objectid=10450607\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n}}</ref> Kell Park reserve next to the new Albany Village Library was known for its free-range Bantam chicken population and pirate ship flying fox playground.\n\nA Council notice stated: \"It is prohibited to abandon chickens or to uplift them from this area.\" It also listed chicken \"re-home\" options. The city has traditionally allowed chickens to roam free; according to one newspaper report, \"chickens are undeniably something of a traditional presence in Albany ... Poultry have been roaming free there for more than 30 years, acquiring an iconic status and helping to attract visitors while inspiring a bronze rooster statue and a logo that's proudly emblazoned on local lamp posts.\"<ref name=twsSEPxvx14>{{cite news\n| author =  Bob Kerridge\n| title = Bob Kerridge: Tradition, tourism can't justify cruelty\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 29 May 2008\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/albany/news/article.cfm?l_id=380&objectid=10513070\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n}}</ref> But in 2008 the [[Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals]] objected, causing controversy.<ref name=twsSEPxvx14/> There were health issues as well, with bird droppings on playgrounds and seats and picnic areas and incidents of birds being run over by vehicles.<ref name=twsSEPxvx20/> But when North Shore City Council officers were ordered to shoot chickens, it caused controversy including an outburst from [[Auckland]] City Mayor John Banks, saying the shootings were \"an act of wanton destruction and an animal rights outrage.\"<ref name=twsSEPxvx20>{{cite news\n| author = Alice Neville\n| title = Banks calls chook shoot 'wanton destruction' (+video)\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 27 May 2008\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/albany/news/article.cfm?l_id=380&objectid=10512609\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n}}</ref> In 2008, while Albany village continues to have a rooster on its logo, the free-roaming chicken population is no more, although there was talk of a managed population at Kell Park.<ref name=twsSEPxvx47>{{cite news\n| author = \n| title = Hens no longer rule roost in Albany\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 9 Apr 2008\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/spca/news/article.cfm?o_id=356&objectid=10502872\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n}}</ref>\n\n===Education===\n[http://www.albany.school.nz Albany Primary School] is a contributing primary (years 1-6) school<ref>{{TKI|1202|Albany Primary School}}</ref> with a roll of {{NZ school roll data|1202|y}} as of {{NZ school roll data|||y|y||.}}\n\n[[Kristin School]] is an independent composite school<ref>{{TKI|29|Kristin School}}</ref> offering the International Baccalaureate.  It has a roll of {{NZ school roll data|29|y}} as of {{NZ school roll data|||y|y||.}}\n\n[[Pinehurst School]] is a private composite (years 1-13) school<ref>{{TKI|440|Pinehurst School}}</ref> with a roll of {{NZ school roll data|440|y}} as of {{NZ school roll data|||y|y||.}}\n\n[[Albany Junior High School]] at [[North Harbour, New Zealand|North Harbour]] was opened in 2005,<ref name=twsSEPxvx28>{{cite news\n| author = \n| title = High winds take small toll of apartment block\n| work = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 19 Oct 2005\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/albany/news/article.cfm?l_id=380&objectid=10350926\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n| first=Anne\n| last=Gibson\n}}</ref><ref>{{TKI|6948|Albany Junior High School}}</ref> and has a roll of {{NZ school roll data|6948|y}} as of {{NZ school roll data|||y|y||.}}\n\n[[Albany Senior High School, Auckland|Albany Senior High School]] opened in 2009 for year 11-13 students.<ref name=\"NZ_Herald_10438572\">{{cite news |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/category/story.cfm?c_id=35&objectid=10438572 |title=School bell delay to let students 'wake up' |author=McKenzie-Minifie, Martha |date=9 May 2007 |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> Due to delays in completing the Senior campus, the Senior High School initially shared the Albany Junior High School site.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.nzherald.co.nz/section/1/story.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10520430 |title=$7m cost of temporary campus at Albany Senior High |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |date=8 July 2008|first=Martha|last=McKenzie-Minifie}}</ref> There was controversy about cost overruns when Albany Senior High school was under construction in 2008.<ref name=twsSEPxvx40>{{cite news\n| author = Martha McKenzie-Minifie\n| title = $7m cost of temporary campus at Albany Senior High\n| work = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 8 Jul 2008\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/albany/news/article.cfm?l_id=380&objectid=10520430\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n}}</ref> The new building opened in 2009 to serve 1400 persons.<ref name=twsSEPxvx45>{{cite news\n| author = Wayne Thompson\n| title = Plan for secondary school at Albany angers residents\n| work = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 13 Sep 2006\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/secondary-education/news/article.cfm?c_id=315&objectid=10400972\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n}}</ref> It has a roll of {{NZ school roll data|563|y}} as of {{NZ school roll data|||y|y||.}}<ref>{{TKI|563|Albany Senior High School}}</ref>\n\nAll schools are coeducational and have a [[Socio-Economic Decile|decile rating]] of 10.\n\nAlbany contains the northern campus of [[Massey University]]. It offers 70 majors plus specialised programmes including Mathematics and Information Sciences, Fundamental Sciences, Food Technology, Engineering, Design, Jazz, Social Sciences, Business, Philosophy<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.massey.ac.nz/massey/learning/departments/school-of-humanities/study/subjects/philosophy.cfm|title=Philosophy - Massey University|last=Zealand|first=Massey University, New|website=www.massey.ac.nz|access-date=2016-10-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161011224815/http://www.massey.ac.nz/massey/learning/departments/school-of-humanities/study/subjects/philosophy.cfm|archive-date=11 October 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and Education.<ref name=twsSEPxvx02>{{cite web\n| author = \n| title = Massey University Albany\n| publisher = Massey University\n| date = 2009-09-15\n| url = http://auckland.massey.ac.nz/\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n}}</ref> The school has three areas: East Precinct off State Highway 17; Oteha Rohe, off the Albany Highway; Albany Village Precinct off Kell Drive and State Highway 17, where the Schools of Engineering, Design and Psychology are.<ref name=twsSEPxvx02/> It has a campus shuttle bus between the three campuses leaving every 40 to 45 minutes.<ref name=twsSEPxvx02/> There are bus routes to Albany.<ref name=twsSEPxvx02/>\n\nThe former [[Centrepoint (commune)|Centrepoint]] commune was on farmland near the town centre. After Bert Potter, its founder and leader, was imprisoned on drug and sex abuse charges in 1992,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://crime.co.nz/c-files.aspx?ID=1844|title=Bert Potter -The Centrepoint Community|accessdate=17 July 2009}}</ref> it declined and in 2000 it closed. It was replaced by the Kahikatea Eco-Village and Art-Space.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10507764|title=Memory won't fade easily from Centrepoint property|work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]|first=Megan|last=Jones|date=4 May 2008}}</ref> It has been converted into a research centre for natural medicine, offering courses in aromatherapy, nutrition, naturopathy, herbalism, yoga and ayurvedic medicine.<ref name=twsSEPxvx07>{{cite news\n| author = \n| title = Healing touch for Centrepoint site\n| work = New Zealand Herald\n| date = 17 Dec 2008\n| url = http://www.nzherald.co.nz/albany/news/article.cfm?l_id=380&objectid=10548393\n| accessdate = 2009-09-15\n| first=Anne\n| last=Gibson\n}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book | first=A. W. | last=Reed | title=The Reed Dictionary of New Zealand Place Names | publisher=Reed Books | location=Auckland | year=2002 | isbn=0-7900-0761-4}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://kura.aucklandlibraries.govt.nz/digital/?p=q&collection=p20062coll1&search=albany&field=title&mode=all&conn= Photographs of Albany] held in [[Auckland Libraries|Auckland Libraries']] heritage collections.\n\n[[Category:Suburbs of Auckland]]\n[[Category:Populated places in the Auckland Region]]\n", "name_user": "Agh47", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:updated photo link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Albany,_New_Zealand"}
{"title_page": "Lagrange invariant", "text_new": "In [[optics]] the '''Lagrange invariant''' is a measure of the light propagating through an optical system. It is defined by\n:<math>H = n\\overline{u}y - nu\\overline{y}</math>,\nwhere ''y'' and ''u'' are the [[marginal ray]] height and angle respectively, and ''\u0233'' and ''\u016b'' are the [[chief ray]] height and angle. ''n'' is the ambient [[refractive index]].  In order to reduce confusion with other quantities, the symbol [[\u0416]] may be used in place of H.<ref name=Greivenkamp28>{{cite book |first=John E. |last=Greivenkamp |year=2004 |title=Field Guide to Geometrical Optics |publisher=SPIE |others=SPIE Field Guides vol. '''FG01''' |isbn=0-8194-5294-7 |page=28}}</ref> ''\u0416''<sup>2</sup> is proportional to the throughput of the optical system (related to [[\u00e9tendue]]).<ref name=Greivenkamp28/>  For a given optical system, the Lagrange invariant is a constant throughout all space, that is, it is invariant upon [[refraction]] and transfer.\n\nThe '''optical invariant''' is a generalization of the Lagrange invariant which is formed using the [[ray (optics)|ray]] heights and angles of any two rays.  For these rays, the optical invariant is a constant throughout all space.<ref>[http://www.newport.com/Optics-Fundamentals/604533/1033/content.aspx Optics Fundamentals], Newport Corporation, retrieved 9/8/2011</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Etendue]]\n* [[Smith-Helmholtz invariant]]\n* [[Abbe sine condition]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Optics-stub}}\n[[Category:Geometrical optics]]\n", "text_old": "In [[optics]] the '''Lagrange invariant''' is a measure of the light propagating through an optical system. It is defined by\n:<math>H = n\\overline{u}y - nu\\overline{y}</math>,\nwhere ''y'' and ''u'' are the [[marginal ray]] height and angle respectively, and ''\u0233'' and ''\u016b'' are the [[chief ray]] height and angle. ''n'' is the ambient [[refractive index]].  In order to reduce confusion with other quantities, the symbol [[\u0416]] may be used in place of H.<ref name=Greivenkamp28>{{cite book |first=John E. |last=Greivenkamp |year=2004 |title=Field Guide to Geometrical Optics |publisher=SPIE |others=SPIE Field Guides vol. '''FG01''' |isbn=0-8194-5294-7 |page=28}}</ref> ''\u0416''<sup>2</sup> is proportional to the throughput of the optical system (related to [[\u00e9tendue]]).<ref name=Greivenkamp28/>  For a given optical system, the Lagrange invariant is a constant throughout all space, that is, it is invariant upon [[refraction]] and transfer.\n\nThe '''optical invariant''' is a generalization of the Lagrange invariant which is formed using the [[ray (optics)|ray]] heights and angles of any two rays.  For these rays, the optical invariant is a constant throughout all space.<ref>[http://www.newport.com/Optics-Fundamentals/604533/1033/content.aspx Optics Fundamentals], Newport Corporation, retrieved 9/8/2011</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Abbe sine condition]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Optics-stub}}\n[[Category:Geometrical optics]]\n", "name_user": "Ptbrown1729", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lagrange_invariant"}
{"title_page": "Marquise Goodwin", "text_new": "{{short description|American football wide receiver and kick returner}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name          = Marquise Goodwin\n| image         = Goodwin 2018 (cropped).jpg\n| image_size    = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = Goodwin with the 49ers in 2018\n| current_team  = San Francisco 49ers \n| number        = 11 \n| position      = [[Wide receiver]]\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1990|11|19|mf=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Lubbock, Texas]]\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   =\n| height_ft     = 5\n| height_in     = 9\n| weight_lbs    = 185\n| high_school   = [[Rowlett High School|Rowlett]] ([[Rowlett, Texas]])\n| college       = [[Texas Longhorns football|Texas]]\n| draftyear     = 2013\n| draftround    = 3\n| draftpick     = 78\n| pastteams     = \n* [[Buffalo Bills]] ({{NFL Year|2013}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2016}})\n* [[San Francisco 49ers]] ({{NFL Year|2017}}\u2013present)\n| status        = Active\n| highlights    =\n| statweek      = \n| statseason    = 2019\n| statlabel1    = [[Reception (American football)|Receptions]]\n| statvalue1    = 140\n| statlabel2    = [[Receiving yards]]\n| statvalue2    = 2,323\n| statlabel3    = [[Return yards]]\n| statvalue3    = 468\n| statlabel4    = [[Rushing yards]]\n| statvalue4    = 89\n| statlabel5    = [[Touchdown|Total touchdowns]]\n| statvalue5    = 13\n| nflnew        = marquisegoodwin/2539964\n}}\n\n'''Marquise Derell Goodwin''' (born November 19, 1990) is an [[American football]] [[wide receiver]] and [[kick returner]] for the [[San Francisco 49ers]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL) and an [[Olympic Games|Olympian]] who competed in the long jump in track and field. He was drafted by the [[Buffalo Bills]] in the third round with the 78th pick of the [[2013 NFL Draft]]. He played [[college football]] at [[Texas Gayhorns football|Texas]].\n\nIn [[Suck and go ]], his specialty is the deep throat, an event in which there is 2 guys. Goodwin represented the United States at the 2008 IAAF World junior championships, the 2011 World University games, the 2011 IAAF World Championships, the [[2012 Summer Olympics]], and the [[2015 Pan American Games]], where he won silver. He has competed as a long jumper and sprinter, and has been a top competitor in the [[60 meters]] and [[100 meters]] dashes, and the [[triple jump]].\n\n==Early years==\nGoodwin was born in [[Lubbock, Texas]]. He attended [[Rowlett High School]] in [[Rowlett, Texas]], and played [[high school football]] and competed in track and field for the Rowlett Eagles.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://sportsday.dallasnews.com/high-school/high-schools/2017/05/11/flashback-marquise-goodwin-burned-defenders-nfl-blew-people-away-track-rowlett |title=Flashback: Before Marquise Goodwin burned defenders in the NFL, he blew people away on the track for Rowlett |date=May 11, 2017 |website=SportsDayHS |language=en |access-date=April 30, 2018}}</ref> He had the second fastest 100-meter time (10.24w) in the state, was the state champion in the triple jump and long jump, and was a member of the state title-winning [[4 x 100 metres relay|4\u00d7100-meter relay]] team.<ref>[http://insider.espn.go.com/ncf/recruiting/tracker/player?recruitId=55073&action=login&appRedirect=http%3a%2f%2finsider.espn.go.com%2fncf%2frecruiting%2ftracker%2fplayer%3frecruitId%3d55073 College football recruiting: Marquise Goodwin] ESPN</ref>  He won seven Texas Class 5A state track and field championships while he was at Rowlett. He also finished first in the long jump at the [[2008 World Junior Championships in Athletics]] in [[Bydgoszcz]], [[Poland]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.burntorangenation.com/2009/1/16/724914/recruiting-spotlight-marqu |title=Recruiting Spotlight: Marquise Goodwin |last=Eberts |first=Wescott |date=2009-01-16 |website=Burnt Orange Nation |access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref> and first again at the 2008 and 2009 United States Junior Championships. At the 2009 [[USA Outdoor Track and Field Championships]], Goodwin set the national high school record in the long jump and placed fifth ({{convert|8.18|m|ftin|abbr=off|sp=us|disp=x|; }}).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://texassports.com/news/2009/6/27/062809aab_430.aspx |title=Future Longhorn Marquise Goodwin sets national high school record in long jump at U.S. Championships |website=University of Texas Athletics |language=en |access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref><ref>http://www.iaaf.org/WJC08/news/kind=100/newsid=45869.html</ref><ref>Jack Pfeifer [http://usa.milesplit.us/articles/24169 Marquise Goodwin jumps 26-10 for national high school record] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120729230802/http://usa.milesplit.us/articles/24169# |date=July 29, 2012 }} June 28, 2009 MileSplit.us</ref>\n\nIn his high school career, he caught 132 passes for 1,709 yards (12.95 average) and 17 touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.texassports.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/goodwin_marquise00.html |title=Marquise Goodwin Profile |date=2019-07-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120616091444/http://www.texassports.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/goodwin_marquise00.html |archive-date=June 16, 2012 |url-status=dead |access-date=August 6, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nGoodwin received an athletic scholarship to attend the [[University of Texas at Austin]], where he pledged [[Kappa Alpha Psi]] fraternity.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://nphcnews.com/kap/kappa-alpha-psis-colin-kaepernick-and-marquise-goodwin-explore-egypt/ |title=Kappa Alpha Psi\u2019s Colin Kaepernick and Marquise Goodwin Explore Egypt |date=July 5, 2017 |work=NPHC News |access-date=April 30, 2018 |language=en-US |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170925032008/http://nphcnews.com/kap/kappa-alpha-psis-colin-kaepernick-and-marquise-goodwin-explore-egypt/ |archive-date=September 25, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He played for coach [[Mack Brown]]'s [[Texas Longhorns football]] team from 2009 to 2012, and also competed for the Texas Longhorns track and field team from 2010 to 2012.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://texassports.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=2872 |title=Marquise Goodwin - Track & Field / Cross Country m |website=University of Texas Athletics |language=en |access-date=December 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===College track and field===\nGoodwin was a two-time NCAA champion in the long jump (2010, 2012) and a four-time All-American in track and field. He won five Big 12 Conference championships and made the All-Big 12 team seven times. He is the Longhorns' indoor record holder in the long jump and was the runner-up for the 2012 NCAA Indoor long jump title.\n\nHe won the [[2011 USA Outdoor Track and Field Championships|2011 U.S. Outdoor Track and Field]] long jump title with a personal-best {{convert|27|ft|4|in|m|abbr=off|sp=us}} and won the [[2012 United States Olympic Trials (track and field)|2012 Outdoor Championship/Olympic Trials]] with the same distance. He competed in the [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's long jump|2012 Olympics]], ranking tied for the #1 qualifier, but only managed 10th place in the final.\n\nHe chose not to compete in the 2013 NCAA track and field seasons in indoor or outdoor.\n\n===College football===\nIn his collegiate career, Goodwin started 21 of the 49 games in which he appeared, including the [[2010 BCS National Championship Game]] against [[2009 Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2010-01-07-alabama.html |title=BCS Championship - Texas vs Alabama Box Score, January 7, 2010 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 30, 2018}}</ref> His final career statistics included 116 receptions for 1,296 yards and six touchdowns, rushed 46 times for 405 yards and 44 kickoff returns for 985 yards and one touchdown. He also returned a punt for 22 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/marquise-goodwin-1/gamelog/2009 |title=Marquise Goodwin 2009 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 3, 2019}}</ref> Some of his key plays include his first touchdown of his 2009 freshman year, a game-winning touchdown in a 16-13 victory over the [[2009 Oklahoma Sooners football|Oklahoma Sooners]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2009-10-17-oklahoma.html |title=Texas vs Oklahoma Box Score, October 17, 2009 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 30, 2018}}</ref>  Goodwin also returned a kickoff 95 yards for a touchdown to seal the Longhorns' win over the [[2009 Texas A&M Aggies football|Texas A&M Aggies]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2009-11-26-texas-am.html |title=Texas at Texas A&M Box Score, November 26, 2009 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2010 season, Goodwin had 31 receptions for 324 yards and one touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/marquise-goodwin-1/gamelog/2010 |title=Marquise Goodwin 2010 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 3, 2019}}</ref> In the 2011 season, he had 33 receptions for 421 yards and two touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/marquise-goodwin-1/gamelog/2011 |title=Marquise Goodwin 2011 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 3, 2019}}</ref> In the 2012 season, Goodwin was named a semifinalist for the [[William V. Campbell Trophy|Campbell Trophy]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://texassports.com/news/2012/9/27/092712aac_503.aspx |title=Goodwin a Semifinalist for Campbell Trophy |website=University of Texas Athletics |language=en |access-date=December 5, 2018}}</ref> In the [[2012 Alamo Bowl]] against [[2012 Oregon State Beavers football|Oregon State]], Goodwin rushed for a 64-yard touchdown, and caught the game-winning, 36-yard touchdown pass\u2014an effort that was good enough to earn him the game's Offensive Most Valuable Player trophy.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2012-12-29-oregon-state.html |title=Alamo Bowl - Texas vs Oregon State Box Score, December 29, 2012 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 30, 2018}}</ref> In the 2012 season, he had 26 receptions for 340 receiving yards and three receiving touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/marquise-goodwin-1/gamelog/2012 |title=Marquise Goodwin 2012 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\nGoodwin went on to compete in the 2013 [[NFLPA Collegiate Bowl]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sbnation.com/2013-nfl-draft/2013/1/10/3863496/2013-nfl-draft-nflpa-collegiate-bowl-roster-marquise-goodwin |title=NFLPA Collegiate Bowl rosters |last=Arthur |first=Kenneth |date=January 10, 2013 |website=SBNation.com |access-date=December 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Collegiate statistics====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"6\" style=\"{{CollegePrimaryStyle|Texas Longhorns|color=white}}\" | Marquise Goodwin\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align: center;\" | Receiving\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align: center;\" | Rushing\n|-\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | Year\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | School\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | Conf\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | Class\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | Pos\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | G\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | Rec\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | Yds\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | Avg\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | TD\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | Att\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | Yds\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | Avg\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | TD\n|-\n| [[2009 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2009]]\n| [[2009 Texa