 Goodwin was drafted by the [[Buffalo Bills]] in the third round, with the 78th overall pick, of the [[2013 NFL Draft]].<ref>http://collegesportsblog.dallasnews.com/2013/04/former-texas-longhorn-marquise-goodwin-drafted-by-buffalo-bills-in-third-round.html/</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2013/draft.htm |title=2013 NFL Draft Listing |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Buffalo Bills===\nOn May 10, 2013, Goodwin signed a four-year contract with the Bills, where he also practiced in his first day of rookie minicamp.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2013/05/10/bills-sign-marquise-goodwin-dustin-hopkins-two-other-draft-picks/ |title=Bills sign Marquise Goodwin, Dustin Hopkins, two other draft picks |date=2013-05-10 |website=ProFootballTalk |language=en |access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref> He caught his first career [[touchdown]] Week 6 against the [[Cincinnati Bengals]], a 40-yard pass from [[Thaddeus Lewis]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201310130buf.htm |title=Cincinnati Bengals at San Francisco - October 13th, 2013 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 30, 2018}}</ref> Goodwin played 12 games in his rookie season making 17 receptions for 283 receiving yards. He also had 16 kickoff return opportunities totaling 351 returning yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/G/GoodMa00/gamelog/2013/ |title=Marquise Goodwin 2013 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, hobbled by numerous injuries (concussion, ankle, ribs, and hamstring), Goodwin caught only one pass for 42 yards, which came against the Detroit Lions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.syracuse.com/buffalo-bills/2014/10/buffalo_bills_injury_report_marquise_goodwin.html |title=Buffalo Bills injury report: Marquise Goodwin limited by hamstring Thursday |last=Fairburn |first=Matthew |date=2014-10-16 |website=syracuse.com |language=en-US |access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201410050det.htm |title=San Francisco at Detroit Lions - October 5th, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 30, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/G/GoodMa00/gamelog/2014/ |title=Marquise Goodwin 2014 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter missing five games with broken ribs, Goodwin posted two receptions for 24 yards in the 2015 season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/G/GoodMa00/gamelog/2015/ |title=Marquise Goodwin 2015 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Goodwin posted 29 receptions, 431 yards, and three touchdowns, setting career highs in games played, receptions, and receiving yards. While Goodwin enjoyed his most productive season, he was also inconsistent.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/G/GoodMa00/gamelog/2016/ |title=Marquise Goodwin 2016 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref> His 42.6% catch rate ranked 107th among qualified NFL wide receivers in 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.playerprofiler.com/nfl/marquise-goodwin|title=Marquise Goodwin Advanced Stats and Metrics Profile: Catch Rate|work=PlayerProfiler.com}}</ref>\n\n===San Francisco 49ers===\n[[File:Marquise Goodwin with the 49ers in 2018.jpg|thumb|Marquise Goodwin wears a fan's jersey before a 49ers home game]]\nOn March 9, 2017, Goodwin signed a two-year contract with the [[San Francisco 49ers]].<ref>{{cite web|title=49ers Agree to Terms with Seven Free Agents|url=http://www.49ers.com/news/article-2/49ers-Agree-to-Terms-with-Seven-Free-Agents/27ef0da5-47b8-4a0f-96d5-d6c61d929fb6|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171214161411/http://www.49ers.com/news/article-2/49ers-Agree-to-Terms-with-Seven-Free-Agents/27ef0da5-47b8-4a0f-96d5-d6c61d929fb6|url-status=dead|archive-date=December 14, 2017|website=49ers.com|date=March 9, 2017}}</ref> On September 10, 2017, in his 49ers debut, Goodwin had three receptions for 21 yards in the season opening 23\u20133 loss to the [[2017 Carolina Panthers season|Carolina Panthers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201709100sfo.htm|title=Carolina Panthers at San Francisco 49ers - September 10th, 2017|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=October 7, 2017}}</ref> On November 12, 2017, against the New York Giants, he caught his first touchdown of the season on an 83-yard reception.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201711120sfo.htm |title=New York Giants at San Francisco 49ers - November 12th, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 30, 2018}}</ref> After beating one defender, Goodwin blew a kiss to the sky and once in the end zone, then took a knee in prayer before falling to both knees with his head in hands, as his teammates gathered around him. After the game, in which the 49ers beat the New York Giants for their first win of the season, Goodwin revealed that he and his wife had lost their prematurely born son due to complications during pregnancy in the early morning hours the day of the game.<ref>{{cite web|title=Marquise Goodwin Plays In 49ers' Win; Afterward He Says, 'We Lost Our Baby Boy'|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2017/11/13/563717061/marquise-goodwin-plays-in-49ers-win-afterwards-he-says-we-lost-our-baby-boy|website=NPR.org|accessdate=November 15, 2017|date=November 13, 2017}}</ref> In Week 15, Goodwin caught a career-high 10 passes for 114 yards in a 25-23 win over the Titans.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201712170sfo.htm |title=Tennessee Titans at San Francisco 49ers - December 17th, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 30, 2018}}</ref> Goodwin established new career highs in receptions and receiving yards in his first season with the 49ers, finishing the season with 56 catches for 962 yards and two touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/G/GoodMa00/gamelog/2017/ |title=Marquise Goodwin 2017 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn March 8, 2018, Goodwin signed a three-year, $20.3 million contract extension with the 49ers that will last through the 2021 season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000920216/article/niners-sign-marquise-goodwin-to-threeyear-extension |title=Niners sign Marquise Goodwin to three-year extension |last=Wesseling |first=Chris |date=March 8, 2018 |website=NFL.com}}</ref>\n\nIn Week 6, against the [[2018 Green Bay Packers|Green Bay Packers]], Goodwin set career-highs with 126 yards and two touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000974874/article/rodgers-works-magic-again-in-packers-comeback-win |title=Rodgers works magic again in Packers' comeback win |last=Bergman |first=Jeremy |website=NFL.com |language=en |access-date=December 5, 2018}}</ref> In the 2018 season, he finished with 23 receptions for 395 yards and four touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/G/GoodMa00/gamelog/2018/ |title=Marquise Goodwin 2018 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Goodwin played in nine games before being placed on injured reserve on December 10, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|title=49ers Announce Roster Moves|url=https://www.49ers.com/news/marquise-goodwin-49ers-injured-reserve|website=49ers.com|date=December 10, 2019}}</ref> He finished the season with 12 receptions for 186 yards and a touchdown. Without Goodwin, the 49ers reached [[Super Bowl LIV]], but lost 31-20 to the [[2019 Kansas City Chiefs season|Kansas City Chiefs]].\n\n===NFL statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; width:50%\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Team\n! colspan=\"2\" | Games\n! colspan=\"5\" | Receiving\n! colspan=\"5\" | Rushing\n! colspan=\"2\" | Fumbles\n|-\n! GP !! GS !! Rec !! Yds !! Avg !! Lng !! TD !! Att !! Yds !! Avg !! Lng !! TD !! FUM !! Lost\n|-\n! [[2013 NFL season|2013]] !! [[2013 Buffalo Bills season|BUF]]\n|| 12 || 1 || 17 || 283 || 16.6 || 59T || 3 || 3 || 13 || 4.3 || 17 || 0 || '''1''' || '''1'''\n|-\n! [[2014 NFL season|2014]] !! [[2014 Buffalo Bills season|BUF]]\n|| 10 || 0 || 1 || 42 || '''42.0''' || 42 || 0 || 3 || 8 || 2.7 || 12 || 0 || '''1''' || 0\n|-\n! [[2015 NFL season|2015]] !! [[2015 Buffalo Bills season|BUF]]\n|| 2 || 0 || 2 || 24 || 12.0 || 14 || 0 || -- || -- || -- || -- || -- || -- || --\n|-\n! [[2016 NFL season|2016]] !! [[2016 Buffalo Bills season|BUF]]\n|| 15 || '''9''' || 29 || 431 || 14.9 || '''84T''' || 3 || -- || -- || -- || -- || -- || -- || --\n|-\n! [[2017 NFL season|2017]] !! [[2017 San Francisco 49ers season|SF]]\n|| '''16''' || 6 || '''56''' || '''962''' || 17.2 || 83T || 2 || '''4''' || '''44''' || '''11.0''' || '''18''' || 0 || -- || --\n|-\n! [[2018 NFL season|2018]] !! [[2018 San Francisco 49ers season|SF]]\n|| 11 || 8 || 23 || 395 || 17.2 || 67T || '''4''' || 4 || 9 || 2.3 || 5 || 0 || '''1''' || 0\n|-\n! [[2019 NFL season|2019]] !! [[2019 San Francisco 49ers season|SF]]\n|| 9 || 6 || 12 || 186 || 15.5 || 38T || 1 || 1 || 15 || 15.0 || 15 || 0 || -- || --\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | Career !! 75 !! 40 !! 140 !! 2,323 !! 16.6 !! 84 !! 13 !! 15 !! 89 !! 5.9 !! 18 !! 0 !! 3 !! 1\n|-\n| colspan=\"16\" | Stats at [[NFL.com]]\n|}\n\n==Track career==\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name = Marquise Goodwin\n| nationality = [[Americans|American]]\n| sport = [[Track and Field]]\n| image = Marquise Goodwin 2012 Olympics.jpg\n| image_size =\n| caption = Goodwin at the [[2012 Olympic Games]]\n| event = [[Long Jump]], [[60m]], [[100m]], [[200m]], [[4x100]], [[Triple Jump]]\n| collegeteam = [[University of Texas]]\n| height = {{convert|5|ft|9|in|m|2|abbr=on}}\n| weight = {{convert|192|lb|kg|abbr=on}}\n| country = {{flagicon|USA}} [[United States national athletics team|United States]]\n| pb = \n*'''Long Jump''': 8.45m, (Guadeloupe 2016)\n*'''60m''': 6.67s, (Portland Convention Center 2016)\n*'''100m''': 10.24ws (10.24w), (Austin, TX 2009)\n*'''200m''': 21.24s, (Austin, TX 2009)\n*'''Triple Jump''': 15.38m, (Austin, TX 2009)\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[Athletics (sport)|athletics]]}}\n{{MedalCountry |the {{USA}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Summer Universiade]]}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[2011 Summer Universiade|2011 Shenzhen]] | [[Athletics at the 2011 Summer Universiade|Long Jump]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[IAAF World Junior Championships in Athletics|World Junior Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold |[[2008 World Junior Championships in Athletics|2008 Bydgoszcz]]|Long Jump}}\n{{MedalGold |[[2008 World Junior Championships in Athletics|2008 Bydgoszcz]]|4x100m}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Pan American Games]]}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[2015 Pan American Games|2015 Toronto]] | [[Athletics at the 2015 Pan American Games \u2013 Men's long jump|Long Jump]]}}\n}}\n\nGoodwin made the 2012 United States Olympic team in the [[long jump]] with a career-best and meet-best mark of 8.33m (27-04.25) at the [[2012 United States Olympic Trials (track and field)|US Olympic Team Trials]], a jump that would have been good enough to win the gold medal at the following Olympics.\n\nAt the [[2012 Summer Olympics]], he qualified for the finals on his first jump of 8.11m (26-7), but he failed to match that performance in the finals and finished in 10th place.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.burntorangenation.com/2012/8/4/3220327/marquise-goodwin-falls-short-in-olympic-long-jump-finals |title=Marquise Goodwin Falls Short In Olympic Long Jump Finals |last=Eberts |first=Wescott |date=2012-08-04 |website=Burnt Orange Nation |access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, after a three-year absence, he returned to track and field. In his first event back, despite jumping a career best 8.37m (27-05.5), he finished in fourth place, just missing qualification for the [[2015 World Championships in Athletics|World Championship]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2015/06/26/marquise-goodwin-finishes-fourth-in-long-jump-at-u-s-championships/ |title=Marquise Goodwin finishes fourth in long jump at U.S. championships |last=Alper |first=Josh |date=June 26, 2015 |website=NBC Sports |access-date=July 23, 2015}}</ref> A month later, at the [[Athletics at the 2015 Pan American Games|2015 Pan Am Games]], he earned a silver medal with a jump of 8.27m (27-1)<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/extra/panamgames/story/_/id/13304231/2015-pan-games-marquise-goodwin-happy-surreal-silver-medal-long-jump |title=Marquise Goodwin happy with 'surreal' silver medal |last=Capel |first=Jim |date=July 22, 2015 |website=ESPN |access-date=July 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Goodwin won the long jump at the Rod McCravy Invitational in Kentucky and placed third in the [[Millrose Games]] in New York. In New York he also placed 6th in the 60m dash, with a then career best 6.68s.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Casey|first1=Tim|title=EVEN AFTER ACHIEVING HIS NFL DREAM, MARQUISE GOODWIN STILL HAS OLYMPIC Hopes|url=https://sports.vice.com/en_us/article/even-after-achieving-his-nfl-dream-marquise-goodwin-still-has-olympic-hopes|accessdate=July 10, 2016|date=March 2, 2016}}</ref> In March, he placed third at the [[2016 USA Indoor Track and Field Championships|United States Indoor Track and Field Championships]] while also making it to the semifinals in the 60-meter dash with another personal best.<ref>{{cite web|title=2016 USA Indoor Track & Field Championships Final Results|url=http://www.usatf.org/Events---Calendar/2016/USATF-Indoor-Track---Field-Championships/Results/Day-2.aspx|website=usatf.org|accessdate=July 10, 2016}}</ref> He won the long jump at the Meeting Region Guadeloupe with a personal best mark of {{T&Fcalc|8.45}}, also a world-leading mark at the time of the meet.<ref>{{cite web|title=Goodwin soars to 8.45m long jump in Guadeloupe|url=http://www.iaaf.org/news/report/marquise-goodwin-guadeloupe-international-201|website=IAAF|accessdate=May 17, 2016}}</ref> As of 2017, his personal best ranks him as the 43rd best long jumper of all time.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.iaaf.org/records/all-time-toplists/jumps/long-jump/outdoor/men/senior |title=Long Jump - men - senior - outdoor |website=www.iaaf.org |access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref>  Then a month later, he won the long jump at the [[2016 IAAF Diamond League|IAAF Diamond League]] meet in [[Birmingham]], England.<ref>{{cite web|title=IAAF Diamond League Birmingham 2016 Results|url=https://www.diamondleague.com/fileadmin/IDL_Default/files/documents/2016/MeetDocs/Birmingham/Results.pdf|accessdate=July 10, 2016}}</ref> However, his dream of returning to the Olympics came up short when he finished a disappointing seventh at the [[2016 United States Olympic Trials (track and field)|Olympic Trials]] in July. His best jump of 8.25m was well below his best jumps of the year, which would have been enough to qualify.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Young|first1=Shalise Manza|title=Bills' Marquise Goodwin falls short at Olympic trials|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/bills-marquise-goodwin-falls-short-at-olympic-trials-190755219.html|accessdate=July 10, 2016|date=July 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nGoodwin is married to former Longhorn hurdler champion [[Morgan Snow|Morgan Goodwin-Snow]]. On November 12, 2017, their premature son died just hours prior to the 49ers' game against the [[2017 New York Giants season|New York Giants]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wagner-McGough|first1=Sean|title=Marquise Goodwin suffers tragedy hours before scoring 83-yard TD in 49ers' first win|url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/marquise-goodwin-suffers-tragedy-hours-before-scoring-83-yard-td-in-49ers-first-win/|accessdate=November 13, 2017|work=[[CBSSports.com]]|date=November 12, 2017|language=en}}</ref> In November 2018, Goodwin missed two games when he and his wife lost their unborn twin boys.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wagoner |first1=Nick |title=Goodwin family opens up on loss of unborn twins |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/25778949/marquise-goodwin-morgan-goodwin-snow-discuss-loss-unborn-twin-boys |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=January 17, 2019}}</ref> Goodwin is a cousin of former [[San Francisco 49ers]] teammate, [[Adrian Colbert]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2017/11/14/49ers-marquise-goodwin-appreciates-flood-of-support/ |title=49ers\u2019 Marquise Goodwin appreciates flood of support |date=2017-11-14 |website=The Mercury News |language=en-US |access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130501235836/http://www.buffalobills.com/team/roster/marquise-goodwin/56d0fa9a-296f-4c64-a3cd-5115720e35a2/ Buffalo Bills bio]\n*{{iaaf name|id=236127}}\n*[[DyeStat]] profile for [http://dyestat.rise.espn.go.com/search.jsp?athID=47090 Marquise Goodwin]{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n*[http://www.texassports.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=3710 Texas Longhorns football bio]\n*[https://twitter.com/flashg88dwin Marquise Goodwin's Twitter]\n\n{{San Francisco 49ers roster navbox}}\n{{Navboxes|list=\n{{ESPNRISE 2000s All-Decade track team}}\n{{Footer USA Track & Field 2012 Summer Olympics}}\n{{Footer US NC long jump Men}}\n{{Bills2013DraftPicks}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Goodwin, Marquise}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American male track and field athletes]]\n[[Category:African-American players of American football]]\n[[Category:American football wide receivers]]\n[[Category:American male long jumpers]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2012 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2015 Pan American Games]]\n[[Category:Buffalo Bills players]]\n[[Category:Olympic track and field athletes of the United States]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games medalists in athletics (track and field)]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games silver medalists for the United States]]\n[[Category:People from Garland, Texas]]\n[[Category:People from Rowlett, Texas]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Texas]]\n[[Category:San Francisco 49ers players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from the Dallas\u2013Fort Worth metroplex]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Lubbock, Texas]]\n[[Category:Texas Longhorns football players]]\n[[Category:Texas Longhorns men's track and field athletes]]\n[[Category:Track and field athletes from Texas]]\n[[Category:Track and field athletes in the National Football League]]\n[[Category:Universiade medalists in athletics (track and field)]]\n[[Category:Universiade silver medalists for the United States]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 2011 Summer Universiade]]\n[[Category:USA Outdoor Track and Field Championships winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football wide receiver and kick returner}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name          = Marquise Goodwin\n| image         = Goodwin 2018 (cropped).jpg\n| image_size    = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = Goodwin with the 49ers in 2018\n| current_team  = San Francisco 49ers \n| number        = 11 \n| position      = [[Wide receiver]]\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1990|11|19|mf=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Lubbock, Texas]]\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   =\n| height_ft     = 5\n| height_in     = 9\n| weight_lbs    = 185\n| high_school   = [[Rowlett High School|Rowlett]] ([[Rowlett, Texas]])\n| college       = [[Texas Longhorns football|Texas]]\n| draftyear     = 2013\n| draftround    = 3\n| draftpick     = 78\n| pastteams     = \n* [[Buffalo Bills]] ({{NFL Year|2013}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2016}})\n* [[San Francisco 49ers]] ({{NFL Year|2017}}\u2013present)\n| status        = Active\n| highlights    =\n| statweek      = \n| statseason    = 2019\n| statlabel1    = [[Reception (American football)|Receptions]]\n| statvalue1    = 140\n| statlabel2    = [[Receiving yards]]\n| statvalue2    = 2,323\n| statlabel3    = [[Return yards]]\n| statvalue3    = 468\n| statlabel4    = [[Rushing yards]]\n| statvalue4    = 89\n| statlabel5    = [[Touchdown|Total touchdowns]]\n| statvalue5    = 13\n| nflnew        = marquisegoodwin/2539964\n}}\n\n'''Marquise Derell Goodwin''' (born November 19, 1990) is an [[American football]] [[wide receiver]] and [[kick returner]] for the [[San Francisco 49ers]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL) and an [[Olympic Games|Olympian]] who competed in the long jump in track and field. He was drafted by the [[Buffalo Bills]] in the third round with the 78th pick of the [[2013 NFL Draft]]. He played [[college football]] at [[Texas Longhorns football|Texas]].\n\nIn [[track and field]], his specialty is the [[long jump]], an event in which he won two national college championships. Goodwin represented the United States at the 2008 IAAF World junior championships, the 2011 World University games, the 2011 IAAF World Championships, the [[2012 Summer Olympics]], and the [[2015 Pan American Games]], where he won silver. He has competed as a long jumper and sprinter, and has been a top competitor in the [[60 meters]] and [[100 meters]] dashes, and the [[triple jump]].\n\n==Early years==\nGoodwin was born in [[Lubbock, Texas]]. He attended [[Rowlett High School]] in [[Rowlett, Texas]], and played [[high school football]] and competed in track and field for the Rowlett Eagles.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://sportsday.dallasnews.com/high-school/high-schools/2017/05/11/flashback-marquise-goodwin-burned-defenders-nfl-blew-people-away-track-rowlett |title=Flashback: Before Marquise Goodwin burned defenders in the NFL, he blew people away on the track for Rowlett |date=May 11, 2017 |website=SportsDayHS |language=en |access-date=April 30, 2018}}</ref> He had the second fastest 100-meter time (10.24w) in the state, was the state champion in the triple jump and long jump, and was a member of the state title-winning [[4 x 100 metres relay|4\u00d7100-meter relay]] team.<ref>[http://insider.espn.go.com/ncf/recruiting/tracker/player?recruitId=55073&action=login&appRedirect=http%3a%2f%2finsider.espn.go.com%2fncf%2frecruiting%2ftracker%2fplayer%3frecruitId%3d55073 College football recruiting: Marquise Goodwin] ESPN</ref>  He won seven Texas Class 5A state track and field championships while he was at Rowlett. He also finished first in the long jump at the [[2008 World Junior Championships in Athletics]] in [[Bydgoszcz]], [[Poland]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.burntorangenation.com/2009/1/16/724914/recruiting-spotlight-marqu |title=Recruiting Spotlight: Marquise Goodwin |last=Eberts |first=Wescott |date=2009-01-16 |website=Burnt Orange Nation |access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref> and first again at the 2008 and 2009 United States Junior Championships. At the 2009 [[USA Outdoor Track and Field Championships]], Goodwin set the national high school record in the long jump and placed fifth ({{convert|8.18|m|ftin|abbr=off|sp=us|disp=x|; }}).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://texassports.com/news/2009/6/27/062809aab_430.aspx |title=Future Longhorn Marquise Goodwin sets national high school record in long jump at U.S. Championships |website=University of Texas Athletics |language=en |access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref><ref>http://www.iaaf.org/WJC08/news/kind=100/newsid=45869.html</ref><ref>Jack Pfeifer [http://usa.milesplit.us/articles/24169 Marquise Goodwin jumps 26-10 for national high school record] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120729230802/http://usa.milesplit.us/articles/24169# |date=July 29, 2012 }} June 28, 2009 MileSplit.us</ref>\n\nIn his high school career, he caught 132 passes for 1,709 yards (12.95 average) and 17 touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.texassports.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/goodwin_marquise00.html |title=Marquise Goodwin Profile |date=2019-07-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120616091444/http://www.texassports.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/goodwin_marquise00.html |archive-date=June 16, 2012 |url-status=dead |access-date=August 6, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nGoodwin received an athletic scholarship to attend the [[University of Texas at Austin]], where he pledged [[Kappa Alpha Psi]] fraternity.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://nphcnews.com/kap/kappa-alpha-psis-colin-kaepernick-and-marquise-goodwin-explore-egypt/ |title=Kappa Alpha Psi\u2019s Colin Kaepernick and Marquise Goodwin Explore Egypt |date=July 5, 2017 |work=NPHC News |access-date=April 30, 2018 |language=en-US |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170925032008/http://nphcnews.com/kap/kappa-alpha-psis-colin-kaepernick-and-marquise-goodwin-explore-egypt/ |archive-date=September 25, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He played for coach [[Mack Brown]]'s [[Texas Longhorns football]] team from 2009 to 2012, and also competed for the Texas Longhorns track and field team from 2010 to 2012.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://texassports.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=2872 |title=Marquise Goodwin - Track & Field / Cross Country m |website=University of Texas Athletics |language=en |access-date=December 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===College track and field===\nGoodwin was a two-time NCAA champion in the long jump (2010, 2012) and a four-time All-American in track and field. He won five Big 12 Conference championships and made the All-Big 12 team seven times. He is the Longhorns' indoor record holder in the long jump and was the runner-up for the 2012 NCAA Indoor long jump title.\n\nHe won the [[2011 USA Outdoor Track and Field Championships|2011 U.S. Outdoor Track and Field]] long jump title with a personal-best {{convert|27|ft|4|in|m|abbr=off|sp=us}} and won the [[2012 United States Olympic Trials (track and field)|2012 Outdoor Championship/Olympic Trials]] with the same distance. He competed in the [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's long jump|2012 Olympics]], ranking tied for the #1 qualifier, but only managed 10th place in the final.\n\nHe chose not to compete in the 2013 NCAA track and field seasons in indoor or outdoor.\n\n===College football===\nIn his collegiate career, Goodwin started 21 of the 49 games in which he appeared, including the [[2010 BCS National Championship Game]] against [[2009 Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2010-01-07-alabama.html |title=BCS Championship - Texas vs Alabama Box Score, January 7, 2010 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 30, 2018}}</ref> His final career statistics included 116 receptions for 1,296 yards and six touchdowns, rushed 46 times for 405 yards and 44 kickoff returns for 985 yards and one touchdown. He also returned a punt for 22 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/marquise-goodwin-1/gamelog/2009 |title=Marquise Goodwin 2009 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 3, 2019}}</ref> Some of his key plays include his first touchdown of his 2009 freshman year, a game-winning touchdown in a 16-13 victory over the [[2009 Oklahoma Sooners football|Oklahoma Sooners]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2009-10-17-oklahoma.html |title=Texas vs Oklahoma Box Score, October 17, 2009 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 30, 2018}}</ref>  Goodwin also returned a kickoff 95 yards for a touchdown to seal the Longhorns' win over the [[2009 Texas A&M Aggies football|Texas A&M Aggies]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2009-11-26-texas-am.html |title=Texas at Texas A&M Box Score, November 26, 2009 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2010 season, Goodwin had 31 receptions for 324 yards and one touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/marquise-goodwin-1/gamelog/2010 |title=Marquise Goodwin 2010 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 3, 2019}}</ref> In the 2011 season, he had 33 receptions for 421 yards and two touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/marquise-goodwin-1/gamelog/2011 |title=Marquise Goodwin 2011 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 3, 2019}}</ref> In the 2012 season, Goodwin was named a semifinalist for the [[William V. Campbell Trophy|Campbell Trophy]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://texassports.com/news/2012/9/27/092712aac_503.aspx |title=Goodwin a Semifinalist for Campbell Trophy |website=University of Texas Athletics |language=en |access-date=December 5, 2018}}</ref> In the [[2012 Alamo Bowl]] against [[2012 Oregon State Beavers football|Oregon State]], Goodwin rushed for a 64-yard touchdown, and caught the game-winning, 36-yard touchdown pass\u2014an effort that was good enough to earn him the game's Offensive Most Valuable Player trophy.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2012-12-29-oregon-state.html |title=Alamo Bowl - Texas vs Oregon State Box Score, December 29, 2012 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 30, 2018}}</ref> In the 2012 season, he had 26 receptions for 340 receiving yards and three receiving touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/marquise-goodwin-1/gamelog/2012 |title=Marquise Goodwin 2012 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\nGoodwin went on to compete in the 2013 [[NFLPA Collegiate Bowl]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sbnation.com/2013-nfl-draft/2013/1/10/3863496/2013-nfl-draft-nflpa-collegiate-bowl-roster-marquise-goodwin |title=NFLPA Collegiate Bowl rosters |last=Arthur |first=Kenneth |date=January 10, 2013 |website=SBNation.com |access-date=December 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Collegiate statistics====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"6\" style=\"{{CollegePrimaryStyle|Texas Longhorns|color=white}}\" | Marquise Goodwin\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align: center;\" | Receiving\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align: center;\" | Rushing\n|-\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | Year\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | School\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | Conf\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | Class\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | Pos\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | G\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | Rec\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | Yds\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | Avg\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | TD\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | Att\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | Yds\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | Avg\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | TD\n|-\n| [[2009 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2009]]\n| [[2009 Texas Longhorns football team|Texas]]\n| [[2009 Big 12 Conference football season|Big 12]]\n| FR\n| WR\n| 14\n| 30\n| 279\n| 9.3\n| 1\n| 2\n| 8\n| 4.0\n| 0\n|-\n| [[2010 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2010]]\n| [[2010 Texas Longhorns football team|Texas]]\n| [[2010 Big 12 Conference football season|Big 12]]\n| SO\n| WR\n| 11\n| 31\n| 324\n| 10.5\n| 1\n| 9\n| 37\n| 4.1\n| 0\n|-\n| [[2011 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2011]]\n| [[2011 Texas Longhorns football team|Texas]]\n| [[2011 Big 12 Conference football season|Big 12]]\n| JR\n| WR\n| 12\n| 33\n| 421\n| 12.8\n| 2\n| 22\n| 220\n| 10.0\n| 0\n|-\n| [[2012 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2012]]\n| [[2012 Texas Longhorns football team|Texas]]\n| [[2012 Big 12 Conference football season|Big 12]]\n| SR\n| WR\n| 13\n| 26\n| 340\n| 13.1\n| 3\n| 13\n| 140\n| 10.8\n| 3\n|-\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | Career\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | Texas\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | \n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | 120\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | 1,364\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | 11.4\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | 7\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | 46\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | 405\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | 8.8\n| style=\"font-weight:bold;\" | 3\n|}\n\n==Professional career==\n{{nfl predraft\n|    height ft = 5\n|    height in = 8\u215e\n|       weight = 183\n|         dash = 4.27<ref>http://bleacherreport.com/articles/1543885-nfl-combine-2013-15-fastest-40-yard-dash-times-for-wide-receivers</ref>\n|    ten split = 1.50\n| twenty split = 2.41\n|      shuttle = 4.09\n|   cone drill = 6.66\n|     vertical = 42\n|     broad ft = 11\n|     broad in = 0\n|        bench = 13\n|    wonderlic = \n|     arm span = 31\u00bd\n|    hand span = 8\u215d\n|         note = All values from [[NFL Combine]].<ref>http://www.nfldraftscout.com/ratings/dsprofile.php?pyid=90106&draftyear=2013&genpos=WR</ref>\n}}\n\nAfter posting the third-fastest 40-yard dash time ever at the NFL scouting combine, Goodwin was drafted by the [[Buffalo Bills]] in the third round, with the 78th overall pick, of the [[2013 NFL Draft]].<ref>http://collegesportsblog.dallasnews.com/2013/04/former-texas-longhorn-marquise-goodwin-drafted-by-buffalo-bills-in-third-round.html/</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2013/draft.htm |title=2013 NFL Draft Listing |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Buffalo Bills===\nOn May 10, 2013, Goodwin signed a four-year contract with the Bills, where he also practiced in his first day of rookie minicamp.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2013/05/10/bills-sign-marquise-goodwin-dustin-hopkins-two-other-draft-picks/ |title=Bills sign Marquise Goodwin, Dustin Hopkins, two other draft picks |date=2013-05-10 |website=ProFootballTalk |language=en |access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref> He caught his first career [[touchdown]] Week 6 against the [[Cincinnati Bengals]], a 40-yard pass from [[Thaddeus Lewis]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201310130buf.htm |title=Cincinnati Bengals at San Francisco - October 13th, 2013 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 30, 2018}}</ref> Goodwin played 12 games in his rookie season making 17 receptions for 283 receiving yards. He also had 16 kickoff return opportunities totaling 351 returning yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/G/GoodMa00/gamelog/2013/ |title=Marquise Goodwin 2013 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, hobbled by numerous injuries (concussion, ankle, ribs, and hamstring), Goodwin caught only one pass for 42 yards, which came against the Detroit Lions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.syracuse.com/buffalo-bills/2014/10/buffalo_bills_injury_report_marquise_goodwin.html |title=Buffalo Bills injury report: Marquise Goodwin limited by hamstring Thursday |last=Fairburn |first=Matthew |date=2014-10-16 |website=syracuse.com |language=en-US |access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201410050det.htm |title=San Francisco at Detroit Lions - October 5th, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 30, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/G/GoodMa00/gamelog/2014/ |title=Marquise Goodwin 2014 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter missing five games with broken ribs, Goodwin posted two receptions for 24 yards in the 2015 season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/G/GoodMa00/gamelog/2015/ |title=Marquise Goodwin 2015 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Goodwin posted 29 receptions, 431 yards, and three touchdowns, setting career highs in games played, receptions, and receiving yards. While Goodwin enjoyed his most productive season, he was also inconsistent.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/G/GoodMa00/gamelog/2016/ |title=Marquise Goodwin 2016 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref> His 42.6% catch rate ranked 107th among qualified NFL wide receivers in 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.playerprofiler.com/nfl/marquise-goodwin|title=Marquise Goodwin Advanced Stats and Metrics Profile: Catch Rate|work=PlayerProfiler.com}}</ref>\n\n===San Francisco 49ers===\n[[File:Marquise Goodwin with the 49ers in 2018.jpg|thumb|Marquise Goodwin wears a fan's jersey before a 49ers home game]]\nOn March 9, 2017, Goodwin signed a two-year contract with the [[San Francisco 49ers]].<ref>{{cite web|title=49ers Agree to Terms with Seven Free Agents|url=http://www.49ers.com/news/article-2/49ers-Agree-to-Terms-with-Seven-Free-Agents/27ef0da5-47b8-4a0f-96d5-d6c61d929fb6|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171214161411/http://www.49ers.com/news/article-2/49ers-Agree-to-Terms-with-Seven-Free-Agents/27ef0da5-47b8-4a0f-96d5-d6c61d929fb6|url-status=dead|archive-date=December 14, 2017|website=49ers.com|date=March 9, 2017}}</ref> On September 10, 2017, in his 49ers debut, Goodwin had three receptions for 21 yards in the season opening 23\u20133 loss to the [[2017 Carolina Panthers season|Carolina Panthers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201709100sfo.htm|title=Carolina Panthers at San Francisco 49ers - September 10th, 2017|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=October 7, 2017}}</ref> On November 12, 2017, against the New York Giants, he caught his first touchdown of the season on an 83-yard reception.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201711120sfo.htm |title=New York Giants at San Francisco 49ers - November 12th, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 30, 2018}}</ref> After beating one defender, Goodwin blew a kiss to the sky and once in the end zone, then took a knee in prayer before falling to both knees with his head in hands, as his teammates gathered around him. After the game, in which the 49ers beat the New York Giants for their first win of the season, Goodwin revealed that he and his wife had lost their prematurely born son due to complications during pregnancy in the early morning hours the day of the game.<ref>{{cite web|title=Marquise Goodwin Plays In 49ers' Win; Afterward He Says, 'We Lost Our Baby Boy'|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2017/11/13/563717061/marquise-goodwin-plays-in-49ers-win-afterwards-he-says-we-lost-our-baby-boy|website=NPR.org|accessdate=November 15, 2017|date=November 13, 2017}}</ref> In Week 15, Goodwin caught a career-high 10 passes for 114 yards in a 25-23 win over the Titans.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201712170sfo.htm |title=Tennessee Titans at San Francisco 49ers - December 17th, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 30, 2018}}</ref> Goodwin established new career highs in receptions and receiving yards in his first season with the 49ers, finishing the season with 56 catches for 962 yards and two touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/G/GoodMa00/gamelog/2017/ |title=Marquise Goodwin 2017 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn March 8, 2018, Goodwin signed a three-year, $20.3 million contract extension with the 49ers that will last through the 2021 season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000920216/article/niners-sign-marquise-goodwin-to-threeyear-extension |title=Niners sign Marquise Goodwin to three-year extension |last=Wesseling |first=Chris |date=March 8, 2018 |website=NFL.com}}</ref>\n\nIn Week 6, against the [[2018 Green Bay Packers|Green Bay Packers]], Goodwin set career-highs with 126 yards and two touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000974874/article/rodgers-works-magic-again-in-packers-comeback-win |title=Rodgers works magic again in Packers' comeback win |last=Bergman |first=Jeremy |website=NFL.com |language=en |access-date=December 5, 2018}}</ref> In the 2018 season, he finished with 23 receptions for 395 yards and four touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/G/GoodMa00/gamelog/2018/ |title=Marquise Goodwin 2018 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Goodwin played in nine games before being placed on injured reserve on December 10, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|title=49ers Announce Roster Moves|url=https://www.49ers.com/news/marquise-goodwin-49ers-injured-reserve|website=49ers.com|date=December 10, 2019}}</ref> He finished the season with 12 receptions for 186 yards and a touchdown. Without Goodwin, the 49ers reached [[Super Bowl LIV]], but lost 31-20 to the [[2019 Kansas City Chiefs season|Kansas City Chiefs]].\n\n===NFL statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; width:50%\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Team\n! colspan=\"2\" | Games\n! colspan=\"5\" | Receiving\n! colspan=\"5\" | Rushing\n! colspan=\"2\" | Fumbles\n|-\n! GP !! GS !! Rec !! Yds !! Avg !! Lng !! TD !! Att !! Yds !! Avg !! Lng !! TD !! FUM !! Lost\n|-\n! [[2013 NFL season|2013]] !! [[2013 Buffalo Bills season|BUF]]\n|| 12 || 1 || 17 || 283 || 16.6 || 59T || 3 || 3 || 13 || 4.3 || 17 || 0 || '''1''' || '''1'''\n|-\n! [[2014 NFL season|2014]] !! [[2014 Buffalo Bills season|BUF]]\n|| 10 || 0 || 1 || 42 || '''42.0''' || 42 || 0 || 3 || 8 || 2.7 || 12 || 0 || '''1''' || 0\n|-\n! [[2015 NFL season|2015]] !! [[2015 Buffalo Bills season|BUF]]\n|| 2 || 0 || 2 || 24 || 12.0 || 14 || 0 || -- || -- || -- || -- || -- || -- || --\n|-\n! [[2016 NFL season|2016]] !! [[2016 Buffalo Bills season|BUF]]\n|| 15 || '''9''' || 29 || 431 || 14.9 || '''84T''' || 3 || -- || -- || -- || -- || -- || -- || --\n|-\n! [[2017 NFL season|2017]] !! [[2017 San Francisco 49ers season|SF]]\n|| '''16''' || 6 || '''56''' || '''962''' || 17.2 || 83T || 2 || '''4''' || '''44''' || '''11.0''' || '''18''' || 0 || -- || --\n|-\n! [[2018 NFL season|2018]] !! [[2018 San Francisco 49ers season|SF]]\n|| 11 || 8 || 23 || 395 || 17.2 || 67T || '''4''' || 4 || 9 || 2.3 || 5 || 0 || '''1''' || 0\n|-\n! [[2019 NFL season|2019]] !! [[2019 San Francisco 49ers season|SF]]\n|| 9 || 6 || 12 || 186 || 15.5 || 38T || 1 || 1 || 15 || 15.0 || 15 || 0 || -- || --\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | Career !! 75 !! 40 !! 140 !! 2,323 !! 16.6 !! 84 !! 13 !! 15 !! 89 !! 5.9 !! 18 !! 0 !! 3 !! 1\n|-\n| colspan=\"16\" | Stats at [[NFL.com]]\n|}\n\n==Track career==\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name = Marquise Goodwin\n| nationality = [[Americans|American]]\n| sport = [[Track and Field]]\n| image = Marquise Goodwin 2012 Olympics.jpg\n| image_size =\n| caption = Goodwin at the [[2012 Olympic Games]]\n| event = [[Long Jump]], [[60m]], [[100m]], [[200m]], [[4x100]], [[Triple Jump]]\n| collegeteam = [[University of Texas]]\n| height = {{convert|5|ft|9|in|m|2|abbr=on}}\n| weight = {{convert|192|lb|kg|abbr=on}}\n| country = {{flagicon|USA}} [[United States national athletics team|United States]]\n| pb = \n*'''Long Jump''': 8.45m, (Guadeloupe 2016)\n*'''60m''': 6.67s, (Portland Convention Center 2016)\n*'''100m''': 10.24ws (10.24w), (Austin, TX 2009)\n*'''200m''': 21.24s, (Austin, TX 2009)\n*'''Triple Jump''': 15.38m, (Austin, TX 2009)\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[Athletics (sport)|athletics]]}}\n{{MedalCountry |the {{USA}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Summer Universiade]]}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[2011 Summer Universiade|2011 Shenzhen]] | [[Athletics at the 2011 Summer Universiade|Long Jump]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[IAAF World Junior Championships in Athletics|World Junior Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold |[[2008 World Junior Championships in Athletics|2008 Bydgoszcz]]|Long Jump}}\n{{MedalGold |[[2008 World Junior Championships in Athletics|2008 Bydgoszcz]]|4x100m}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Pan American Games]]}}\n{{MedalSilver| [[2015 Pan American Games|2015 Toronto]] | [[Athletics at the 2015 Pan American Games \u2013 Men's long jump|Long Jump]]}}\n}}\n\nGoodwin made the 2012 United States Olympic team in the [[long jump]] with a career-best and meet-best mark of 8.33m (27-04.25) at the [[2012 United States Olympic Trials (track and field)|US Olympic Team Trials]], a jump that would have been good enough to win the gold medal at the following Olympics.\n\nAt the [[2012 Summer Olympics]], he qualified for the finals on his first jump of 8.11m (26-7), but he failed to match that performance in the finals and finished in 10th place.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.burntorangenation.com/2012/8/4/3220327/marquise-goodwin-falls-short-in-olympic-long-jump-finals |title=Marquise Goodwin Falls Short In Olympic Long Jump Finals |last=Eberts |first=Wescott |date=2012-08-04 |website=Burnt Orange Nation |access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, after a three-year absence, he returned to track and field. In his first event back, despite jumping a career best 8.37m (27-05.5), he finished in fourth place, just missing qualification for the [[2015 World Championships in Athletics|World Championship]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2015/06/26/marquise-goodwin-finishes-fourth-in-long-jump-at-u-s-championships/ |title=Marquise Goodwin finishes fourth in long jump at U.S. championships |last=Alper |first=Josh |date=June 26, 2015 |website=NBC Sports |access-date=July 23, 2015}}</ref> A month later, at the [[Athletics at the 2015 Pan American Games|2015 Pan Am Games]], he earned a silver medal with a jump of 8.27m (27-1)<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/extra/panamgames/story/_/id/13304231/2015-pan-games-marquise-goodwin-happy-surreal-silver-medal-long-jump |title=Marquise Goodwin happy with 'surreal' silver medal |last=Capel |first=Jim |date=July 22, 2015 |website=ESPN |access-date=July 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Goodwin won the long jump at the Rod McCravy Invitational in Kentucky and placed third in the [[Millrose Games]] in New York. In New York he also placed 6th in the 60m dash, with a then career best 6.68s.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Casey|first1=Tim|title=EVEN AFTER ACHIEVING HIS NFL DREAM, MARQUISE GOODWIN STILL HAS OLYMPIC Hopes|url=https://sports.vice.com/en_us/article/even-after-achieving-his-nfl-dream-marquise-goodwin-still-has-olympic-hopes|accessdate=July 10, 2016|date=March 2, 2016}}</ref> In March, he placed third at the [[2016 USA Indoor Track and Field Championships|United States Indoor Track and Field Championships]] while also making it to the semifinals in the 60-meter dash with another personal best.<ref>{{cite web|title=2016 USA Indoor Track & Field Championships Final Results|url=http://www.usatf.org/Events---Calendar/2016/USATF-Indoor-Track---Field-Championships/Results/Day-2.aspx|website=usatf.org|accessdate=July 10, 2016}}</ref> He won the long jump at the Meeting Region Guadeloupe with a personal best mark of {{T&Fcalc|8.45}}, also a world-leading mark at the time of the meet.<ref>{{cite web|title=Goodwin soars to 8.45m long jump in Guadeloupe|url=http://www.iaaf.org/news/report/marquise-goodwin-guadeloupe-international-201|website=IAAF|accessdate=May 17, 2016}}</ref> As of 2017, his personal best ranks him as the 43rd best long jumper of all time.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.iaaf.org/records/all-time-toplists/jumps/long-jump/outdoor/men/senior |title=Long Jump - men - senior - outdoor |website=www.iaaf.org |access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref>  Then a month later, he won the long jump at the [[2016 IAAF Diamond League|IAAF Diamond League]] meet in [[Birmingham]], England.<ref>{{cite web|title=IAAF Diamond League Birmingham 2016 Results|url=https://www.diamondleague.com/fileadmin/IDL_Default/files/documents/2016/MeetDocs/Birmingham/Results.pdf|accessdate=July 10, 2016}}</ref> However, his dream of returning to the Olympics came up short when he finished a disappointing seventh at the [[2016 United States Olympic Trials (track and field)|Olympic Trials]] in July. His best jump of 8.25m was well below his best jumps of the year, which would have been enough to qualify.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Young|first1=Shalise Manza|title=Bills' Marquise Goodwin falls short at Olympic trials|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/bills-marquise-goodwin-falls-short-at-olympic-trials-190755219.html|accessdate=July 10, 2016|date=July 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nGoodwin is married to former Longhorn hurdler champion [[Morgan Snow|Morgan Goodwin-Snow]]. On November 12, 2017, their premature son died just hours prior to the 49ers' game against the [[2017 New York Giants season|New York Giants]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wagner-McGough|first1=Sean|title=Marquise Goodwin suffers tragedy hours before scoring 83-yard TD in 49ers' first win|url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/marquise-goodwin-suffers-tragedy-hours-before-scoring-83-yard-td-in-49ers-first-win/|accessdate=November 13, 2017|work=[[CBSSports.com]]|date=November 12, 2017|language=en}}</ref> In November 2018, Goodwin missed two games when he and his wife lost their unborn twin boys.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wagoner |first1=Nick |title=Goodwin family opens up on loss of unborn twins |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/25778949/marquise-goodwin-morgan-goodwin-snow-discuss-loss-unborn-twin-boys |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=January 17, 2019}}</ref> Goodwin is a cousin of former [[San Francisco 49ers]] teammate, [[Adrian Colbert]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2017/11/14/49ers-marquise-goodwin-appreciates-flood-of-support/ |title=49ers\u2019 Marquise Goodwin appreciates flood of support |date=2017-11-14 |website=The Mercury News |language=en-US |access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130501235836/http://www.buffalobills.com/team/roster/marquise-goodwin/56d0fa9a-296f-4c64-a3cd-5115720e35a2/ Buffalo Bills bio]\n*{{iaaf name|id=236127}}\n*[[DyeStat]] profile for [http://dyestat.rise.espn.go.com/search.jsp?athID=47090 Marquise Goodwin]{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n*[http://www.texassports.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=3710 Texas Longhorns football bio]\n*[https://twitter.com/flashg88dwin Marquise Goodwin's Twitter]\n\n{{San Francisco 49ers roster navbox}}\n{{Navboxes|list=\n{{ESPNRISE 2000s All-Decade track team}}\n{{Footer USA Track & Field 2012 Summer Olympics}}\n{{Footer US NC long jump Men}}\n{{Bills2013DraftPicks}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Goodwin, Marquise}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American male track and field athletes]]\n[[Category:African-American players of American football]]\n[[Category:American football wide receivers]]\n[[Category:American male long jumpers]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2012 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Athletes (track and field) at the 2015 Pan American Games]]\n[[Category:Buffalo Bills players]]\n[[Category:Olympic track and field athletes of the United States]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games medalists in athletics (track and field)]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games silver medalists for the United States]]\n[[Category:People from Garland, Texas]]\n[[Category:People from Rowlett, Texas]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Texas]]\n[[Category:San Francisco 49ers players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from the Dallas\u2013Fort Worth metroplex]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Lubbock, Texas]]\n[[Category:Texas Longhorns football players]]\n[[Category:Texas Longhorns men's track and field athletes]]\n[[Category:Track and field athletes from Texas]]\n[[Category:Track and field athletes in the National Football League]]\n[[Category:Universiade medalists in athletics (track and field)]]\n[[Category:Universiade silver medalists for the United States]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 2011 Summer Universiade]]\n[[Category:USA Outdoor Track and Field Championships winners]]\n", "name_user": "2601:5ca:180:340:8475:8210:d931:cda9", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marquise_Goodwin"}
{"title_page": "Central Eastside, Portland, Oregon", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n| name                    = Central Eastside\n| native_name             = \n| native_name_lang        = <!-- ISO 639-2 code e.g. \"fr\" for French. If more than one, use {{lang}} instead -->\n| settlement_type         = Subdistrict\n| image_skyline           = \n| image_size              = \n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = \n| image_flag              = \n| flag_alt                = \n| image_seal              = \n| seal_alt                = \n| image_shield            = \n| shield_alt              = \n| nickname                = \n| motto                   = \n| image_map               = \n| map_alt                 = \n| map_caption             = \n| pushpin_map             = USA Oregon Portland\n| pushpin_label_position  = \n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = \n| coordinates             = {{coord|45.515097|-122.660782|region:US-OR_type:city|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| coordinates_footnotes   = [http://www.portlandonline.com/shared/cfm/image.cfm?id=58593 PDF map]\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = [[United States]]\n| subdivision_type1       = State\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Oregon]]\n| subdivision_type2       = City\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]]\n| established_title       = \n| established_date        = \n| founder                 = \n| seat_type               = \n| seat                    = \n| leader_title1           = \n| leader_name1            = \n| leader_title2           = \n| leader_name2            = \n| government_footnotes    = \n| leader_party            = \n| leader_title            = \n| leader_name             = \n| unit_pref               = US\n<!-- ALL fields with measurements have automatic unit conversion -->\n<!-- for references: use <ref> tags -->\n| area_footnotes          = <ref>{{cite web |url=https://prosperportland.us/portfolio-items/central-eastside/ |title=Central Eastside |publisher=[[Prosper Portland]] |access-date=April 15, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200415180942/https://prosperportland.us/portfolio-items/central-eastside/ |archive-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n| area_total_km2          = \n| area_total_sq_mi        = 1.11\n| dimensions_footnotes    = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_ft            = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| population_total        = \n| population_as_of        = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_density_sq_mi = auto\n| population_demonym      = \n| population_note         = \n| demographics_type1      = \n| demographics1_footnotes = \n| demographics1_title1    = No. of households\n| demographics1_info1     = \n| demographics1_title2    = Occupancy rate\n| demographics1_info2     = \n| demographics1_title3    = {{nowrap|Owner-occupied}}\n| demographics1_info3     = \n| demographics1_title4    = Renting\n| demographics1_info4     = \n| demographics1_title5    = Avg. household size\n| demographics1_info5     = \n| timezone1               = \n| utc_offset1             = \n| timezone1_DST           = \n| utc_offset1_DST         = \n| postal_code_type        = \n| postal_code             = \n| area_code_type          = \n| area_code               = \n| iso_code                = \n| website                 = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| footnotes               = \n}}\n'''Central Eastside''' is a [[subdistrict]] in [[Portland, Oregon]], United States. It is situated in [[Neighborhoods of Portland, Oregon#Southeast|Southeast Portland]] along the east bank of the [[Willamette River]] and makes up a part of Portland's Central City district.\n\n==History==\n{{see also|East Portland, Oregon}}\n\nIn 1845, [[Oregon Trail]] pioneer [[James B. Stephens]] laid claim to {{convert|640|acre|ha}} of land situated directly across the [[Willamette River]] from the then-newly established [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]] townsite.<ref name=\"east-portland-1874\">{{cite web |url=https://oregonhistoryproject.org/articles/historical-records/east-portland-1874/ |title=East Portland, 1874 |publisher=[[Oregon Historical Society]] |access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref> The land had been controlled by [[John McLoughlin]] of the [[Hudson\u2019s Bay Company]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.opb.org/artsandlife/series/historical-photo/oregon-historical-photo-city-of-east-portland/ |last=Rosman |first=John |title=Oregon Historical Photo: The City Of East Portland |date=May 12, 2014 |publisher=[[Oregon Public Broadcasting]] |access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"forgotten-city\">{{cite web |url=http://visitahc.org/wp-content/uploads/Exhibit-booklet.pdf |title=East Portland: A Changing Landscape, A Forgotten City |publisher=Architectural Heritage Center |access-date=April 15, 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200415215652/http://visitahc.org/wp-content/uploads/Exhibit-booklet.pdf |archive-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref>{{rp|2}} The area consisted of [[orchard]]s and [[hay]], and its location along the east bank of the river\u2014with its [[marsh]]es, [[creek]]s, and [[Slough (hydrology)|slough]]s\u2014made development challenging.<ref name=\"guo-2014\">{{cite report |url=https://www.pdx.edu/sba/sites/www.pdx.edu.sba/files/01%20Central%20Eastside%20-%20Guo.pdf |last=Guo |first=Angela |title=The Evolution of Portland's Central Eastside |work=Center for Real Estate Quarterly Report |volume=8 |number=2 |publisher=[[Portland State University]] |date=2014 |access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref>{{rp|3}} Stephens established the Stark Street Ferry to link the east and west sides of the river in 1848. A mule on a treadmill powered the vessel's [[paddle wheel]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Terry |first=John |title=Hundreds of ferries once served Oregonians; now there are just three |date=Oct 15, 2011 |newspaper=[[The Oregonian]] |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/O/2011/10/hundreds_of_ferries_once_serve.html |access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref> On April{{nbsp}}16, 1868, the [[Oregon Central Railroad]] broke ground at the settlement, which by then was being referred to as [[East Portland, Oregon|East Portland]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.portlandoregon.gov/archives/article/12264 |title=1868 Invitation to railroad groundbreaking |publisher=City of Portland Archives and Records Management |access-date=April 15, 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200415213419/https://www.portlandoregon.gov/archives/article/12264 |archive-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref> The line extended from [[Salem, Oregon|Salem]] in the following year, helping to start the development of an industrial economy based on the shipment of agricultural products across the [[Willamette Valley]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://beta.portland.gov/sites/default/files/2020-01/portlands-central-eastside-2013.pdf |title=Portland Central Eastside |publisher=City of Portland Bureau of Planning and Sustainability |date=January 2020 |page=2 |access-date=April 15, 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200415190953/https://beta.portland.gov/sites/default/files/2020-01/portlands-central-eastside-2013.pdf |archive-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref> The railroad's presence led Stephens to incorporate the City of East Portland in 1870 with its population of 8,293.<ref name=\"forgotten-city\"/>{{rp|6}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.portlandoregon.gov/archives/article/284518 |title=Portland Historical Timeline: 1843 to 1901 |publisher=City of Portland Archives and Records Management |access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://ceic.cc/ Central Eastside Industrial Council]\n\n{{Portland neighborhoods}}\n\n[[Category:Central Eastside, Portland, Oregon| ]]\n[[Category:Neighborhoods in Portland, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Southeast Portland, Oregon]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n| name                    = Central Eastside\n| native_name             = \n| native_name_lang        = <!-- ISO 639-2 code e.g. \"fr\" for French. If more than one, use {{lang}} instead -->\n| settlement_type         = Subdistrict\n| image_skyline           = \n| image_size              = \n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = \n| image_flag              = \n| flag_alt                = \n| image_seal              = \n| seal_alt                = \n| image_shield            = \n| shield_alt              = \n| nickname                = \n| motto                   = \n| image_map               = \n| map_alt                 = \n| map_caption             = \n| pushpin_map             = USA Oregon Portland\n| pushpin_label_position  = \n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = \n| coordinates             = {{coord|45.515097|-122.660782|region:US-OR_type:city|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| coordinates_footnotes   = [http://www.portlandonline.com/shared/cfm/image.cfm?id=58593 PDF map]\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = [[United States]]\n| subdivision_type1       = State\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Oregon]]\n| subdivision_type2       = City\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]]\n| established_title       = \n| established_date        = \n| founder                 = \n| seat_type               = \n| seat                    = \n| leader_title1           = \n| leader_name1            = \n| leader_title2           = \n| leader_name2            = \n| government_footnotes    = \n| leader_party            = \n| leader_title            = \n| leader_name             = \n| unit_pref               = US\n<!-- ALL fields with measurements have automatic unit conversion -->\n<!-- for references: use <ref> tags -->\n| area_footnotes          = <ref>{{cite web |url=https://prosperportland.us/portfolio-items/central-eastside/ |title=Central Eastside |publisher=[[Prosper Portland]] |access-date=April 15, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200415180942/https://prosperportland.us/portfolio-items/central-eastside/ |archive-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n| area_total_km2          = \n| area_total_sq_mi        = 1.11\n| dimensions_footnotes    = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_ft            = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| population_total        = \n| population_as_of        = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_density_sq_mi = auto\n| population_demonym      = \n| population_note         = \n| demographics_type1      = \n| demographics1_footnotes = \n| demographics1_title1    = No. of households\n| demographics1_info1     = \n| demographics1_title2    = Occupancy rate\n| demographics1_info2     = \n| demographics1_title3    = {{nowrap|Owner-occupied}}\n| demographics1_info3     = \n| demographics1_title4    = Renting\n| demographics1_info4     = \n| demographics1_title5    = Avg. household size\n| demographics1_info5     = \n| timezone1               = \n| utc_offset1             = \n| timezone1_DST           = \n| utc_offset1_DST         = \n| postal_code_type        = \n| postal_code             = \n| area_code_type          = \n| area_code               = \n| iso_code                = \n| website                 = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| footnotes               = \n}}\n'''Central Eastside''' is a [[subdistrict]] in [[Portland, Oregon]], United States. It is situated in [[Neighborhoods of Portland, Oregon#Southeast|Southeast Portland]] along the east bank of the [[Willamette River]] and makes up a part of Portland's Central City district.\n\n==History==\n{{see also|East Portland, Oregon}}\n\nIn 1845, [[Oregon Trail]] pioneer [[James B. Stephens]] laid claim to {{convert|640|acre|ha}} of land situated directly across the [[Willamette River]] from the then-newly established [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]] townsite.<ref name=\"east-portland-1874\">{{cite web |url=https://oregonhistoryproject.org/articles/historical-records/east-portland-1874/ |title=East Portland, 1874 |publisher=[[Oregon Historical Society]] |access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref> The land had been controlled by [[John McLoughlin]] of the [[Hudson\u2019s Bay Company]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.opb.org/artsandlife/series/historical-photo/oregon-historical-photo-city-of-east-portland/ |last=Rosman |first=John |title=Oregon Historical Photo: The City Of East Portland |date=May 12, 2014 |publisher=[[Oregon Public Broadcasting]] |access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"forgotten-city\">{{cite web |url=http://visitahc.org/wp-content/uploads/Exhibit-booklet.pdf |title=East Portland: A Changing Landscape, A Forgotten City |publisher=Architectural Heritage Center |access-date=April 15, 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200415215652/http://visitahc.org/wp-content/uploads/Exhibit-booklet.pdf |archive-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref>{{rp|2}} The area consisted of [[orchard]]s and [[hay]], and its location along the east bank of the river\u2014with its [[marsh]]es, [[creek]]s, and [[Slough (hydrology)|slough]]s\u2014made development challenging.<ref name=\"guo-2014\">{{cite report |url=https://www.pdx.edu/sba/sites/www.pdx.edu.sba/files/01%20Central%20Eastside%20-%20Guo.pdf |last=Guo |first=Angela |title=The Evolution of Portland's Central Eastside |work=Center for Real Estate Quarterly Report |volume=8 |number=2 |publisher=[[Portland State University]] |date=2014 |access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref>{{rp|3}} Stephens established the Stark Street Ferry to link the east and west sides of the river in 1848. A mule on a treadmill powered the vessel's [[paddle wheel]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Terry |first=John |title=Hundreds of ferries once served Oregonians; now there are just three |date=Oct 15, 2011 |newspaper=[[The Oregonian]] |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/O/2011/10/hundreds_of_ferries_once_serve.html |access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref> On April{{nbsp}}16, 1868, the [[Oregon Central Railroad]] broke ground in the settlement, which by then was being referred to as [[East Portland, Oregon|East Portland]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.portlandoregon.gov/archives/article/12264 |title=1868 Invitation to railroad groundbreaking |publisher=City of Portland Archives and Records Management |access-date=April 15, 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200415213419/https://www.portlandoregon.gov/archives/article/12264 |archive-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref> The line extended from [[Salem, Oregon|Salem]] in the following year, helping to start the development of an industrial economy based on the shipment of agricultural products across the [[Willamette Valley]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://beta.portland.gov/sites/default/files/2020-01/portlands-central-eastside-2013.pdf |title=Portland Central Eastside |publisher=City of Portland Bureau of Planning and Sustainability |date=January 2020 |page=2 |access-date=April 15, 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200415190953/https://beta.portland.gov/sites/default/files/2020-01/portlands-central-eastside-2013.pdf |archive-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref> The railroad's presence led Stephens to incorporate the City of East Portland in 1870 with its population of 8,293.<ref name=\"forgotten-city\"/>{{rp|6}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.portlandoregon.gov/archives/article/284518 |title=Portland Historical Timeline: 1843 to 1901 |publisher=City of Portland Archives and Records Management |access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://ceic.cc/ Central Eastside Industrial Council]\n\n{{Portland neighborhoods}}\n\n[[Category:Central Eastside, Portland, Oregon| ]]\n[[Category:Neighborhoods in Portland, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Southeast Portland, Oregon]]\n", "name_user": "Truflip99", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Central_Eastside,_Portland,_Oregon"}
{"title_page": "Otto Wilhelm Masing", "text_new": "{{Expand German|topic=biography|Otto Wilhelm Masing|date=March 2010}}\n[[File:Owmasing.svg|thumb|Otto Wilhelm Masing]]\n'''Otto Wilhelm Masing''' ({{osd|8 November|1763|28 October}} in [[Lohusuu]], [[Kreis Dorpat]], [[Livland Governorate]] \u2013 {{osd|15 March|1832|3 March}} in [[\u00c4ksi]], Livland Governorate) was an early [[Baltic German]] [[Estophile]] and a major advocate of peasant rights, especially regarding education.\n\n==Life==\nHe received schooling at the town school of [[Narva]] (1777\u20131779) and then (1779\u20131782) at the [[Gymnasium (school)|Gymnasium]] of [[Torgau]] ([[Germany]]) before studying [[theology]], [[music]] and [[drawing]] at the [[Martin Luther University of Halle-Wittenberg|University of Halle]], returning to [[Estonia]] in 1786. \n\nIn 1796 he married Dorothea Amalie Ehlertz (1776\u20131809) in [[St. John's Church, Tartu|St. John's Church]] of [[Dorpat]] (Tartu),<ref>Entry in the [http://www.ra.ee/dgs/_purl.php?shc=EAA.1253.3.3:252?113,499,1079,184,0 Register of Marriages of the Parish of St. John] (Estonian: Tartu Jaani kogudus)</ref> a daughter of the [[Councillor|city councillor]] Carl Ulrich Ehlertz  (1739\u20131790) <ref>{{Citation\n| last1  = von Lemm\n| first1 = Robert Arthur\n| url = http://opacplus.bsb-muenchen.de/title/BV005090368/ft/bsb00096846?page=77\n| title     = Dorpater Ratslinie 1319-1889 und das Dorpater Stadtamt 1878-1918\n| publisher = Herder-Inst.\n| place = [[Marburg|Marburg/Lahn]]\n| year    = 1960\n}}</ref> and his wife Louisa Dorothea n\u00e9e Stockenberg (1755\u20131803), a great-granddaughter of the sculptor [[Johann Gustav Stockenberg]].\n\n==Work==\n[[File:Aksi Andrease kirik 20150510-124201 3X4 panoraam.jpg|thumb|Church of St. Andrew in [[\u00c4ksi]] (2015)]]\nHis first employment after concluding his studies was as private tutor at [[P\u00fcssi|P\u00fcssi Manor]] for the children of the nobleman Otto Magnus von Toll. \n\nIn 1788 he became the pastor of the (Lutheran) church in [[L\u00fcganuse]] (1788\u20131795), then serving from 1795 in [[Viru-Nigula]] (1795\u20131815) and from 1815 in [[\u00c4ksi]], where he remained as pastor until his death.<ref>http://www.monument.ee/viru-nigula-vald/viru-nigula-otto-wilhelm-masing</ref> \n\nFrom 1818 he also took on the post of assessor of the [[Ecclesiastical court|consistory]] of [[Governorate of Livonia|Livonia]] and from 1821 onwards he was also [[Provost (religion)|Provost]] for [[Tartu]]. \n\n==Contributions as publicist and linguist==\n[[File:Masingu aabitsa tiitelleht.jpeg|thumb|300px|right|Title page of 'ABD' by Otto Wilhelm Masing, published in 1795]]\nIn 1795, Masing compiled and published a children's textbook for learning reading, the ''ABD''. (The letter 'C' does not appear in [[Estonian words]], and back then, was not considered a member of [[Estonian alphabet]].  This considered, the title could be translated as \"ABC.\") He published a further textbook with methodical reading instructions, the ''Luggemislehhed'', in 1821. \n\nFrom 1821 to 1823, Masing published a newsletter ''Marahva N\u00e4ddala-Leht'' ([[Estonian language|Estonian]] for ''Peasant's Weekly''), one of the earliest regular publications in the [[Estonian language]].\n\nAmong other linguistic contributions, Masing is credited with creating the letter '[[\u00f5]]' to denote an Estonian phoneme not found in other nearby languages.<ref>https://www.sirp.ee/s1-artiklid/varamu/kuidas-tuli-o-taht-eesti-kirjakeelde/</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n* Imperial Russian [[Order of Saint Vladimir]], 4th class (awarded 1821) <ref>{{Citation | last1 = Napiersky | first1 = Karl Eduard | title = Beitr\u00e4ge zur Geschichte der Kirchen und Prediger in Livland. Drittes Heft, Lebensnachrichten von den livl\u00e4ndischen Predigern, mit litter\u00e4rischen Nachweisen. Zweiter Theil, H-P | publisher = J.F. Steffenhagen und Sohn | place = [[Jelgava|Mitau]] | year = 1851| hdl = 10062/29497 | author1-link = Karl Eduard von Napiersky }}</ref><ref>{{Citation | last1 = Paucker | first1 = Hugo Richard | title = Ehstlands Geistlichkeit in geordneter Zeit- und Reihefolge | publisher = Lindfors Erben | place = [[Tallinn|Reval]] | year = 1849| hdl = 10062/17510 }}</ref>\n\n==External links==\n* Estonica: [https://web.archive.org/web/20070610023546/http://www.estonica.org/eng/lugu.html?kateg=43&menyy_id=96&alam=61&leht=7 1710\u20131850. The Baltic Landesstaat. Emergence of national consciousness and Estophilia]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Masing, Otto Wilhelm}}\n[[Category:Linguists from Estonia]]\n[[Category:Estonian Lutheran clergy]]\n[[Category:Estophiles]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of St. Vladimir, 4th class]]\n[[Category:1763 births]]\n[[Category:1832 deaths]]\n[[Category:18th-century Estonian people]]\n[[Category:19th-century Estonian people]]\n[[Category:Baltic-German people]]\n[[Category:Burials at Raadi cemetery]]\n\n{{Estonia-linguist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Expand German|topic=biography|Otto Wilhelm Masing|date=March 2010}}\n[[File:Owmasing.svg|thumb|Otto Wilhelm Masing]]\n'''Otto Wilhelm Masing''' ({{osd|8 November|1763|28 October}} in [[Lohusuu]], [[Kreis Dorpat]], [[Livland Governorate]] \u2013 {{osd|15 March|1832|3 March}} in [[\u00c4ksi]], Livland Governorate) was an early [[Baltic German]] [[Estophile]] and a major advocate of peasant rights, especially regarding education.\n\n==Life==\nHe received schooling at the town school of [[Narva]] (1777\u20131779) and then (1779\u20131782) at the [[Gymnasium (school)|Gymnasium]] of [[Torgau]] ([[Germany]]) before studying [[theology]], [[music]] and [[drawing]] at the [[Martin Luther University of Halle-Wittenberg|University of Halle]], returning to [[Estonia]] in 1786. \n\nIn 1796 he married Dorothea Amalie Ehlertz (1776\u20131809) in [[St. John's Church, Tartu|Dorpat]] ([[Tartu]]),<ref>Entry in the [http://www.ra.ee/dgs/_purl.php?shc=EAA.1253.3.3:252?113,499,1079,184,0 Register of Marriages of the Parish of St. John] (Estonian: Tartu Jaani kogudus)</ref> a daughter of the [[Councillor|city councillor]] Carl Ulrich Ehlertz  (1739\u20131790) <ref>{{Citation\n| last1  = von Lemm\n| first1 = Robert Arthur\n| url = http://opacplus.bsb-muenchen.de/title/BV005090368/ft/bsb00096846?page=77\n| title     = Dorpater Ratslinie 1319-1889 und das Dorpater Stadtamt 1878-1918\n| publisher = Herder-Inst.\n| place = [[Marburg|Marburg/Lahn]]\n| year    = 1960\n}}</ref> and his wife Louisa Dorothea n\u00e9e Stockenberg (1755\u20131803), a great-granddaughter of the sculptor [[Johann Gustav Stockenberg]].     \n\n==Work==\n[[File:Aksi Andrease kirik 20150510-124201 3X4 panoraam.jpg|thumb|Church of St. Andrew in [[\u00c4ksi]] (2015)]]\nHis first employment after concluding his studies was as private tutor at [[P\u00fcssi|P\u00fcssi Manor]] for the children of the nobleman Otto Magnus von Toll. \n\nIn 1788 he became the pastor of the (Lutheran) church in [[L\u00fcganuse]] (1788\u20131795), then serving from 1795 in [[Viru-Nigula]] (1795\u20131815) and from 1815 in [[\u00c4ksi]], where he remained as pastor until his death.<ref>http://www.monument.ee/viru-nigula-vald/viru-nigula-otto-wilhelm-masing</ref> \n\nFrom 1818 he also took on the post of assessor of the [[Ecclesiastical court|consistory]] of [[Governorate of Livonia|Livonia]] and from 1821 onwards he was also [[Provost (religion)|Provost]] for [[Tartu]]. \n\n==Contributions as publicist and linguist==\n[[File:Masingu aabitsa tiitelleht.jpeg|thumb|300px|right|Title page of 'ABD' by Otto Wilhelm Masing, published in 1795]]\nIn 1795, Masing compiled and published a children's textbook for learning reading, the ''ABD''. (The letter 'C' does not appear in [[Estonian words]], and back then, was not considered a member of [[Estonian alphabet]].  This considered, the title could be translated as \"ABC.\") He published a further textbook with methodical reading instructions, the ''Luggemislehhed'', in 1821. \n\nFrom 1821 to 1823, Masing published a newsletter ''Marahva N\u00e4ddala-Leht'' ([[Estonian language|Estonian]] for ''Peasant's Weekly''), one of the earliest regular publications in the [[Estonian language]].\n\nAmong other linguistic contributions, Masing is credited with creating the letter '[[\u00f5]]' to denote an Estonian phoneme not found in other nearby languages.<ref>https://www.sirp.ee/s1-artiklid/varamu/kuidas-tuli-o-taht-eesti-kirjakeelde/</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n* Imperial Russian [[Order of Saint Vladimir]], 4th class (awarded 1821) <ref>{{Citation | last1 = Napiersky | first1 = Karl Eduard | title = Beitr\u00e4ge zur Geschichte der Kirchen und Prediger in Livland. Drittes Heft, Lebensnachrichten von den livl\u00e4ndischen Predigern, mit litter\u00e4rischen Nachweisen. Zweiter Theil, H-P | publisher = J.F. Steffenhagen und Sohn | place = [[Jelgava|Mitau]] | year = 1851| hdl = 10062/29497 | author1-link = Karl Eduard von Napiersky }}</ref><ref>{{Citation | last1 = Paucker | first1 = Hugo Richard | title = Ehstlands Geistlichkeit in geordneter Zeit- und Reihefolge | publisher = Lindfors Erben | place = [[Tallinn|Reval]] | year = 1849| hdl = 10062/17510 }}</ref>\n\n==External links==\n* Estonica: [https://web.archive.org/web/20070610023546/http://www.estonica.org/eng/lugu.html?kateg=43&menyy_id=96&alam=61&leht=7 1710\u20131850. The Baltic Landesstaat. Emergence of national consciousness and Estophilia]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Masing, Otto Wilhelm}}\n[[Category:Linguists from Estonia]]\n[[Category:Estonian Lutheran clergy]]\n[[Category:Estophiles]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of St. Vladimir, 4th class]]\n[[Category:1763 births]]\n[[Category:1832 deaths]]\n[[Category:18th-century Estonian people]]\n[[Category:19th-century Estonian people]]\n[[Category:Baltic-German people]]\n[[Category:Burials at Raadi cemetery]]\n\n{{Estonia-linguist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Alvinicious715", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Otto_Wilhelm_Masing"}
{"title_page": "Beyond the Stellar Empire (play-by-mail game)", "text_new": "{{short description|Fantasy role-playing game}}\n{{Italic title}}\n'''''Beyond the Stellar Empire''''' (or '''''BSE''''') was a [[play-by-mail]] (PBM) game published by Adventures By Mail. ''BSE'' was an [[Open-ended (gameplay)|open-ended]] \"space opera\" with a single available game that began in playtesting in 1981.<ref>[[#Mar87|Marte 1987]]. p. 6.</ref> According to Stephen Marte, like \"[[The Tribes of Crane|Tribes of Crane]] and [[Midgard (game)|Midgard]], BSE is the stomping ground of many of PBM's best power gamers\".<ref>[[#Mar87|Marte 1987]]. p. 6., Marte bolded Tribes of Crane, Midgard, and BSE in the original text.</ref> The game comprised two variants, one monitored by Game Masters who imposed artificial constraints, and another without constraints. Gameplay took place on a vast space stage where [[mega-corporation]]s formed the dominant organizing framework, alongside various other groups that players could join to pursue tasks to advance, collaborate with other players, and progress to more senior positions such as colony governors. ''Beyond the Stellar Empire'' placed #5 and #11 in 1987 and 1988, respectively, in ''[[Paper Mayhem]]'', a magazine for play-by-mail games, for Best PBM Game of the Year. In subsequent years, the game did not score well in ''Paper Mayhem'' reader ratings for playability, use, and product understanding. ''Beyond the Stellar Empire: The New System'' won the [[Origins Award]] for Best New Play-By-Mail Game of 1989.\n\n==Development==\nReviewer Stephen Marte stated in 1987 that he had contact information for 150 PBM players but speculated that as many as 450 actually played the game.<ref>[[#Mui13|Muir 2013]]. p. 14.</ref>\n\nIn the January/February 1990 issue of ''[[Paper Mayhem]]'', a magazine for [[Play-by-mail game|play-by-mail games]], Mike Popolizio, Liz Leblanc, and Marti Popolizio described a redesign conducted on ''BSE''.<ref name=Poplizio>[[#Pop90|Popolizio, Leblanc, and Popolizio1990]]. p. 8\u201310.</ref> The overhaul included faster turnaround times for turns, additional options for diplomacy, increased ability to implement player suggestions, introduction of black-markets, and other changes.<ref name=Poplizio/> \n\nIn a 1992 issue of ''Paper Mayhem'', Wayne Alexander identified two variants of ''Beyond the Stellar Empire'': the Capellan Periphery and the Draconian Variant.<ref>[[#Ale92|Alexander 1992]]. p. 31.</ref> Alexander noted that the Capellan Periphery was the initial variant and was open-ended in the sense that it had no victory conditions\u2013players could continue to progress through work and expenditures, requesting and completing assignments, acquiring larger ships and colonies, etc.<ref>[[#Ale92|Alexander 1992]]. p. 31.</ref> However, he lamented that the Capellan Periphery was not truly open-ended in that the Game Masters (GMs) eventually would impose an artificial constraint on play that he called \"The Wall\".<ref>[[#Ale92|Alexander 1992]]. p. 31.</ref> This didn't prevent the players from having an enjoyable playing experience, but it limited \"power players\".<ref>[[#Ale92|Alexander 1992]]. p. 31.</ref> In other words, according to Alexander, \"The Capellan Periphery has a lot of sizzle, but the steak is just dog meat.\"<ref>[[#Ale92|Alexander 1992]]. p. 31.</ref> The Draconian Variant, while nascent in 1992, and saddled with some minor gameplay challenges, put players on the \"ground floor\" of a truly open-ended game, causing Alexander to describe it as one \"with very little sizzle at this point, but the steak is filet mignon in potential\".<ref>[[#Ale92|Alexander 1992]]. p. 31.</ref>\n\n==Gameplay==\nThe game took place on a vast space stage. Stephen Marte stated the following about the field of play in 1987: <blockquote>The playing field consists of 80 systems. Each system is 30X30 hexes and each hex is 46,000 square miles. Five hundred planets, moons, and gas giants have been found in the 52 systems of the Capellan Periphery and it is estimated there are another 500 worlds in the 38 systems of the less explored Transhole Region. Planets and moons may be mapped, scanned, and geologically proved down to a 10 square mile sector. For all intents and purposes the scope of the playing field is as large as your imagination.<ref>[[#Mar87|Marte 1987]]. p. 6.</ref></blockquote>\n\nThe central element of the game was its thirteen [[mega-corporation]]s.<ref>[[#Mar87|Marte 1987]]. p. 6.</ref> Most of these were directed by a Game Master employed by Adventures by Mail, but run by a board of coordinators made up of players which managed a large hierarchy of players.<ref>[[#Mar87|Marte 1987]]. p. 6.</ref> These corporations provided frameworks that enabled players to choose, pursue, and accomplish tasks, but also generated interesting competition dynamics between corporations as well as internal competition struggles that sometimes caused cleavages serious enough to cause banishments or voluntary departures.<ref>[[#Mar87|Marte 1987]]. p. 6.</ref> Players did not have to join a mega-corporation: other possible groups included \"seven alien races, a religious sect, and a small piratical band know[n] as the Raiders of the Imperial Periphery (RIP)\".<ref>[[#Mar87|Marte 1987]]. p. 6.</ref>\n\nPlayers were limited to two starcaptains at the outset, but had significant variety among the 16 ship types and great room for game progression.<ref>[[#Mar87|Marte 1987]]. p. 6.</ref> For example, by 1987, there were 250 players acting as colony governors of varying sizes.<ref>[[#Mar87|Marte 1987]]. p. 6.</ref> Powerful players in mature roles could shift to a research focus to keep gameplay from getting stale.<ref>[[#Mar87|Marte 1987]]. p. 6.</ref>\n\n==Reception and Legacy==\nReviewer Stephen Marte observed in 1987 that ''Beyond the Stellar Empire'' was in some ways \"the \"ultimate PBM game\".<ref>[[#Mar87|Marte 1987]]. p. 6.</ref> In the November/December 1987 issue of ''Paper Mayhem'', ''Beyond the Stellar Empire'' tied for the #5 spot on the list of Best PBM Games of 1987 with [[Beyond the Quadra Zone (play-by-mail game)|''Beyond the Quadra Zone'']].<ref>[[#Maa87|Paper Mayhem 1987]]. p. 2.</ref> In 1988, the game tied for 11th place in the list of Best PBM Games of 1988 along with [[Rimworlds (play-by-mail game)|''Rimworlds'']].<ref>[[#Maa88|Paper Mayhem 1988]]. p. 2.</ref> However, the game did not perform well in reader ratings in ''Paper Mayhem'' during the following years. In the May/June 1989 issue, the game scored 43 of 44 rated games.<ref>[[#May89|Paper Mayhem 1989]]. p. 2.</ref> In the July/August 1990 issue, it placed #63 of #68.<ref>[[#May90|Paper Mayhem 1990]]. p. 64.</ref> In July/August 1993 it was #81 of #81.<ref>[[#May93|Paper Mayhem 1993]]. p. 44\u201345.</ref> And in Nov/Dec 1994 it again placed last at #72 of #72.<ref>[[#May94|Paper Mayhem 1994]]. p. 44\u201345.</ref>\n\n''Beyond the Stellar Empire: The New System'' was awarded the [[Origins Award]] for \"Best New Play-by-Mail Game of 1989\".<ref>[[#Gam12|Game Manufacturer's Association 1989]].</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of play-by-mail games]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite magazine |last= Alexander|first= Wayne J.|date= September\u2013October 1992|title= Beyond the Stellar Empire: ''Capellan Periphery versus Draconian Variant''; The Poison and the Antidote? |magazine= [[Paper Mayhem]] |number= 56|page= 31|ref=Way92}}\n* {{cite web| url = http://www.gama.org/OriginsAwards/OriginsAwardsWinnersThe1980s/The1989OriginsAwards/tabid/3232/Default.aspx| title = The 1989 Origins Awards| publisher = [[Game Manufacturers Association|The Game Manufacturers Association]]| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121216052421/http://www.gama.org/OriginsAwards/OriginsAwardsWinnersThe1980s/The1989OriginsAwards/tabid/3232/Default.aspx| url-status = dead| archivedate = 2012-12-16|ref=Gam12}}\n* {{cite magazine |last= Lloyd|first= Vickie|date= September\u2013October 1992|title= BSE: The Good Times are Over |magazine= [[Paper Mayhem]] |number= 56|pages= 28\u201331|ref=Llo92}}\n* {{cite magazine |last= Marte|first= Stephen|date= March\u2013April 1987|title= Beyond the Stellar Empire |magazine= [[Paper Mayhem]] |number= 23|pages= 6\u20138|ref=Mar87}}\n* {{cite magazine |last= Marte|first= Stephen|date= November\u2013December 1988|title= Stellar Politics: Part II |magazine= [[Paper Mayhem]] |number= 33|pages= 18\u201320|ref=Mar88}}\n* {{cite magazine |last= Paper Mayhem|first= |date= November\u2013December 1987|title= Best PBM Game of 1987 |magazine= [[Paper Mayhem]] |number= 27|page= 2|ref=Maa87}}\n* {{cite magazine |last= Paper Mayhem|first= |date= November\u2013December 1988|title= Best PBM Game of 1988 |magazine= [[Paper Mayhem]] |number= 33|page= 2|ref=Maa88}}\n* {{cite magazine |last= Paper Mayhem|first= |date= May\u2013June 1989|title= PBM Game Ratings: ''As of 3/30/89'' |magazine= [[Paper Mayhem]] |number= 36|page= 3|ref=May89}}\n* {{cite magazine |last= Paper Mayhem|first= |date= July\u2013August 1990|title= PBM Game Ratings: As of 5-26-90 |magazine= [[Paper Mayhem]] |number= 43|page= 64|ref=May90}}\n* {{cite magazine |last= Paper Mayhem|first= |date= July\u2013August 1993|title= PBM Game Ratings: ''As of 06/06/93'' |magazine= [[Paper Mayhem]] |number= 61|pages= 44\u201345|ref=May93}}\n* {{cite magazine |last= Paper Mayhem|first= |date= November\u2013December 1994|title= PBM Game Ratings: ''As of 9/12/94'' |magazine= [[Paper Mayhem]] |number= 69|pages= 44\u201345|ref=May94}}\n* {{cite magazine |last1= Popolizio|first1= Mike |last2= LeBlanc|first2= Liz |last3= Popolizio|first3= Marti |date= 1990|title= Revamping a Classic! The Redesign of BSE|url= |magazine= [[Paper Mayhem]]|pages= 8\u201310|ref=Pop90}}\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n[[Category:Origins Award winners]]\n[[Category:Play-by-mail games]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Fantasy role-playing game}}\n{{Italic title}}\n'''''Beyond the Stellar Empire''''' (or '''''BSE''''') was a [[play-by-mail]] (PBM) game published by Adventures By Mail. ''BSE'' was an [[Open-ended (gameplay)|open-ended]] \"space opera\" with a single available game that began in playtesting in 1981.<ref>[[#Mar87|Marte 1987]]. p. 6.</ref> According to Stephen Marte, like \"[[The Tribes of Crane|Tribes of Crane]] and [[Midgard (game)|Midgard]], BSE is the stomping ground of many of PBM's best power gamers\".<ref>[[#Mar87|Marte 1987]]. p. 6., Marte bolded Tribes of Crane, Midgard, and BSE in the original text.</ref> The game comprised two variants, one monitored by Game Masters who imposed artificial constraints, and another without constraints. Gameplay took place on a vast space stage where [[mega-corporation]]s formed the dominant organizing framework, alongside various other groups that players could join to pursue tasks to advance, collaborate with other players, and progress to more senior positions such as colony governors. ''Beyond the Stellar Empire'' placed #5 and #11 in 1987 and 1988, respectively, in ''[[Paper Mayhem]]'', a magazine for play-by-mail games, for Best PBM Game of the Year. In subsequent years, the game did not score well in ''Paper Mayhem'' reader ratings for playability, use, and product understanding. ''Beyond the Stellar Empire: The New System'' won the [[Origins Award]] for Best New Play-By-Mail Game of 1989.\n\n==Development==\nReviewer Stephen Marte stated in 1987 that he had contact information for 150 PBM players but speculated that as many as 450 actually played the game.<ref>[[#Mui13|Muir 2013]]. p. 14.</ref>\n\nIn the January/February 1990 issue of ''[[Paper Mayhem]]'', a magazine for [[Play-by-mail game|play-by-mail games]], Mike Popolizio, Liz Leblanc, and Marti Popolizio described a redesign conducted on ''BSE''.<ref name=Poplizio>[[#Pop90|Popolizio, Leblanc, and Popolizio1990]]. p. 8\u201310.</ref> The overhaul included faster turnaround times for turns, additional options for diplomacy, increased ability to implement player suggestions, introduction of black-markets, and other changes.<ref name=Poplizio/> \n\nIn a 1992 issue of ''Paper Mayhem'', Wayne Alexander identified two variants of ''Beyond the Stellar Empire'': the Capellan Periphery and the Draconian Variant.<ref>[[#Ale92|Alexander 1992]]. p. 31.</ref> Alexander noted that the Capellan Periphery was the initial variant and was open-ended in the sense that it had no victory conditions\u2013players could continue to progress through work and expenditures, requesting and completing assignments, acquiring larger ships and colonies, etc.<ref>[[#Ale92|Alexander 1992]]. p. 31.</ref> However, he lamented that the Capellan Periphery was not truly open-ended in that the Game Masters (GMs) eventually would impose an artificial constraint on play that he called \"The Wall\".<ref>[[#Ale92|Alexander 1992]]. p. 31.</ref> This didn't prevent the players from having an enjoyable playing experience, but it limited \"power players\".<ref>[[#Ale92|Alexander 1992]]. p. 31.</ref> In other words, according to Alexander, \"The Capellan Periphery has a lot of sizzle, but the steak is just dog meat.\"<ref>[[#Ale92|Alexander 1992]]. p. 31.</ref> The Draconian Variant, while nascent in 1992, and saddled with some minor gameplay challenges, put players on the \"ground floor\" of a truly open-ended game, causing Alexander to describe it as one \"with very little sizzle at this point, but the steak is filet mignon in potential\".<ref>[[#Ale92|Alexander 1992]]. p. 31.</ref>\n\n==Gameplay==\nThe game took place on a vast space stage. Stephen Marte stated the following about the field of play in 1987: <blockquote>The playing field consists of 80 systems. Each system is 30X30 hexes and each hex is 46,000 square miles. Five hundred planets, moons, and gas giants have been found in the 52 systems of the Capellan Periphery and it is estimated there are another 500 worlds in the 38 systems of the less explored Transhole Region. Planets and moons may be mapped, scanned, and geologically proved down to a 10 square mile sector. For all intents and purposes the scope of the playing field is as large as your imagination.<ref>[[#Mar87|Marte 1987]]. p. 6.</ref></blockquote>\n\nThe central element of the game was its thirteen [[mega-corporation]]s.<ref>[[#Mar87|Marte 1987]]. p. 6.</ref> Most of these were directed by a Game Master employed by Adventures by Mail, but run by a board of coordinators made up of players which managed a large hierarchy of players.<ref>[[#Mar87|Marte 1987]]. p. 6.</ref> These corporations provided frameworks that enabled players to choose, pursue, and accomplish tasks, but also generated interesting competition dynamics between corporations as well as internal competition struggles that sometimes caused cleavages serious enough to cause banishments or voluntary departures.<ref>[[#Mar87|Marte 1987]]. p. 6.</ref> Players did not have to join a mega-corporation: other possible groups included \"seven alien races, a religious sect, and a small piratical band know[n] as the Raiders of the Imperial Periphery (RIP)\".<ref>[[#Mar87|Marte 1987]]. p. 6.</ref>\n\nPlayers were limited to two starcaptains at the outset, but had significant variety among the 16 ship types and great room for game progression.<ref>[[#Mar87|Marte 1987]]. p. 6.</ref> For example, by 1987, there were 250 players acting as colony governors of varying sizes.<ref>[[#Mar87|Marte 1987]]. p. 6.</ref> Powerful players in mature roles could shift to a research focus to keep gameplay from getting stale.<ref>[[#Mar87|Marte 1987]]. p. 6.</ref>\n\n==Reception and Legacy==\nReviewer Stephen Marte observed in 1987 that ''Beyond the Stellar Empire'' was in some ways \"the \"ultimate PBM game\".<ref>[[#Mar87|Marte 1987]]. p. 6.</ref> In the November/December 1987 issue of ''Paper Mayhem'', ''Beyond the Stellar Empire'' tied for the #5 spot on the list of Best PBM Games of 1987 with [[Beyond the Quadra Zone (play-by-mail game)|''Beyond the Quadra Zone'']].<ref>[[#Maa87|Paper Mayhem 1987]]. p. 2.</ref> In 1988, the game tied for 11th place in the list of Best PBM Games of 1988 along with [[Rimworlds (play-by-mail game)|''Rimworlds'']].<ref>[[#Maa88|Paper Mayhem 1988]]. p. 2.</ref> However, the game did not perform well in reader ratings in ''Paper Mayhem'' during the following years. In the May/June 1989 issue, the game scored 43 of 44 rated games.<ref>[[#May89|Paper Mayhem 1989]]. p. 2.</ref> In the July/August 1990 issue, it placed #63 of #68.<ref>[[#May90|Paper Mayhem 1990]]. p. 64.</ref> In July/August 1993 it was #81 of #81.<ref>[[#May93|Paper Mayhem 1993]]. p. 44\u201345.</ref> And in Nov/Dec 1994 it again placed last at #72 of #72.<ref>[[#May94|Paper Mayhem 1994]]. p. 44\u201345.</ref>\n\n''Beyond the Stellar Empire: The New System'' was awarded the [[Origins Award]] for \"Best New Play-by-Mail Game of 1989\".<ref>[[#Gam12|Game Manufacturer's Association 1989]].</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of play-by-mail games]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite magazine |last= Alexander|first= Wayne J.|date= September\u2013October 1992|title= Beyond the Stellar Empire: ''Capellan Periphery versus Draconian Variant''; The Poison and the Antidote? |magazine= [[Paper Mayhem]] |number= 56|page= 31|ref=Way92}}\n* {{cite web| url = http://www.gama.org/OriginsAwards/OriginsAwardsWinnersThe1980s/The1989OriginsAwards/tabid/3232/Default.aspx| title = The 1989 Origins Awards| publisher = [[Game Manufacturers Association|The Game Manufacturers Association]]| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121216052421/http://www.gama.org/OriginsAwards/OriginsAwardsWinnersThe1980s/The1989OriginsAwards/tabid/3232/Default.aspx| url-status = dead| archivedate = 2012-12-16|ref=Gam12}}\n* {{cite magazine |last= Lloyd|first= Vickie|date= September\u2013October 1992|title= BSE: The Good Times are Over |magazine= [[Paper Mayhem]] |number= 56|pages= 28\u201331|ref=Llo92}}\n* {{cite magazine |last= Marte|first= Stephen|date= March\u2013April 1987|title= Beyond the Stellar Empire |magazine= [[Paper Mayhem]] |number= 23|pages= 6\u20138|ref=Mar87}}\n* {{cite magazine |last= Marte|first= Stephen|date= November\u2013December 1988|title= Stellar Politics: Part II |magazine= [[Paper Mayhem]] |number= 33|pages= 18\u201320|ref=Mar88}}\n* {{cite magazine |last= Paper Mayhem|first= |date= November\u2013December 1987|title= Best PBM Game of 1987 |magazine= [[Paper Mayhem]] |number= 27|page= 2|ref=Maa87}}\n* {{cite magazine |last= Paper Mayhem|first= |date= November\u2013December 1988|title= Best PBM Game of 1988 |magazine= [[Paper Mayhem]] |number= 33|page= 2|ref=Maa88}}\n* {{cite magazine |last= Paper Mayhem|first= |date= May\u2013June 1989|title= PBM Game Ratings: As of 3/30/89 |magazine= [[Paper Mayhem]] |number= 36|page= 3|ref=May89}}\n* {{cite magazine |last= Paper Mayhem|first= |date= July\u2013August 1990|title= PBM Game Ratings: As of 5-26-90 |magazine= [[Paper Mayhem]] |number= 43|page= 64|ref=May90}}\n* {{cite magazine |last= Paper Mayhem|first= |date= July\u2013August 1993|title= PBM Game Ratings: As of 06/06/93 |magazine= [[Paper Mayhem]] |number= 61|pages= 44\u201345|ref=May93}}\n* {{cite magazine |last= Paper Mayhem|first= |date= November\u2013December 1994|title= PBM Game Ratings: As of 9/12/94 |magazine= [[Paper Mayhem]] |number= 69|pages= 44\u201345|ref=May94}}\n* {{cite magazine |last1= Popolizio|first1= Mike |last2= LeBlanc|first2= Liz |last3= Popolizio|first3= Marti |date= 1990|title= Revamping a Classic! The Redesign of BSE|url= |magazine= [[Paper Mayhem]]|pages= 8\u201310|ref=Pop90}}\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n[[Category:Origins Award winners]]\n[[Category:Play-by-mail games]]\n", "name_user": "Airborne84", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBibliography", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beyond_the_Stellar_Empire_(play-by-mail_game)"}
{"title_page": "Scotiabank Arena", "text_new": "{{about|the indoor sporting arena in Toronto|the arena in Calgary|Scotiabank Saddledome|the arena in Halifax, Nova Scotia|Scotiabank Centre|the arena in Ottawa formerly known as Scotiabank Place|Canadian Tire Centre}}\n{{Redirect|Air Canada Centre|the headquarters of Air Canada in Montreal|Air Canada#Headquarters}}\n{{short description|Indoor arena in Toronto, Ontario, Canada}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=January 2015}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox venue\n| stadium_name = Scotiabank Arena\n| nickname = The Hanger<br  />The ACC\n| logo_image = [[File:Scotiabank Arena logo.svg|250px]]\n| image = [[File:Scotiabank Arena - 2018 (cropped).jpg|250px]]\n| caption = Exterior view of the arena in 2018\n| address = 40 [[Bay Street]]\n| location = [[Toronto|Toronto, Ontario]]\n| coordinates = {{Coord|43|38|36|N|79|22|45|W|type:landmark_scale:2000|display=it}}\n| pushpin_map = Canada Toronto#Canada Ontario#Canada\n| pushpin_relief = yes\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location in Toronto##Location in Ontario##Location in Canada\n| publictransit = {{rint|toronto|rail}} [[Union Station (Toronto)|Union Station]]<br />{{rint|toronto|subway|1}} [[Union station (TTC)|Union subway station]]<br />{{rint|gotransit|bus}} [[Union Station Bus Terminal|GO Bus Terminal]]\n| broke_ground = March 12, 1997\n| opened = February 19, 1999\n| Acreage = {{convert|61780.5|m2|sqft|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4306707/air-canada-centre-gets-new-name/|title=Air Canada Centre sign removed on eve of facility becoming Scotiabank Arena|work=Global News|accessdate=September 27, 2018|publisher=Corus Entertainment Inc.|date=June 30, 2018}}</ref>\n| owner = [[Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment]]\n| operator = \n| former_names = Air Canada Centre<!-- This article uses Canadian English. \"Centre\" is the correct spelling in this case. --> {{small|(1999\u20132018)}}\n| construction_cost = {{CAD|265&nbsp;million}}<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.theaircanadacentre.com/corporate/CompanyFacts.asp|title=Company Facts|accessdate=August 29, 2017|publisher=Air Canada Centre}}</ref><ref name=cost/><br />(${{formatprice|{{Inflation|CA|265000000|1999}}}} in {{Inflation-year|CA}} dollars{{inflation-fn|CA}})\n| architect = Brisbin Brook Beynon Architects (Architect of Record)<br />[[Populous (company)|HOK Sport]]<br />(Consulting Architects)<ref>{{cite web |title=Clubhouse Confidential: When a Bunch of Alpha Males Get Together Daily in a Confined Space, Lots of Things\u2014Good and Bad\u2014Can Happen|first=Michael|last=Faber|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1024724/3/index.htm|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|date=January 14, 2002|accessdate=January 16, 2013}}</ref>\n| project_manager = Clarendon Projects Ltd.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clarendonprojects.com/aircanadacentre.html|title=Clarendon Projects \u2013 Air Canada Centre|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402151414/http://www.clarendonprojects.com/aircanadacentre.html|archivedate=April 2, 2012}}</ref>\n| structural engineer = [[Halcrow Group|Yolles Partnership Inc.]]<ref>[http://www.halcrow.com/Our-projects/Project-details/Air-Canada-Centre-Canada/ Halcrow Yolles \u2013 Air Canada Centre] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111026034118/http://halcrow.com/Our-projects/Project-details/Air-Canada-Centre-Canada/ |date=October 26, 2011 }}</ref>\n| services engineer = The Mitchell Partnership, Inc.<ref>[http://www.tmptoronto.com/document_library/Air%20Canada%20Centre.pdf The Mitchell Partnership \u2013 Air Canada Centre] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140517115741/http://www.tmptoronto.com/document_library/Air%20Canada%20Centre.pdf |date=May 17, 2014 }}</ref>\n| general_contractor = [[PCL Construction|PCL Constructors Western, Inc.]]\n| tenants = [[Toronto Maple Leafs]] ([[National Hockey League|NHL]]) (1999\u2013present)<br />[[Toronto Raptors]] ([[National Basketball Association|NBA]]) (1999\u2013present)<br />[[Toronto Rock]] ([[National Lacrosse League|NLL]]) (2001\u2013present)<br />[[Toronto Phantoms]] ([[Arena Football League|AFL]]) (2001\u20132002)<br />[[Toronto Marlies]] ([[American Hockey League|AHL]]) (2010\u2013present, occasional home games)\n| seating_capacity = [[Basketball]]: 19,800 (20,511 with standing room)<br />[[Ice hockey|Hockey]]: 18,800 (20,270 with standing room)<br />[[Lacrosse]]: 18,800<br />[[Concert]]s: 19,800<br />[[Theatre]]: 5,200<ref>{{cite web|title=About|url=https://www.aircanadacentre.com/venue-information/about|publisher=Air Canada Centre|accessdate=May 10, 2018}}</ref>\n| parking = 2 underground levels\n| website = [https://www.scotiabankarena.com/ scotiabankarena.com]\n}}\n\n'''Scotiabank Arena''', formerly '''Air Canada Centre<!-- This article uses Canadian English. \"Centre\" is the correct spelling in this case. -->''', is a multi-purpose [[arena]] located on [[Bay Street]] in the [[South Core, Toronto|South Core]] district of [[Downtown Toronto|Downtown]] [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada. It is the home of the [[Toronto Maple Leafs]] of the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL), the [[Toronto Raptors]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) and the [[Toronto Rock]] of the [[National Lacrosse League]] (NLL). In addition, the minor league [[Toronto Marlies]] of the [[American Hockey League]] (AHL) and the [[Raptors 905]] of the [[NBA G League]] play occasional games at the arena. The arena was previously home to the [[Toronto Phantoms]] of the [[Arena Football League]] (AFL) during their brief existence.\n\nThe arena  is {{convert|61780.5|m2|sqft}} in size. It is owned and operated by [[Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment|Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment Ltd.]] (MLSE), the same group that owns the Leafs and the Raptors, as well as their respective development teams. In 2018, Scotiabank Arena was the 13th busiest arena in the world and the busiest in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pollstar.com/Chart/2019/01/2018YearEndWorldwideTicketSalesTop200ArenaVenues_705.pdf|title=2018 YEAR END Worldwide Ticket Sales TOP 200 ARENA VENUES|publisher=[[Pollstar]]|date=2018|accessdate=June 22, 2019}}</ref> It is also the most photographed location in Canada on [[Instagram]] according to [[BuzzFeed]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/leafs/2018/07/01/scotiabank-arena-now-officially-the-home-of-maple-leafs-and-raptors.html|title=Scotiabank Arena now officially the home of Maple Leafs and Raptors - The Star|publisher=Toronto Star}}</ref> Scotiabank Arena is connected to [[Union Station (Toronto)|Toronto Union]] railway station, [[Union station (TTC)|subway station]] and [[Union Station Bus Terminal|bus terminal]] via the [[PATH (Toronto)|PATH]].\n\nScotiabank Arena has, from its initial design to completion, revolutionized many concepts included in new arenas and stadiums built since then.{{according to whom|date=October 2019}} These features include luxury suites accessible on the ground floor, splitting the main scoreboard into several sections, rotating all sponsor signage in the bowl at once (to allow dominant messaging or \"neutralization\" for events that disallow commercial advertising), and multiple restaurants in and out of the main arena bowl view.\n\nScotiabank Arena also hosts other events, such as concerts, political conventions and [[Esports|video game competitions]].\n\n==History==\n===Before opening===\nThe arena site was once occupied by [[Canada Post]]'s Toronto Postal Delivery Building (designed by [[Charles B. Dolphin]]). The Canada Post building was built in 1938, to assist in the recent population growth of Toronto and its surrounding area.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.scotiabankarena.com/venue-information/about/history|title=History {{!}} Scotiabank Arena|last=Arena|first=Scotiabank|website=www.scotiabankarena.com|language=en|access-date=November 15, 2018}}</ref> The building was handed over to Department of National Defence for war storage purposes upon completion in 1941, but returned to Canada Post in 1946. Modifications were made to the building to be more adequately equipped for postal delivery, after it was altered by the Department of National Defence. After the work was completed in 1948, the building now possessed the capability and equipment for proper mail sorting and other mailing functions. The building was strategically located south of Union Station and was connected directly to the train platforms via an underground tunnel. Trains would be able to directly unload mail and move it directly to the mail sorting centre.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tayloronhistory.com/2013/02/12/torontos-architectural-gemsthe-postal-delivery-building-now-the-acc/|title=History|language=en|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>  \n\n====1990s Transition to Stadium====\nIn the early 1990s, the building needed major renovations. To cut costs, Canada Post decided to close the facility and move operations to an alternate letter processing plant, which had been constructed in the 1970s on Eastern Avenue.  Eventually, all of the old building's work was transferred here.<ref name=\":0\" /> In the early 1990s, real estate developers [[Bramalea (company)|Bramalea Ltd]] and [[Trizec Properties|Trizec]] arranged to purchase the building from Canada Post, and redevelop the site into a {{convert|230,000|m2|sqft|adj=on}} office, retail and residential space. Financial and development details of the purchase imposed various conditions prior to development, including rezoning by the city, remediation of soil contamination by Canada Post.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bramalea's Moves Shake Taxpayers|first=Stevie|last=Cameron|date=November 15, 1992|publisher=[[The Globe and Mail]]}}</ref>\n\nDue to financial difficulties, the building's ownership was returned to Canada Post in 1993. The Toronto Raptors purchased the building from Canada Post the next year.<ref name=\"rapnba\">{{cite web| url=http://www.nba.com/raptors/history/raptors_history.html/| title=Laying the Groundwork for the NBA in Toronto| website=nba.com| accessdate=October 14, 2017}}</ref>\n[[File:Postal terminal now Air Canada Centre.jpg|thumb|left|The arena retains the eastern wall of the original postal structure built in 1941, through a process of [[facadism]].]]\nConstruction of the arena was started by the Toronto Raptors, under their initial ownership group headed by Canadian businessman [[John Bitove]]. In 1995, it had been decided that the NBA would expand into Canada. The Toronto Raptors were created and would need an indoor arena to play in. The Canada Post building was chosen to be the new home of the Raptors due to its downtown location and lot size. Other venues such as [[Exhibition Place]], North York Centre, Bay and Wellesley, and Bay and Dundas were also considered. The Canada Post building was purchased for {{CAD|60}} million.<ref name=\":0\" /> The Raptors initially played in SkyDome (now [[Rogers Centre]]) while the arena was constructed.<ref name=\"blogTo\">{{cite web|first=Chris|last=Bateman|title=That time the Raptors and the Maple Leafs moved to the ACC|url=http://www.blogto.com/city/2014/02/that_time_the_raptors_and_leafs_moved_to_the_acc/|website=blogTo|date=February 22, 2014|accessdate=December 4, 2017}}</ref> Groundbreaking took place in March 1997. The building retained the [[Art Deco]] facade of the Toronto Postal Delivery Building along the east (along [[Bay Street]]) and south ([[Lake Shore Boulevard]]) walls of that structure, but the rest of the building (facing [[Union Station (Toronto)|Union Station]]) was removed to make room for the arena, through the process of [[facadism]]. The original building is protected under the ''[[Ontario Heritage Act]]''.\n\n===Arena 'Wars'===\nWhen MLGL ([[Maple Leaf Sports and Entertainment|Maple Leaf Gardens, Limited]] at the time the controlling company of the Toronto Maple Leafs) lost out on their desire to be the franchise owners of the Raptors, competition between the two organizations heated up centred around venues. MLGL declined to allow Maple Leaf Gardens to be used for the NBA upstart as a result pushing Bitove to secure rights to have the Raptors' opening seasons played at SkyDome until construction of the new stadium to be complete.\n\nThe 1930s-era Maple Leaf Gardens was showing its age; the Maple Leafs in desperate desire for a new facility began developing plans for building an all-new stadium with one of the key criteria for the new location that it must be within close walking proximity to both the subway system and GO Transit. During the early stages of construction, MLGL floated to the media plans for their own plans to build a competing single-use stadium on adjacent property just to the north of the stadium atop the train sheds at Union Station (similar to how [[Madison Square Garden]] was constructed) as the new home for the Toronto Maple Leafs.<ref name=ArenaWars>{{cite news|title=Leafs ready to Move (Page 2)|first=Craig|last=Daniels|date=April 16, 1997|publisher=[[The Toronto Sun]]}}</ref> The reaction from Raptors was nothing but anger. \"This proposed (Maple Leaf) location really disturbs us\" stated team president Richard Peddie, who went on to say that they would fight the Leafs \"every step of the way\" and he didn't understand why the Leafs have refused to join with the Raptors at their site; claiming that the Leafs want to \"build virtually on top of us\".<ref name=\"ArenaWars\" /> The major problem of the Union Station proposal is the land that the stadium would be built on was actually City of Toronto land that was leased out to CN Rail and CP Rail, which were in a major, long-standing dispute over rent payments (dating back to 1969). As a result, MLGL offered the city $156 Million (1997 CAD) in cash & assets to settle any and all outstanding claims and to buy the air rights above the Union Station train platforms.\n\nDuring this period John Bitove who disputed over the future of the arena who as a result of a [[shotgun clause]] was forced to sell his stake to Allan Slaight (who wanted a joint arena deal with MLGL) and now with majority ownership immediately went into talks with MLGL which eventually purchased both the Raptors and their partially completed arena, which subsequently resulted in major modifications to the original design, which was basketball-specific, to make the arena become more suitable for hockey. Originally planned to cost $217&nbsp;million, MLGL increased the budget to $265&nbsp;million after taking control.<ref name=cost>{{cite news|title=Upgrades added to cost|first=David|last=Shoalts|date=February 17, 1999|publisher=[[The Globe and Mail]]}}</ref> The Raptors were twice fined a million dollars (which were donated to their charitable foundation) by the NBA for missing deadlines to begin construction of their new arena.<ref>{{cite news|title=Raptors' arena bites dust|last=Christe|first=James|date=May 16, 1997|publisher=[[The Globe and Mail]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998, a strange twist of scheduling conflicts had the Toronto Raptors playing their final regular-season game at [[Copps Coliseum]] in Hamilton, as the Toronto Blue Jays had first right of refusal for all SkyDome dates.  The Raptors had attempted to play the April 19 match at Maple Leaf Gardens, but were unsuccessful.<ref>{{cite news|title=Raptors Move Final Game to Hamilton|date=January 7, 1998|publisher=[[Associated Press]]|url=https://www.apnews.com/7027ff09054e45b3b7471205f12cb521}}</ref>\n\n===Since opening===\n[[File:Air Canada Centre in 1999.jpg|thumb|left|Air Canada Centre in July 1999, five months after the arena opened]]\nIn December 1998, the building's construction was completed. Opening events took place early the next year and [[Steve Stavro]] (who was the majority shareholder of MLGL) was named CEO. The initial hockey game took place February 20, 1999 (Toronto Maple Leafs vs. [[Montreal Canadiens]]), the first basketball Game on February 21, 1999 (Toronto Raptors vs. [[Vancouver Grizzlies]]), and the opening concert on February 22, 1999 ([[The Tragically Hip]]).<ref name=\":0\" /> Features of the new building consist of a {{convert|65000|sqft|adj=on}} arena and a {{convert|165000|sqft|adj=on}} office tower. There is also an east\u2013west covered, climate controlled galleria and walkway onsite that contains restaurants, the ticket office, and other commercial units. The Galleria also connects Scotiabank Arena to popular locations in the downtown core such as Union Station, Bay Street and York Street. Scotiabank Arena is connected to the underground PATH network. The Galleria also doubles as a historical museum by displaying numerous artifacts from the old Canada Post building.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.pcl.com/Projects-that-Inspire/Pages/Air-Canada-Centre.aspx|title=Air Canada Centre|work=PCL Constructors|access-date=November 15, 2018|language=en-us}}</ref>\n[[File:PATH Escalators Construction Scotiabank Arena.jpg|thumb|left|Escalators for a new [[PATH (Toronto)|PATH]] system connection to the under-construction [[CIBC Square]] office complex being installed in the arena's lobby in 2019]]In its first ten years of operation, the new arena had an estimated economic benefit of $2.4&nbsp;billion. This boosted Toronto's economy and led to further construction in the downtown core. Many projects in the area were completed ahead of schedule as a result of a desire to increase the infrastructure of downtown Toronto, and also from private funding (approximately $13&nbsp;million) that was invested in seeing the economic growth of Toronto. These projects included the Bay West Teamway, Union Plaza, the Galleria (shopping centre), and Bremner Boulevard.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n[[Air Canada]] purchased [[naming rights]] to the arena for US$30&nbsp;million for 20 years.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/background/marketing/|work=CBC News|title=Branding for dollars|date=February 15, 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, MLSE completed a $5-million upgrade of the arena, including a new LED signage system.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mapleleafs.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=459588|title=Air Canada Centre Renovations to Improve Ultimate Fan Experience|date=September 9, 2003|accessdate=January 6, 2014|publisher=[[Toronto Maple Leafs]]}}</ref>  During the summer of 2015, a $10-million upgrade of the arena was carried out, which included the installation of a new scoreboard four times larger than the previous one. The old scoreboard was later installed at [[Coca-Cola Coliseum|Ricoh Coliseum]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/leafs/2015/07/24/acc-to-debut-new-scoreboard-this-year.html|title=Air Canada Centre to debut new scoreboard this year|first=Raju|last=Mudhar|date=July 24, 2015|accessdate=July 24, 2015|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref>\n\nIn the winter of 2003\u20132004, the [[Alcohol and Gaming Commission of Ontario]] imposed a seven-day penalty on the arena for \"permitting drunken patrons to be in the licensed patrons{{sic}}\" in the fall of 2002 at a Toronto Maple Leafs game and also a [[The Rolling Stones|Rolling Stones]] concert. As a result of these misdemeanours, there was no alcohol served at the arena from December 21 to 28 in 2003. The venue had multiple major events during this time frame, which included a Toronto Raptors\u2013[[Orlando Magic]] game on December 21, a Toronto Maple Leafs\u2013[[Florida Panthers]] game on December 23, and [[Disney on Ice]]: [[Toy Story 2]], which ran from December 25, 2003 to January 1, 2004.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/sports/air-canada-centre-loses-liquor-licence-for-a-week-1.401537|title=Air Canada Centre loses liquor licence for a week {{!}} CBC Sports|work=CBC|access-date=November 15, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n[[File:DSC08942 - Legends Row (37049346192).jpg|thumb|In September 2014, a group of life-sized statues were installed at the southwest corner of the arena.]]\nOn September 6, 2014, a group of statues known as ''Legends Row'' was unveiled outside the arena at the southwest corner of the building.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/leafs/2014/09/06/maple_leaf_legends_row_unveils_first_three_honourees.html|title=Maple Leafs Legends Row starts with Ted Kennedy, Darryl Sittler, Johnny Bower|publisher=Torstar Corporation|accessdate=September 27, 2018|work=Toronto Star|date=September 7, 2014|last=Rubin|first=Josh}}</ref> The statues were situated in multiple waves from 2014 to 2016 and include [[Ted Kennedy (ice hockey)|Ted Kennedy]], [[Johnny Bower]], [[Darryl Sittler]], [[B\u00f6rje Salming|Borje Salming]], [[Syl Apps]], [[George Armstrong (ice hockey)|George Armstrong]], [[Mats Sundin]], [[Dave Keon]], [[Turk Broda]], and [[Tim Horton]]. In 2017, the final four statues were unveiled including [[Red Kelly]], [[Frank Mahovlich]], [[Charlie Conacher]], and [[Wendel Clark]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nhl.com/news/maple-leafs-legends-row-adds-conacher-kelly-mahovlich-and-clark/c-286915412|title=Maple Leafs Legends Row 'is full' with four added|website=NHL.com|language=en-US|access-date=November 15, 2018}}</ref> ''Legends Row'' now features 14 life-sized statues of former Maple Leaf players alongside a {{convert|9|m|ft|adj=mid|-long|round=5}} granite players' bench.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://torontosun.com/2017/10/05/4-more-leafs-added-to-legends-row/wcm/53247716-67d7-445e-9f20-a91a51890592|title=Four more Maple Leafs added to Legends Row|work=Toronto Sun|publisher=Postmedia Network Inc.|date=October 5, 2017|last=Hornby|first=Lance|accessdate=September 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Air Canada Centre was renamed Scotiabank Arena on July 1, 2018. The landmark 20-year sponsorship agreement between Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment and [[Scotiabank]] is worth about C$800&nbsp;million. This is believed to be the highest-priced annual building and team sponsorship in North American sports history.<ref name=\"MLSEScotiaBankArena\">{{cite news|title=HOME OF THE MAPLE LEAFS AND RAPTORS TO BECOME SCOTIABANK ARENA NEXT SUMMER|url=http://mlse.com/news/scotiabankarena/|publisher=[[Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment]]|date=August 29, 2017|accessdate=May 10, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"WestheadTSN\">{{cite news|last=Westhead|first=Rick|title=MLSE agrees to record arena rights deal with Scotiabank|url=https://www.tsn.ca/talent/mlse-agrees-to-record-arena-rights-deal-with-scotiabank-1.842133|website=[[The Sports Network|TSN]]|date=August 29, 2017|accessdate=May 10, 2018}}</ref> The arena is the third in Canada to bear naming rights to Scotiabank.\n\n==Maple Leaf Square==\n[[File:First period play gets a little rowdy.jpg|thumb|A popular gathering point during [[Toronto Maple Leafs|Maple Leafs]] and [[Toronto Raptors|Raptors]] playoff runs, the arena has a large video screen that overlooks the atrium of Maple Leaf Square.]]\n{{main|Maple Leaf Square}}\nIn late 2005, Maple Leaf Sports and Entertainment announced that they would be renovating the western side of the Air Canada Centre during the 2008 off-season to connect it with the [[Maple Leaf Square]] development. Maple Leaf Square is jointly owned by MLSE, [[Cadillac Fairview]] and Lantera Developments. The $500&nbsp;million development includes two restaurants, Hotel Le Germain at Maple Leaf Square boutique hotel, extensive retail shopping, including a {{convert|840|m2|sqft|adj=on}} Leafs, [[Toronto Marlies|Marlies]], Raptors, and [[Toronto FC]] store, two 54-storey condominiums, a [[Longo's]] supermarket, and a public square. It opened in 2010. The two-year, $48&nbsp;million renovation of the ACC added a new atrium that includes a High-Definition broadcast studio for [[Leafs Nation Network]] (formerly Leafs TV), [[NBA TV Canada]] and [[GolTV (Canadian TV channel)|GolTV Canada]].\n\nThe outside wall of the atrium features a {{convert|9.1|by|15.2|m|ft|adj=on}} video screen overlooking the plaza, which often broadcasts games taking place inside the arena. During [[Stanley Cup playoffs|NHL]] and [[NBA playoffs|NBA playoff]] runs, the square attracts thousands of Leafs and Raptors fans, respectively, sometimes broadcasting away playoff matches featuring the Leafs and/or the Raptors as well.<ref>{{cite web|title=Air Canada Centre Re-Opens Bigger And Better After Summer Hiatus|url=http://www.nba.com/raptors/news/accexpansion_presser_091109.html|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|website=NBA.com/Raptors|date=September 11, 2009|accessdate=January 6, 2014}}</ref> A section of the square is designated Ford Fan Zone at Maple Leaf Square, with naming rights given to the [[Ford Motor Company of Canada]]. During Raptors playoff runs, the square has acquired the nickname \"[[Jurassic Park (film)|Jurassic Park]]\" after the 1993 film adaptation that inspired the team's name. During the [[2019 NBA Playoffs]] and especially during the [[2019 NBA Finals]], other city squares across Canada also acquired the Jurassic Park nickname, such as in [[Halifax, Nova Scotia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/raptors-jurassic-park-spin-offs-ontario-1.5159009|publisher=CBC|title=Jurassic Park spin-offs popping up as Raptors fever sweeps Canada|author=Lucas Powers}}</ref>\n\n==Events==\n===Concerts===\n{{main|List of entertainment events at Scotiabank Arena}}\n\n===Political conventions===\nIn 2003, the governing [[Liberal Party of Canada]] held their [[2003 Liberal Party of Canada leadership election|leadership convention]] at the Air Canada Centre. [[Paul Martin]] was elected as the new leader of the party and thus also became [[Prime Minister of Canada|prime minister]], succeeding [[Jean Chr\u00e9tien]].\n\n===Sports===\n<!--Please don't add WWE events per consensus-->\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | direction = horizontal\n | image1 = Raptors vs Bucks 2.jpg\n | width1 = 165\n | image2 = Buffalo Bandits at Toronto Rock.jpg\n | width2 = 155\n | image3 = Toronto AirCanadaCenter 01.jpg\n | width3 = 165\n |footer= Scotiabank Arena is a [[Multi-purpose stadium|multi-purpose arena]] that is able to host a number of sporting events, including basketball, box lacrosse, and ice hockey.\n}}\nThe first Maple Leafs home game took place on February 20, 1999, versus the Montreal Canadiens, won by the Leafs 3\u20132 on an [[overtime (ice hockey)|overtime]] goal by [[Steve Thomas (ice hockey)|Steve Thomas]]. Maple Leaf home games are generally sold out,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Williams|first1=Cheryl|title=Toronto Maple Leafs|url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/toronto-maple-leafs/#h3_jump_10|website=The Canadian Encyclopedia|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref> and there is a waitlist since the start of 2015 for Season Ticket Holders for upcoming seasons.<ref>{{cite web|title=Purchase Season Seats|url=http://mapleleafs.nhl.com/club/page.htm?id=73129|website=Toronto Maple Leafs|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref> The first Raptors game took place the following night versus the then-[[Memphis Grizzlies|Vancouver Grizzlies]]. The Raptors won 102\u201387 in front of a sell-out crowd. The facility hosted the [[2000 National Hockey League All-Star Game|2000 NHL All-Star Game]], the championship game of the [[2004 World Cup of Hockey]], all games of the [[2016 World Cup of Hockey]] and the [[2016 NBA All-Star Game]], the first NBA All-Star Game held outside of the United States.\n\nThe Toronto Rock also moved to the Air Canada Centre from Maple Leaf Gardens for the [[2001 NLL season]]. The Rock's first game was a 17\u20137 win over the [[Ottawa Rebel]] on December 21, 2000.\n\nOn October 3, 2003, Air Canada Centre had a power outage during the third quarter of a Raptors pre-season game against the Athens-based club [[Panathinaikos B.C.|Panathinaikos]]. The game was called final, because the power was not restored in time and the Raptors already had a [[Mercy rule|30-point lead]].\n\nAir Canada Centre hosted the [[2015 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships]] for the first time, as well as hosted the final match of that tournament, in which Canada was crowned champion, defeating Russia. The ACC co-hosted that tournament with [[Bell Centre]] in Montreal, and both venues co-hosted the [[2017 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|2017 edition of the same event]], though the ACC did not host the medal rounds.\n[[File:Laura Wright performs during the Invictus Flag Raising (37021670620).jpg|thumb|Flag raising during the [[2017 Invictus Games]] closing ceremonies]]\nIn 2017, the Air Canada Centre hosted the opening and closing ceremonies for [[2017 Invictus Games|that year's Invictus Games]].<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.invictusgames2017.com/ceremonies/|title=Ceremonies|publisher=Invictus Games Toronto 2017|year=2016|accessdate=August 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn September 23, 2017, the ACC presented the opening ceremony as a live two-hour event spectacular. This ceremony was designed to welcome and honour the 550 competitors and their families who come from 17 different competing nations. The show featured hundreds of cast members, including honorary men and women from the [[Canadian Armed Forces]]. The cast showed a display of ceremony in multiple different productions and the raising of the flag. Other guests of the event included celebrities, world dignitaries, headline music stars and other special guests. They gathered to celebrate the service and stories of the members of the 2017 Invictus Games. Headline performers included [[Laura Wright (singer)|Laura Wright]], [[Alessia Cara]], [[The Tenors]], [[Sarah McLachlan]], and [[La Bottine Souriante]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe ACC hosted the Invictus Games Toronto 2017 Closing Ceremony on September 20, 2017. The event featured an arrangement of international headline music artists, coming together to celebrate and recognize the Invictus Games competitors. The closing ceremony featured headline musical guests [[Bachman & Turner]], [[Bryan Adams]], [[C\u0153ur de pirate|Coeur de Pirate]], [[Bruce Springsteen]], and [[Kelly Clarkson]]. This celebration also included words from world dignitaries as the Games are passed to the host nation of the [[2018 Invictus Games|Invictus Games 2018]], [[Sydney]], [[Australia]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe venue hosted its first championship series when the Raptors played the [[Golden State Warriors]] in Games 1, 2, and 5 of the [[2019 NBA Finals]]. The Raptors won the NBA championship, albeit in the Warriors' home arena of [[Oracle Arena]] in [[Oakland]] in Game 6.\n\nThe arena has also played host to five [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]] (UFC) events.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmajunkie.com/news/2013/05/ufc-165-heads-to-air-canada-centre-in-toronto-on-sept-21|title=UFC 165 heads to Air Canada Centre in Toronto on Sept. 21|publisher=mmajunkie.com|author=Staff|date=May 14, 2013|accessdate=May 14, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"UFC206\">{{cite news|url=http://www.mmafighting.com/2016/8/19/12562718/ufc-releases-schedule-for-rest-of-2016-including-ufc-206-in-toronto|title=UFC releases schedule for rest of 2016 including UFC 206 in Toronto|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Marc Raimondi|date=August 19, 2016|accessdate=August 19, 2016}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Event\n! Date\n|-\n| [[UFC 140]]\n| Saturday, December 10, 2011\n|-\n| [[UFC 152]]\n| Saturday, September 22, 2012\n|-\n| [[UFC 165]]\n| Saturday, September 21, 2013\n|-\n| [[UFC 206]]\n|Saturday, December 10, 2016\n|-\n| [[UFC 231]]\n|Saturday, December 8, 2018\n|}\n<!--Please don't add WWE events per consensus-->\n\n===Video game competitions===\nOn August 27 and 28, 2016, Air Canada Centre hosted the [[2016 Summer North American League of Legends Championship Series|sixth season of the Summer North American Championship Series]] of ''[[League of Legends]]'' (LoL), marking the first [[League of Legends Championship Series|professional ''League of Legends'' competition]] in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lolesports.com/en_US/articles/na-summer-finals-coming-toronto|title=LoL Esports|website=www.lolesports.com}}</ref> ''League of Legends'' is a popular [[multiplayer online battle arena]] (MOBA) [[PC game|computer game]] by American video game developer [[Riot Games]]; ''League of Legends'' competitions are among the most viewed among professional video game competitions worldwide. During the final round, [[Team SoloMid]] (TSM) defeated [[Cloud9]] (C9) three matches to one in a best-of-five format. The Summer North American Championship Series serve as the qualifiers for the annual [[League of Legends World Championship]] for North American teams.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n==External links==\n<!-- Per [[WP:ELMINOFFICIAL]], choose one official website only -->\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.scotiabankarena.com/}}\n* [http://torontoplaques.com/Pages/Toronto_Postal_Delivery_Building.html Toronto's Historical Plaques; Toronto Postal Delivery Building]\n{{Portal bar|Sports|Ice hockey|Canada|Ontario}}\n{{Navboxes\n|list1=\n&nbsp;\n{{S-start-collapsible|header={{S-sta|et}}}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = Home of the<br />[[Toronto Raptors]]\n | years = 1999\u2013present\n | before = [[Rogers Centre|SkyDome]]\n | after = current\n}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = Home of the<br />[[Toronto Maple Leafs]]\n | years = 1999\u2013present\n | before = [[Maple Leaf Gardens]]\n | after = current\n}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = Home of the<br />[[Toronto Rock]]\n | years = 2000\u2013present\n | before = [[Maple Leaf Gardens]]\n | after = current\n}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = Home of the<br />[[Toronto Phantoms]]\n | years = 2001\u20132002\n | before = [[XL Center|Hartford Civic Center]]\n | after = last arena\n}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = Host of the<br />[[National Hockey League All-Star Game|NHL All-Star Game]]\n | years = 2000\n | before = [[Amalie Arena|St. Pete Times Forum]]\n | after = [[Pepsi Center]]\n}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = Host of the<br />[[NBA All-Star Game]]\n | years = 2016\n | before = [[Madison Square Garden]]\n | after = [[Smoothie King Center]]\n}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = Host of<br />[[Unforgiven (2006)|Unforgiven]]\n | years = 2006\n | before = [[Chesapeake Energy Arena|Ford Center]]\n | after = [[FedExForum]]\n}}\n{{End}}\n{{Toronto landmarks}}\n{{Sport venues in Toronto}}\n{{NHL Arenas}}\n{{NBA Arenas}}\n{{NLL Arenas}}\n{{Toronto Maple Leafs}}\n{{Toronto Raptors}}\n{{Toronto Phantoms}}\n{{Maple Leaf Sports and Entertainment}}\n{{Canada Cup World Cup of Hockey Finals venues}}\n}}<!-- end of infoboxes -->\n\n[[Category:Indoor ice hockey venues in Canada]]\n[[Category:Indoor lacrosse venues in Canada]]\n[[Category:Basketball venues in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Music venues in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Music venues completed in 1999]]\n[[Category:Sports venues completed in 1999]]\n[[Category:Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment]]\n[[Category:Toronto Maple Leafs]]\n[[Category:Toronto Raptors venues]]\n[[Category:Sports venues in Toronto]]\n[[Category:National Hockey League venues]]\n[[Category:National Basketball Association venues]]\n[[Category:PATH (Toronto)]]\n[[Category:Ice hockey venues in Toronto]]\n[[Category:City of Toronto Heritage Properties]]\n[[Category:1999 establishments in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Scotiabank]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the indoor sporting arena in Toronto|the arena in Calgary|Scotiabank Saddledome|the arena in Halifax, Nova Scotia|Scotiabank Centre|the arena in Ottawa formerly known as Scotiabank Place|Canadian Tire Centre}}\n{{Redirect|Air Canada Centre|the headquarters of Air Canada in Montreal|Air Canada#Headquarters}}\n{{short description|Indoor arena in Toronto, Ontario, Canada}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=January 2015}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox venue\n| stadium_name = Scotiabank Arena\n| nickname = The Hanger<br  />The ACC\n| logo_image = [[File:Scotiabank Arena logo.svg|250px]]\n| image = [[File:Scotiabank Arena - 2018 (cropped).jpg|250px]]\n| caption = Exterior view of the arena in 2018\n| address = 40 [[Bay Street]]\n| location = [[Toronto|Toronto, Ontario]]\n| coordinates = {{Coord|43|38|36|N|79|22|45|W|type:landmark_scale:2000|display=it}}\n| pushpin_map = Canada Toronto#Canada Ontario#Canada\n| pushpin_relief = yes\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location in Toronto##Location in Ontario##Location in Canada\n| publictransit = {{rint|toronto|rail}} [[Union Station (Toronto)|Union Station]]<br />{{rint|toronto|subway|1}} [[Union station (TTC)|Union subway station]]<br />{{rint|gotransit|bus}} [[Union Station Bus Terminal|GO Bus Terminal]]\n| broke_ground = March 12, 1997\n| opened = February 19, 1999\n| Acreage = {{convert|61780.5|m2|sqft|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4306707/air-canada-centre-gets-new-name/|title=Air Canada Centre sign removed on eve of facility becoming Scotiabank Arena|work=Global News|accessdate=September 27, 2018|publisher=Corus Entertainment Inc.|date=June 30, 2018}}</ref>\n| owner = [[Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment]]\n| operator = \n| former_names = Air Canada Centre<!-- This article uses Canadian English. \"Centre\" is the correct spelling in this case. --> {{small|(1999\u20132018)}}\n| construction_cost = {{CAD|265&nbsp;million}}<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.theaircanadacentre.com/corporate/CompanyFacts.asp|title=Company Facts|accessdate=August 29, 2017|publisher=Air Canada Centre}}</ref><ref name=cost/><br />(${{formatprice|{{Inflation|CA|265000000|1999}}}} in {{Inflation-year|CA}} dollars{{inflation-fn|CA}})\n| architect = Brisbin Brook Beynon Architects (Architect of Record)<br />[[Populous (company)|HOK Sport]]<br />(Consulting Architects)<ref>{{cite web |title=Clubhouse Confidential: When a Bunch of Alpha Males Get Together Daily in a Confined Space, Lots of Things\u2014Good and Bad\u2014Can Happen|first=Michael|last=Faber|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1024724/3/index.htm|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|date=January 14, 2002|accessdate=January 16, 2013}}</ref>\n| project_manager = Clarendon Projects Ltd.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clarendonprojects.com/aircanadacentre.html|title=Clarendon Projects \u2013 Air Canada Centre|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402151414/http://www.clarendonprojects.com/aircanadacentre.html|archivedate=April 2, 2012}}</ref>\n| structural engineer = [[Halcrow Group|Yolles Partnership Inc.]]<ref>[http://www.halcrow.com/Our-projects/Project-details/Air-Canada-Centre-Canada/ Halcrow Yolles \u2013 Air Canada Centre] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111026034118/http://halcrow.com/Our-projects/Project-details/Air-Canada-Centre-Canada/ |date=October 26, 2011 }}</ref>\n| services engineer = The Mitchell Partnership, Inc.<ref>[http://www.tmptoronto.com/document_library/Air%20Canada%20Centre.pdf The Mitchell Partnership \u2013 Air Canada Centre] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140517115741/http://www.tmptoronto.com/document_library/Air%20Canada%20Centre.pdf |date=May 17, 2014 }}</ref>\n| general_contractor = [[PCL Construction|PCL Constructors Western, Inc.]]\n| tenants = [[Toronto Maple Leafs]] ([[National Hockey League|NHL]]) (1999\u2013present)<br />[[Toronto Raptors]] ([[National Basketball Association|NBA]]) (1999\u2013present)<br />[[Toronto Rock]] ([[National Lacrosse League|NLL]]) (2001\u2013present)<br />[[Toronto Phantoms]] ([[Arena Football League|AFL]]) (2001\u20132002)<br />[[Toronto Marlies]] ([[American Hockey League|AHL]]) (2010\u2013present, occasional home games)\n| seating_capacity = [[Basketball]]: 19,800 (20,511 with standing room)<br />[[Ice hockey|Hockey]]: 18,800 (20,270 with standing room)<br />[[Lacrosse]]: 18,800<br />[[Concert]]s: 19,800<br />[[Theatre]]: 5,200<ref>{{cite web|title=About|url=https://www.aircanadacentre.com/venue-information/about|publisher=Air Canada Centre|accessdate=May 10, 2018}}</ref>\n| parking = 2 underground levels\n| website = [https://www.scotiabankarena.com/ scotiabankarena.com]\n}}\n\n'''Scotiabank Arena''', formerly '''Air Canada Centre<!-- This article uses Canadian English. \"Centre\" is the correct spelling in this case. -->''', is a multi-purpose [[arena]] located on [[Bay Street]] in the [[South Core, Toronto|South Core]] district of [[Downtown Toronto|Downtown]] [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada. It is the home of the [[Toronto Maple Leafs]] of the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL), the [[Toronto Raptors]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) and the [[Toronto Rock]] of the [[National Lacrosse League]] (NLL). In addition, the minor league [[Toronto Marlies]] of the [[American Hockey League]] (AHL) and the [[Raptors 905]] of the [[NBA G League]] play occasional games at the arena. The arena was previously home to the [[Toronto Phantoms]] of the [[Arena Football League]] (AFL) during their brief existence.\n\nThe arena  is {{convert|61780.5|m2|sqft}} in size. It is owned and operated by [[Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment|Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment Ltd.]] (MLSE), the same group that owns the Leafs and the Raptors, as well as their respective development teams. In 2018, Scotiabank Arena was the 13th busiest arena in the world and the busiest in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pollstar.com/Chart/2019/01/2018YearEndWorldwideTicketSalesTop200ArenaVenues_705.pdf|title=2018 YEAR END Worldwide Ticket Sales TOP 200 ARENA VENUES|publisher=[[Pollstar]]|date=2018|accessdate=June 22, 2019}}</ref> It is also the most photographed location in Canada on [[Instagram]] according to [[BuzzFeed]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/leafs/2018/07/01/scotiabank-arena-now-officially-the-home-of-maple-leafs-and-raptors.html|title=Scotiabank Arena now officially the home of Maple Leafs and Raptors - The Star|publisher=Toronto Star}}</ref> Scotiabank Arena is connected to [[Union Station (Toronto)|Toronto Union]] railway station, [[Union station (TTC)|subway station]] and [[Union Station Bus Terminal|bus terminal]] via the [[PATH (Toronto)|PATH]].\n\nScotiabank Arena has, from its initial design to completion, revolutionized many concepts included in new arenas and stadiums built since then.{{according to whom|date=October 2019}} These features include luxury suites accessible on the ground floor, splitting the main scoreboard into several sections, rotating all sponsor signage in the bowl at once (to allow dominant messaging or \"neutralization\" for events that disallow commercial advertising), and multiple restaurants in and out of the main arena bowl view.\n\nScotiabank Arena also hosts other events, such as concerts, political conventions and [[Esports|video game competitions]].\n\n==History==\n===Before opening===\nThe arena site was once occupied by [[Canada Post]]'s Toronto Postal Delivery Building (designed by [[Charles B. Dolphin]]). The Canada Post building was built in 1938, to assist in the recent population growth of Toronto and its surrounding area.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.scotiabankarena.com/venue-information/about/history|title=History {{!}} Scotiabank Arena|last=Arena|first=Scotiabank|website=www.scotiabankarena.com|language=en|access-date=November 15, 2018}}</ref> The building was handed over to Department of National Defence for war storage purposes upon completion in 1941, but returned to Canada Post in 1946. Modifications were made to the building to be more adequately equipped for postal delivery, after it was altered by the Department of National Defence. After the work was completed in 1948, the building now possessed the capability and equipment for proper mail sorting and other mailing functions. The building was strategically located south of Union Station and was connected directly to the train platforms via an underground tunnel. Trains would be able to directly unload mail and move it directly to the mail sorting centre.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://tayloronhistory.com/2013/02/12/torontos-architectural-gemsthe-postal-delivery-building-now-the-acc/|title=History|language=en|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>  \n\n====1990s Transition to Stadium====\nIn the early 1990s, the building needed major renovations. To cut costs, Canada Post decided to close the facility and move operations to an alternate letter processing plant, which had been constructed in the 1970s on Eastern Avenue.  Eventually, all of the old building's work was transferred here.<ref name=\":0\" /> In the early 1990s, real estate developers [[Bramalea (company)|Bramalea Ltd]] and [[Trizec Properties|Trizec]] arranged to purchase the building from Canada Post, and redevelop the site into a {{convert|230,000|m2|sqft|adj=on}} office, retail and residential space. Financial and development details of the purchase imposed various conditions prior to development, including rezoning by the city, remediation of soil contamination by Canada Post.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bramalea's Moves Shake Taxpayers|first=Stevie|last=Cameron|date=November 15, 1992|publisher=[[The Globe and Mail]]}}</ref>\n\nDue to financial difficulties, the building's ownership was returned to Canada Post in 1993. The Toronto Raptors purchased the building from Canada Post the next year.<ref name=\"rapnba\">{{cite web| url=http://www.nba.com/raptors/history/raptors_history.html/| title=Laying the Groundwork for the NBA in Toronto| website=nba.com| accessdate=October 14, 2017}}</ref>\n[[File:Postal terminal now Air Canada Centre.jpg|thumb|left|The arena retains the eastern wall of the original postal structure built in 1941, through a process of [[facadism]].]]\nConstruction of the arena was started by the Toronto Raptors, under their initial ownership group headed by Canadian businessman [[John Bitove]]. In 1995, it had been decided that the NBA would expand into Canada. The Toronto Raptors were created and would need an indoor arena to play in. The Canada Post building was chosen to be the new home of the Raptors due to its downtown location and lot size. Other venues such as [[Exhibition Place]], North York Centre, Bay and Wellesley, and Bay and Dundas were also considered. The Canada Post building was purchased for {{CAD|60}} million.<ref name=\":0\" /> The Raptors initially played in SkyDome (now [[Rogers Centre]]) while the arena was constructed.<ref name=\"blogTo\">{{cite web|first=Chris|last=Bateman|title=That time the Raptors and the Maple Leafs moved to the ACC|url=http://www.blogto.com/city/2014/02/that_time_the_raptors_and_leafs_moved_to_the_acc/|website=blogTo|date=February 22, 2014|accessdate=December 4, 2017}}</ref> Groundbreaking took place in March 1997. The building retained the [[Art Deco]] facade of the Toronto Postal Delivery Building along the east (along [[Bay Street]]) and south ([[Lake Shore Boulevard]]) walls of that structure, but the rest of the building (facing [[Union Station (Toronto)|Union Station]]) was removed to make room for the arena, through the process of [[facadism]]. The original building is protected under the ''[[Ontario Heritage Act]]''.\n\n===Arena 'Wars'===\nWhen MLGL ([[Maple Leaf Sports and Entertainment|Maple Leaf Gardens, Limited]] at the time the controlling company of the Toronto Maple Leafs) lost out on their desire to be the franchise owners of the Raptors, competition between the two organizations heated up centred around venues. MLGL declined to allow Maple Leaf Gardens to be used for the NBA upstart as a result pushing Bitove to secure rights to have the Raptors' opening seasons played at SkyDome until construction of the new stadium to be complete.\n\nThe 1930s-era Maple Leaf Gardens was showing its age; the Maple Leafs in desperate desire for a new facility began developing plans for building an all-new stadium with one of the key criteria for the new location that it must be within close walking proximity to both the subway system and GO Transit. During the early stages of construction, MLGL floated to the media plans for their own plans to build a competing single-use stadium on adjacent property just to the north of the stadium atop the train sheds at Union Station (similar to how [[Madison Square Garden]] was constructed) as the new home for the Toronto Maple Leafs.<ref name=ArenaWars>{{cite news|title=Leafs ready to Move (Page 2)|first=Craig|last=Daniels|date=April 16, 1997|publisher=[[The Toronto Sun]]}}</ref> The reaction from Raptors was nothing but anger. \"This proposed (Maple Leaf) location really disturbs us\" stated team president Richard Peddie, who went on to say that they would fight the Leafs \"every step of the way\" and he didn't understand why the Leafs have refused to join with the Raptors at their site; claiming that the Leafs want to \"build virtually on top of us\".<ref name=\"ArenaWars\" /> The major problem of the Union Station proposal is the land that the stadium would be built on was actually City of Toronto land that was leased out to CN Rail and CP Rail, which were in a major, long-standing dispute over rent payments (dating back to 1969). As a result, MLGL offered the city $156 Million (1997 CAD) in cash & assets to settle any and all outstanding claims and to buy the air rights above the Union Station train platforms.\n\nDuring this period John Bitove who disputed over the future of the arena who as a result of a [[shotgun clause]] was forced to sell his stake to Allan Slaight (who wanted a joint arena deal with MLGL) and now with majority ownership immediately went into talks with MLGL which eventually purchased both the Raptors and their partially completed arena, which subsequently resulted in major modifications to the original design, which was basketball-specific, to make the arena become more suitable for hockey. Originally planned to cost $217&nbsp;million, MLGL increased the budget to $265&nbsp;million after taking control.<ref name=cost>{{cite news|title=Upgrades added to cost|first=David|last=Shoalts|date=February 17, 1999|publisher=[[The Globe and Mail]]}}</ref> The Raptors were twice fined a million dollars (which were donated to their charitable foundation) by the NBA for missing deadlines to begin construction of their new arena.<ref>{{cite news|title=Raptors' arena bites dust|last=Christe|first=James|date=May 16, 1997|publisher=[[The Globe and Mail]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998, a strange twist of scheduling conflicts had the Toronto Raptors playing their final regular-season game at [[Copps Coliseum]] in Hamilton, as the Toronto Blue Jays had first right of refusal for all SkyDome dates.  The Raptors had attempted to play the April 19 match at Maple Leaf Gardens, but were unsuccessful.<ref>{{cite news|title=Raptors Move Final Game to Hamilton|date=January 7, 1998|publisher=[[Associated Press]]|url=https://www.apnews.com/7027ff09054e45b3b7471205f12cb521}}</ref>\n\n===Since opening===\n[[File:Air Canada Centre in 1999.jpg|thumb|left|Air Canada Centre in July 1999, five months after the arena opened]]\nIn December 1998, the building's construction was completed. Opening events took place early the next year and [[Steve Stavro]] (who was the majority shareholder of MLGL) was named CEO. The initial hockey game took place February 20, 1999 (Toronto Maple Leafs vs. [[Montreal Canadiens]]), the first basketball Game on February 21, 1999 (Toronto Raptors vs. [[Vancouver Grizzlies]]), and the opening concert on February 22, 1999 ([[The Tragically Hip]]).<ref name=\":0\" /> Features of the new building consist of a {{convert|65000|sqft|adj=on}} arena and a {{convert|165000|sqft|adj=on}} office tower. There is also an east\u2013west covered, climate controlled galleria and walkway onsite that contains restaurants, the ticket office, and other commercial units. The Galleria also connects Scotiabank Arena to popular locations in the downtown core such as Union Station, Bay Street and York Street. Scotiabank Arena is connected to the underground PATH network. The Galleria also doubles as a historical museum by displaying numerous artifacts from the old Canada Post building.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.pcl.com/Projects-that-Inspire/Pages/Air-Canada-Centre.aspx|title=Air Canada Centre|work=PCL Constructors|access-date=November 15, 2018|language=en-us}}</ref>\n[[File:PATH Escalators Construction Scotiabank Arena.jpg|thumb|left|Escalators for a new [[PATH (Toronto)|PATH]] system connection to the under-construction [[CIBC Square]] office complex being installed in the arena's lobby in 2019]]In its first ten years of operation, the new arena had an estimated economic benefit of $2.4&nbsp;billion. This boosted Toronto's economy and led to further construction in the downtown core. Many projects in the area were completed ahead of schedule as a result of a desire to increase the infrastructure of downtown Toronto, and also from private funding (approximately $13&nbsp;million) that was invested in seeing the economic growth of Toronto. These projects included the Bay West Teamway, Union Plaza, the Galleria (shopping centre), and Bremner Boulevard.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n[[Air Canada]] purchased [[naming rights]] to the arena for US$30&nbsp;million for 20 years.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/background/marketing/|work=CBC News|title=Branding for dollars|date=February 15, 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, MLSE completed a $5-million upgrade of the arena, including a new LED signage system.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mapleleafs.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=459588|title=Air Canada Centre Renovations to Improve Ultimate Fan Experience|date=September 9, 2003|accessdate=January 6, 2014|publisher=[[Toronto Maple Leafs]]}}</ref>  During the summer of 2015, a $10-million upgrade of the arena was carried out, which included the installation of a new scoreboard four times larger than the previous one. The old scoreboard was later installed at [[Coca-Cola Coliseum|Ricoh Coliseum]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/leafs/2015/07/24/acc-to-debut-new-scoreboard-this-year.html|title=Air Canada Centre to debut new scoreboard this year|first=Raju|last=Mudhar|date=July 24, 2015|accessdate=July 24, 2015|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref>\n\nIn the winter of 2003\u20132004, the [[Alcohol and Gaming Commission of Ontario]] imposed a seven-day penalty on the arena for \"permitting drunken patrons to be in the licensed patrons{{sic}}\" in the fall of 2002 at a Toronto Maple Leafs game and also a [[The Rolling Stones|Rolling Stones]] concert. As a result of these misdemeanours, there was no alcohol served at the arena from December 21 to 28 in 2003. The venue had multiple major events during this time frame, which included a Toronto Raptors\u2013[[Orlando Magic]] game on December 21, a Toronto Maple Leafs\u2013[[Florida Panthers]] game on December 23, and [[Disney on Ice]]: [[Toy Story 2]], which ran from December 25, 2003 to January 1, 2004.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/sports/air-canada-centre-loses-liquor-licence-for-a-week-1.401537|title=Air Canada Centre loses liquor licence for a week {{!}} CBC Sports|work=CBC|access-date=November 15, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n[[File:DSC08942 - Legends Row (37049346192).jpg|thumb|In September 2014, a group of life-sized statues were installed at the southwest corner of the arena.]]\nOn September 6, 2014, a group of statues known as ''Legends Row'' was unveiled outside the arena at the southwest corner of the building.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/leafs/2014/09/06/maple_leaf_legends_row_unveils_first_three_honourees.html|title=Maple Leafs Legends Row starts with Ted Kennedy, Darryl Sittler, Johnny Bower|publisher=Torstar Corporation|accessdate=September 27, 2018|work=Toronto Star|date=September 7, 2014|last=Rubin|first=Josh}}</ref> The statues were situated in multiple waves from 2014 to 2016 and include [[Ted Kennedy (ice hockey)|Ted Kennedy]], [[Johnny Bower]], [[Darryl Sittler]], [[B\u00f6rje Salming|Borje Salming]], [[Syl Apps]], [[George Armstrong (ice hockey)|George Armstrong]], [[Mats Sundin]], [[Dave Keon]], [[Turk Broda]], and [[Tim Horton]]. In 2017, the final four statues were unveiled including [[Red Kelly]], [[Frank Mahovlich]], [[Charlie Conacher]], and [[Wendel Clark]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nhl.com/news/maple-leafs-legends-row-adds-conacher-kelly-mahovlich-and-clark/c-286915412|title=Maple Leafs Legends Row 'is full' with four added|website=NHL.com|language=en-US|access-date=November 15, 2018}}</ref> ''Legends Row'' now features 14 life-sized statues of former Maple Leaf players alongside a {{convert|9|m|ft|adj=mid|-long|round=5}} granite players' bench.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://torontosun.com/2017/10/05/4-more-leafs-added-to-legends-row/wcm/53247716-67d7-445e-9f20-a91a51890592|title=Four more Maple Leafs added to Legends Row|work=Toronto Sun|publisher=Postmedia Network Inc.|date=October 5, 2017|last=Hornby|first=Lance|accessdate=September 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Air Canada Centre was renamed Scotiabank Arena on July 1, 2018. The landmark 20-year sponsorship agreement between Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment and [[Scotiabank]] is worth about C$800&nbsp;million. This is believed to be the highest-priced annual building and team sponsorship in North American sports history.<ref name=\"MLSEScotiaBankArena\">{{cite news|title=HOME OF THE MAPLE LEAFS AND RAPTORS TO BECOME SCOTIABANK ARENA NEXT SUMMER|url=http://mlse.com/news/scotiabankarena/|publisher=[[Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment]]|date=August 29, 2017|accessdate=May 10, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"WestheadTSN\">{{cite news|last=Westhead|first=Rick|title=MLSE agrees to record arena rights deal with Scotiabank|url=https://www.tsn.ca/talent/mlse-agrees-to-record-arena-rights-deal-with-scotiabank-1.842133|website=[[The Sports Network|TSN]]|date=August 29, 2017|accessdate=May 10, 2018}}</ref> The arena is the third in Canada to bear naming rights to Scotiabank.\n\n==Maple Leaf Square==\n[[File:First period play gets a little rowdy.jpg|thumb|A popular gathering point during [[Toronto Maple Leafs|Maple Leafs]] and [[Toronto Raptors|Raptors]] playoff runs, the arena has a large video screen that overlooks the atrium of Maple Leaf Square.]]\n{{main|Maple Leaf Square}}\nIn late 2005, Maple Leaf Sports and Entertainment announced that they would be renovating the western side of the Air Canada Centre during the 2008 off-season to connect it with the [[Maple Leaf Square]] development. Maple Leaf Square is jointly owned by MLSE, [[Cadillac Fairview]] and Lantera Developments. The $500&nbsp;million development includes two restaurants, Hotel Le Germain at Maple Leaf Square boutique hotel, extensive retail shopping, including a {{convert|840|m2|sqft|adj=on}} Leafs, [[Toronto Marlies|Marlies]], Raptors, and [[Toronto FC]] store, two 54-storey condominiums, a [[Longo's]] supermarket, and a public square. It opened in 2010. The two-year, $48&nbsp;million renovation of the ACC added a new atrium that includes a High-Definition broadcast studio for [[Leafs Nation Network]] (formerly Leafs TV), [[NBA TV Canada]] and [[GolTV (Canadian TV channel)|GolTV Canada]].\n\nThe outside wall of the atrium features a {{convert|9.1|by|15.2|m|ft|adj=on}} video screen overlooking the plaza, which often broadcasts games taking place inside the arena. During [[Stanley Cup playoffs|NHL]] and [[NBA playoffs|NBA playoff]] runs, the square attracts thousands of Leafs and Raptors fans, respectively, sometimes broadcasting away playoff matches featuring the Leafs and/or the Raptors as well.<ref>{{cite web|title=Air Canada Centre Re-Opens Bigger And Better After Summer Hiatus|url=http://www.nba.com/raptors/news/accexpansion_presser_091109.html|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|website=NBA.com/Raptors|date=September 11, 2009|accessdate=January 6, 2014}}</ref> A section of the square is designated Ford Fan Zone at Maple Leaf Square, with naming rights given to the [[Ford Motor Company of Canada]]. During Raptors playoff runs, the square has acquired the nickname \"[[Jurassic Park (film)|Jurassic Park]]\" after the 1993 film adaptation that inspired the team's name. During the [[2019 NBA Playoffs]] and especially during the [[2019 NBA Finals]], other city squares across Canada also acquired the Jurassic Park nickname, such as in [[Halifax, Nova Scotia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/raptors-jurassic-park-spin-offs-ontario-1.5159009|publisher=CBC|title=Jurassic Park spin-offs popping up as Raptors fever sweeps Canada|author=Lucas Powers}}</ref>\n\n==Events==\n===Concerts===\n{{main|List of entertainment events at Scotiabank Arena}}\n\n===Political conventions===\nIn 2003, the governing [[Liberal Party of Canada]] held their [[2003 Liberal Party of Canada leadership election|leadership convention]] at the Air Canada Centre. [[Paul Martin]] was elected as the new leader of the party and thus also became [[Prime Minister of Canada|prime minister]], succeeding [[Jean Chr\u00e9tien]].\n\n===Sports===\n<!--Please don't add WWE events per consensus-->\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | direction = horizontal\n | image1 = Raptors vs Bucks 2.jpg\n | width1 = 165\n | image2 = Buffalo Bandits at Toronto Rock.jpg\n | width2 = 155\n | image3 = Toronto AirCanadaCenter 01.jpg\n | width3 = 165\n |footer= Scotiabank Arena is a [[Multi-purpose stadium|multi-purpose arena]] that is able to host a number of sporting events, including basketball, box lacrosse, and ice hockey.\n}}\nThe first Maple Leafs home game took place on February 20, 1999, versus the Montreal Canadiens, won by the Leafs 3\u20132 on an [[overtime (ice hockey)|overtime]] goal by [[Steve Thomas (ice hockey)|Steve Thomas]]. Maple Leaf home games are generally sold out,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Williams|first1=Cheryl|title=Toronto Maple Leafs|url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/toronto-maple-leafs/#h3_jump_10|website=The Canadian Encyclopedia|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref> and there is a waitlist since the start of 2015 for Season Ticket Holders for upcoming seasons.<ref>{{cite web|title=Purchase Season Seats|url=http://mapleleafs.nhl.com/club/page.htm?id=73129|website=Toronto Maple Leafs|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref> The first Raptors game took place the following night versus the then-[[Memphis Grizzlies|Vancouver Grizzlies]]. The Raptors won 102\u201387 in front of a sell-out crowd. The facility hosted the [[2000 National Hockey League All-Star Game|2000 NHL All-Star Game]], the championship game of the [[2004 World Cup of Hockey]], all games of the [[2016 World Cup of Hockey]] and the [[2016 NBA All-Star Game]], the first NBA All-Star Game held outside of the United States.\n\nThe Toronto Rock also moved to the Air Canada Centre from Maple Leaf Gardens for the [[2001 NLL season]]. The Rock's first game was a 17\u20137 win over the [[Ottawa Rebel]] on December 21, 2000.\n\nOn October 3, 2003, Air Canada Centre had a power outage during the third quarter of a Raptors pre-season game against the Athens-based club [[Panathinaikos B.C.|Panathinaikos]]. The game was called final, because the power was not restored in time and the Raptors already had a [[Mercy rule|30-point lead]].\n\nAir Canada Centre hosted the [[2015 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships]] for the first time, as well as hosted the final match of that tournament, in which Canada was crowned champion, defeating Russia. The ACC co-hosted that tournament with [[Bell Centre]] in Montreal, and both venues co-hosted the [[2017 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|2017 edition of the same event]], though the ACC did not host the medal rounds.\n[[File:Laura Wright performs during the Invictus Flag Raising (37021670620).jpg|thumb|Flag raising during the [[2017 Invictus Games]] closing ceremonies]]\nIn 2017, the Air Canada Centre hosted the opening and closing ceremonies for [[2017 Invictus Games|that year's Invictus Games]].<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.invictusgames2017.com/ceremonies/|title=Ceremonies|publisher=Invictus Games Toronto 2017|year=2016|accessdate=August 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn September 23, 2017, the ACC presented the opening ceremony as a live two-hour event spectacular. This ceremony was designed to welcome and honour the 550 competitors and their families who come from 17 different competing nations. The show featured hundreds of cast members, including honorary men and women from the [[Canadian Armed Forces]]. The cast showed a display of ceremony in multiple different productions and the raising of the flag. Other guests of the event included celebrities, world dignitaries, headline music stars and other special guests. They gathered to celebrate the service and stories of the members of the 2017 Invictus Games. Headline performers included [[Laura Wright (singer)|Laura Wright]], [[Alessia Cara]], [[The Tenors]], [[Sarah McLachlan]], and [[La Bottine Souriante]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe ACC hosted the Invictus Games Toronto 2017 Closing Ceremony on September 20, 2017. The event featured an arrangement of international headline music artists, coming together to celebrate and recognize the Invictus Games competitors. The closing ceremony featured headline musical guests [[Bachman & Turner]], [[Bryan Adams]], [[C\u0153ur de pirate|Coeur de Pirate]], [[Bruce Springsteen]], and [[Kelly Clarkson]]. This celebration also included words from world dignitaries as the Games are passed to the host nation of the [[2018 Invictus Games|Invictus Games 2018]], [[Sydney]], [[Australia]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe venue hosted its first championship series when the Raptors played the [[Golden State Warriors]] in Games 1, 2, and 5 of the [[2019 NBA Finals]]. The Raptors won the NBA championship, albeit in the Warriors' home arena of [[Oracle Arena]] in [[Oakland]] in Game 6.\n\nThe arena has also played host to five [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]] (UFC) events.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmajunkie.com/news/2013/05/ufc-165-heads-to-air-canada-centre-in-toronto-on-sept-21|title=UFC 165 heads to Air Canada Centre in Toronto on Sept. 21|publisher=mmajunkie.com|author=Staff|date=May 14, 2013|accessdate=May 14, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"UFC206\">{{cite news|url=http://www.mmafighting.com/2016/8/19/12562718/ufc-releases-schedule-for-rest-of-2016-including-ufc-206-in-toronto|title=UFC releases schedule for rest of 2016 including UFC 206 in Toronto|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Marc Raimondi|date=August 19, 2016|accessdate=August 19, 2016}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Event\n! Date\n|-\n| [[UFC 140]]\n| Saturday, December 10, 2011\n|-\n| [[UFC 152]]\n| Saturday, September 22, 2012\n|-\n| [[UFC 165]]\n| Saturday, September 21, 2013\n|-\n| [[UFC 206]]\n|Saturday, December 10, 2016\n|-\n| [[UFC 231]]\n|Saturday, December 8, 2018\n|}\n<!--Please don't add WWE events per consensus-->\n\n===Video game competitions===\nOn August 27 and 28, 2016, Air Canada Centre hosted the [[2016 Summer North American League of Legends Championship Series|sixth season of the Summer North American Championship Series]] of ''[[League of Legends]]'' (LoL), marking the first [[League of Legends Championship Series|professional ''League of Legends'' competition]] in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lolesports.com/en_US/articles/na-summer-finals-coming-toronto|title=LoL Esports|website=www.lolesports.com}}</ref> ''League of Legends'' is a popular [[multiplayer online battle arena]] (MOBA) [[PC game|computer game]] by American video game developer [[Riot Games]]; ''League of Legends'' competitions are among the most viewed among professional video game competitions worldwide. During the final round, [[Team SoloMid]] (TSM) defeated [[Cloud9]] (C9) three matches to one in a best-of-five format. The Summer North American Championship Series serve as the qualifiers for the annual [[League of Legends World Championship]] for North American teams.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n==External links==\n<!-- Per [[WP:ELMINOFFICIAL]], choose one official website only -->\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.scotiabankarena.com